<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-FilmInstitute     09-26 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Film Institute,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Attends Gala For American Film Institute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush joined a galaxy of Hollywood
celebrities Tuesday night in paying tribute to the American Film
Institute on the 24th anniversary of the federal arts legislation
that gave it birth.
   Eyeing the black-tie crowd that included actors Charlton Heston,
Douglas Fairbanks Jr., John Travolta and Christopher Reeve and
actresses Marlo Thomas and Brooke Shields, master of ceremonies
Jack Valenti crowed: ``Welcome to Washington, D.C., the
entertainment capital of the world.''
   Valenti, the longtime head of the American Motion Picture
Association and onetime White House aide to Lyndon B. Johnson,
added, ``There are things that happen here that a Hollywood
scriptwriter would give his life to be able to put down.''
   It was Johnson who signed the legislation on Sept. 29, 1965,
creating the National Endowments for the Arts and the Humanities,
which two years later spawned the independent, non-profit American
Film Institute.
   The institute has been a leader in efforts to preserve motion
pictures and television, and trains young directors through a
program in Los Angeles.
   Bush joined in the entertainment at the gala at the National
Building Museum, following a string of celebrities who repeated
famous movie lines. Bush, looking across the ballroom to his wife
Barbara at a table 30 yards away, repeated Humphrey Bogart's toast
from ``Casablanca'':
   ``Here's looking at ya, kid!''
   Bush called film ``the mirror of America ... and also in a sense
the conscience of America.'' He cited such films as ``Coal Miner's
Daughter,'' ``Hoosiers,'' and several recent movies that portrayed
drugs in a bad lights, including ``Lean On Me,'' ``Clean and
Sober'' and ``Dancing As Fast As I Can.''
   ``I want to thank the film industry for helping stop this
terrible threat to our kids. ... I welcome your leadership,'' said
the president.
</TEXT>
