<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0038EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FrogCrossing     09-26 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Frog Crossing,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Has Solution to Frog-Crossing Sign Thefts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STEVENS POINT, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city leaped at a chance to put
its ``Frog Crossing'' signs back up, and the mayor even thinks he's
figured out a way to keep souvenir hunters from slipping away with
them.
   ``I am going to have a T-shirt made of the frog-crossing sign,''
Mayor Scott Schultz said after the signs were re-posted last week.
``Maybe if we get people to buy T-shirts, they won't steal the
sign.''
   The two signs have been missing since shortly after they were
erected in July 1987 on a stretch of road through the Schmeeckle
Reserve. Suspicious minds linked the signs' disappearance with the
return of students that year to the University of Wisconsin-Stevens
Point.
   The signs were posted along two ramps that were cut in the curb
to help frogs and other small animals cross the road.
   A city worker came up with the design, featuring four frogs in
various stages of leaping.
   Recently, one of the original signs was recovered and repaired,
and officials decided to give it another try.
   ``The general reaction is that folks are glad the sign is back
up,'' Schultz said. ``The real purpose was to highlight that there
is a nature preserve.''
   When the first signs disappeared so quickly, official decided it
would be pointless to keep putting them up in a battle with
souvenir-hunters.
   This time, T-shirts aren't the only deterrent to theft, Schultz
said: ``They welded the bolts this time.''
</TEXT>
