<FIRST>r a AM-NBC-Colombia     09-26 0181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NBC-Colombia,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Buys, Airs TV Footage of Mercenaries in Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``NBC Nightly News'' aired videotape pictures
Monday of what it said were British and Australian mercenaries
teaching private soldiers for Colombian drug lords how to kill with
sophisticated weapons and equipment.
   The footage was taken by one of the mercenaries, Australian
Terry Tagley, NBC correspondent Brian Ross reported. He gave no
further details about Tagley's background.
   Ross said 11 highly paid British and Australian mercenaries,
``experts in assassinations and explosives,'' had gone to Colombia.
He quoted Tagley as saying they had been told they were being
brought to Colombia to fight communist guerrillas, but when they
arrived there they realized they actually were working for the drug
cartel.
   NBC News paid Tagley for his videotape, said an NBC spokeswoman,
Katherine McQuay. She declined to say how much.
   NBC on Aug. 21 broadcast video footage of what it said were
Israelis teaching the drug soldiers. Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir has denied that the Israelis, which Israeli newspapers said
were former military officers, did anything wrong.
</TEXT>
