<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0046EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Refugees Bjt   09-26 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Refugees, Bjt,0778</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beirutis Flock Home, Glad But Impoverished After Refugee Ordeal</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A million refugees have flooded back into
Beirut after six months of fighting, many impoverished by their
ordeal and some fearful lest the savage shelling flares up again.
   Long lines of cars began streaming into the shattered capital
within minutes of the announcement Friday by Christian leader Gen.
Michel Aoun that he was accepting an Arab League cease-fire.
   Hundreds more Lebanese booked passage for the three-hour ferry
crossing from Larnaca, Cyprus to the Christian port of Jounieh,
while others flew into the newly reopened Beirut airport.
   The six months of fighting killed at least 929 people and
wounded 2,741.
   Issam Baydoun, a Sunni Moslem bank employee who fled during the
shelling battles that pitted Aoun's mainly Christian fighters
against Syria and its Moslem militia allies, was among the
returnees.
   ``I have spent most of my 30 years' savings during the 2{ months
of forced migration to the south,'' said the 55-year-old father of
two.
   Baydoun said he fled his Beirut home in a seven-story apartment
building in the heavily shelled district of Ras el-Nabeh in July,
when ``things could not be borne anymore.''
   ``My wife had started taking sedatives,'' he said. ``My daughter
screamed every time a shell crashed nearby or because of the sound
of a rocket passing overhead.''
   Just like many other west Beirutis, Baydoun headed south. He
rented a two-room house for $900 a month in Iqlim Kharroub in the
Chouf mountains.
   ``In all, I spent $3,000 in only 75 days of exile,'' he said.
``Believe me, now that we're back I can't afford to restore my
shell-pocked house.''
   Asked whether he would be able to rent another house in the
south if fighting broke out again, Baydoun said:
   ``I am a conscientious employee and have a good reputation at
the bank. The bank manager might be willing to lend me some money
on temporary basis. But to tell you the truth, God knows when I
will be able to pay him back.''
   He was glad to be back, albeit impoverished, saying ``there's no
place like home.''
   The Baydouns' neighborhood is in a section of west Beirut where
Syria and its allies installed their advance artillery batteries.
On the opposite side are Aoun's troops as well as Christian
militants from the Lebanese Forces.
   East Beirut residents also breathed relief when the Arab league
commitee announced the opening of all crossings linking both
sectors of the capital, the lifting of the 6-month-old blockade of
the Christian heartland and the opening of the airport.
   ``May God guide them to the right path,'' said Samira Gobril, a
Maronite Catholic housewife who expressed hope that the leaders of
Lebanon's factions would work together for a durable peace.
   `` May God keep utmost in their minds the plight of the poor
population.''
   Mrs. Gobril, 38, and mother of an 11-year-old boy and an
8-year-old girl, lives in the frequently battered Christian area of
Ashrafieh a few miles from the Green Line that divides east from
west Beirut.
   She had fled to the fashionable mountain resort of Faraya, 20
miles to the northeast.
   ``This time we could afford it,'' she added, but ``it'll take my
husband five years of hard work to recoup the amount of money we
have spent during the last four months.''
   Police said at least 1 million refugees who fled Beirut have
returned since Friday. Beirut took the brunt of the shelling,
forcing all but 150,000 of its remaining 1.5 million people to flee.
   Some of those that did not travel to safer areas of Lebanon took
the ferry to Cyprus, either to wait out the fighting or to apply
for American, Canadian, Australian and other visas as a gateway to
a new life away from their country, shattered by 14 years of civil
war.
   Estimates vary. Immigration officials in Cyprus say about 20,000
Lebanese are on the small east Mediterranean island whose
population numbers just 691,000.
   But relief agency officials working to ease the refugees' plight
said the actual number of Lebanese in Cyprus probably reached
30,000 at the height of the fighting and perhaps more.
   The Christian refugees' only exit to the outside world has been
through a hydrofoil ferry service from the port of Jounieh north of
Beirut to Larnaca on the south Cyprus coast.
   Moslems, too, have been fleeing to Cyprus, though they are still
a minority of the Lebanese refugees on the island.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
