<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo-NorthCarolina 1stLd-Writethru a0689 09-26 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-North Carolina, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0689,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Charlotte Goes Back to Work After Hugo, Many Still Powerless</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to reflect that Hugo was downgraded to tropical
storm when it hit N.C., UPDATE with Bush disaster declaration, additional
water outages, price gouging, power company workers hurt; pick up 8th graf
pvs, `The loss ...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commuters struggled through rush hour with
no traffic lights in Charlotte and power companies rebuilt electric
systems Monday, four days after Hurricane Hugo's remnants struck.
   Also on Monday, President Bush declared four inland North
Carolina counties disaster areas eligible for federal assistance.
   ``The damage has been extensive, and the progress has been
slower than expected,'' said Joe Maher of Duke Power Co. in
Charlotte. He said it would be a week or two before full service is
restored.
   About 280,000 Duke customers in North and South Carolina were
still without electricity, including Bill Lee, the utility's board
chairman.
   ``I feel like I'm in good company,'' Lee said.
   Preliminary damage estimates for hard-hit Mecklenburg County
rose to $336 million, but officials said the damage is so extensive
it is still difficult to gauge.
   Marie Shook, assistant manager of Mecklenburg County, estimated
that 120,000 county residents, mostly in rural areas, remained
without water Monday. County agencies, meanwhile, had 250 reports
of price gouging.
   In Lincoln County, rural residents who were without water
because of the power outages took showers at a high school.
Drinking water was distributed from four locations around the
county.
   ``I'm out of power at home myself,'' said Bob Willis, the
county's emergency management coordinator. ``But I have a daughter
close by with power, so I can get a shower and she won't let me go
hungry.''
   Two power company workers in Lincoln County were injured Monday
when a power line came loose and hit them. One worker was in
critical condition and the other was in stable condition, hospital
officials said.
   The loss of electricity made traffic signals useless as
Charlotte workers began their work week. A National Guardsman and a
Charlotte police officer directing traffic at a busy intersection
were hospitalized after being struck by a car during the morning
rush hour.
   The police officer was treated for a broken leg, while the
guardsman, a member of a military police company from Greenville,
was listed in stable condition with cuts to his face and thigh.
   About 550 National Guardsmen are on duty in North Carolina. More
than 200 North Carolina Forestry Division workers, including 56
chain saw crews, were deployed in Charlotte, Morganton and
Lexington.
   In Brunswick County, the only coastal county to sustain major
damage from Hugo, heavy rain slowed cleanup efforts.
   ``The rain is hampering us for certain,'' said Cecil Logan,
county emergency management coordinator. ``It will delay our major
cleanup efforts for at least a day.''
   Beach homes were left hanging over the surf all along the
county's coastline, with the dune line virtually wiped out in many
areas.
</TEXT>
