<DOCNO> AP890926-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0047EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-MetOpens     09-26 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Met Opens,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Met Opera Opens with Dream Cast in `Aida'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Metropolitan Opera chose ``Aida'' as its
opening night opera and gave it a dream cast.
   Aprile Millo, heralded as the next great Verdi soprano, sang the
title role on Monday night. Not content just to pour out her voice
of grandeur, she used shading, held notes and pianissimo and acted
the slave to Amneris that Aida is. Seldom has a Met Opera Aida been
so often on her knees.
   Placido Domingo, the Radames when this production was new last
December, sang Radames again. His voice was beautiful in tone,
smooth in production, sometimes ringing, occasionally tense and
harder-edged than it formerly was. He doesn't scoop up to high
notes, as most tenors do, in ``Celeste Aida.'' The final love duet,
when both inserted tenderness into their generous-size voices, was
thrilling.
   Dolora Zajick, who made her Met debut last fall, sang a notable
Amneris. She's a mezzo soprano but has a delivery like a soprano
and a confident stage presence. Some Amnerises are almost
unnoticed. When the two were together, this Amneris commanded more
attention than Aida. As Aida was subservient, the king's daughter
Amneris was regal. Miss Zajick's voice also conveyed Amneris' love,
making her a sympathetic character.
   Paata Burchuladze, from Tbilisi, U.S.S.R., was making his Met
debut as the high priest. Burchuladze, a winner in the 1985 Luciano
Pavarotti voice competition in Philadelphia, has the deep notes and
dark sound Americans expect and adore from Russian basses. He has
sung ``Boris Godunov'' in Vienna, Paris and Philadelphia.
   Sherrill Milnes sang Aida's father with urgency _ he's concerned
with the Egypt-Ethiopia war, not with love. Milnes also sang with a
beautiful tone, which characterized all the principals.
   The triumphal entry scene included a couple of horses and, for
once in a Met production, no eccentricity. Three young dancers in
Act 2 were pleasing.
   James Levine conducted with understanding. The production, by
Sonja Frisell, twice uses the device of moving a set by elevator,
thereby revealing the next set either above or below it. This is
dramatic and effective. The first time it was done, going from
Amneris' rooms to a public square full of Egyptians, the audience
gasped with appreciation.
   Though some were well gowned, women in the opening night
audience provided less a fashion show than in some years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
