<FIRST>r a PM-MarylandCongressman     09-26 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Maryland Congressman,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dyson Announces Re-election, Says Ex-Aide Improperly Pocketed Funds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Roy Dyson admitted to mistakes
in judgment during a speech announcing his re-election, and
promised to return $18,000 in campaign contributions from people
linked to a defense contractor.
   Dyson also said Monday he would take ``ultimate responsibility''
for the embezzlement of $7,275 of his former top aide, who
committed suicide in May 1988 by jumping from a New York hotel.
   ``Mistakes were made by my staff. I have made mistakes of
judgment,'' the five-term Democrat told several hundred supporters.
``I regret the controversy these matters have caused, but I want
the people of Maryland to know that these were mistakes of the
head, not of the heart.''
   Dyson, a member of the House Armed Services procurement
subcommittee, said he was returning the contributions from
employees and consultants for Unisys, which is under investigation
by the U.S. Justice Department for possible contract procurement
violations.
   ``I am returning these funds because individual pleas entered as
part of the Justice Department's `Ill Winds' investigation point to
a systematic attempt on the part of Unisys to circumvent the
federal laws governing campaign contributions,'' said Dyson.
   The investigation involves charges that defense firms or their
employees hired private consultants who bribed Pentagon officials
for information needed to win multimillion-dollar contracts.
   The congressman also said he would donate to charity a $2,000
speaking fee he received from the Oshkosh Trucking Co. on the day
he voted in favor of a bill that benefited the company.
   Dyson said he will report the apparent violations in accepting
the speaking fee to the Federal Elections Commission.
   ``Because of these errors, I anticipate that the FEC will levy a
fine which the campaign will pay to the FEC as a civil penalty for
the violations,'' Dyson said.
   Dyson also told supporters that the late Thomas Pappas, his
former top aide, had improperly pocketed $7,275 in campaign funds.
   ``I must accept ultimate responsibility for these errors in
judgment because Tom Pappas was my campaign manager,'' Dyson said.
``I was not aware that Tom was writing checks to staff members and
asking them to cash those checks and return the cash to him.''
   Luis Luna, an attorney who describes himself as ``an all but
declared'' Republican candidate for Dyson's seat, said the
congressman's admissions were welcomed but didn't go far enough in
explaining his connection to Unisys.
</TEXT>
