<FIRST>r w PM-DirectMail Bjt   09-26 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Direct Mail, Bjt,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>You Want to Buy the Names of 146,983 Biology Majors?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You know all that junk mail that falls through
your mail slot every day? If the envelope is just plain brown, it
breaks Bill Garland's heart.
   Garland is a sales representative for the Tension Envelope
Corp., a firm which produces about one-fifth of all the envelopes
used by the direct mail industry. His territory is central Ohio and
he single-handedly sells 100 million envelopes a year, enough to
fill 70 semi-trailers.
   Direct mail is big business, getting bigger. Tension Envelope
has plants in 11 cities, many working two or three shifts, six days
a week, making envelopes, headed for your mailbox.
   Garland was selling envelopes here Monday at the Direct
Marketing Association's 72nd annual conference and exhibition,
which attracted 8,000 people in the direct mail and telephone
selling business and the people who serve them, like Garland.
   ``A plain brown envelope is insane,'' said Garland. ``The
biggest opportunity for blowing the product's whistle is lost.''
   He stood before a display of envelopes that were anything but
plain. Some had rippled edges _ ``zippers'' to the trade _ that all
but compel the recipient to open the envelope, which is the point.
   The latest wrinkle in envelopes is one in which the address flap
flips over, allowing the recipient to reply using the original
envelope.
   It saves storage space, Garland explained: ``If you insert a
return envelope into the outgoing envelope, and you're using a
million envelopes a month, you've got to find space for 2 million
envelopes, not 1 million.''
   Direct marketing likes big numbers. Some 88.5 million Americans,
it brags, bought something through the mail in 1988, and the
average mail-order purchase amounted to $74.
   The compilation of mailing lists, as might be imagined, is big
business because ``targeting'' _ sending the pitch to the most
likely customer _ is the name of the game.
   The American Student List Co. of Great Neck, N.Y., offers lists
of students from kindergarten through graduate school. For $50 a
thousand, you can buy the names and home and school addresses of
146,983 biology majors.
   PCS Mailing List Co. is even more specialized. It will sell you
the names and addresses of 11,438 air traffic controllers, 16,600
subscribers to Tax Angles; 15,547 auto wheel and frame alignment
shops; 1,381 disc jockeys; 7,260 T-shirt stores; 425,000 ``high
income women''; 10,620 hair and wig dealers or 532,390 professors.
   And National Demographics and Lifestyles Inc. of Denver,
pitching its ``relevant'' lists in a comic book, refers to folks
who respond to direct marketing as ``respondoids'' and describes
them as ``ever hopeful yet enslaved mail responsive mortals'' who
``long to fill out questionnaires about themselves and receive
relevant mail.''
   National Demographics gathers its lists from respondoids who
fill out those consumer questionnaires or product registration
cards that come with new hair dryers and toasters. Only 7 percent,
the company says, check the little box indicating they want to be
on no one's mail list.
   Lisa Caugherty, director of the association's Shop at Home
Information Center, says most people like direct marketing. The
3,500-member association has developed codes of conduct to protect
those who don't.
   A 15-page pamphlet spells out the ethics of the business
(``free'' should mean ``a product or service which is offered
without cost or obligation''). Another, aimed at policing those
telephone sales calls, says the callers should not make offers ``in
the guise of research or a survey when the real intent is to sell
products or services or to raise funds.''
   As for the latest twist, telephone machines which make a
recorded sales pitch, the rules say ``a live operator'' should
first introduce the recorded message. Moreover, the guidelines say,
calls shouldn't be made ``during hours which are unreasonable to
the recipients.''
   Whether that's supper time, the guidelines don't say.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
