<FIRST>r w PM-Hispanics-Congress     09-26 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hispanics-Congress,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Reagan Official Disputes Warnings on Hispanics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Republican Hispanic says conditions for
Hispanic youth aren't as bad as described by a federal study and by
Bush administration officials.
   Linda Chavez, who served at the U.S. Civil Rights Commission
during the Reagan administration, provoked strong disagreement with
her testimony at a hearing on Hispanic children Monday by the House
Select Committee on Children, Youth and Families.
   She disputed remarks Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos made last
week when he released a report on school dropouts and said the rate
among Hispanic students is ``a national tragedy.''
   ``The future looks quite good for individual Hispanics,'' said
Chavez.
   ``Native-born Hispanics, despite the ominous report from the
Department of Education, appear to be staying in school longer,''
she said.
   She challenged the statistical basis for the report and said the
department's finding, like other statistical studies of Hispanics,
were skewed by large influxes of recent immigrants _ arriving at a
rate she estimated at 400,000 a year.
   Chavez said Hispanic immigrants will eventually move into the
economic mainstream as have earlier European immigrants, who also
faced high dropout rates in their first generations.
   The studies ``diminish the very real and significant progress''
of Hispanics in this country.
   Her remarks put her at odds, however, with a panel of Hispanic
experts appearing with her before the committee, who cited severe
poverty and education problems among Hispanics.
   ``She's not right,'' said Ann Rosewater, staff director of the
committee, following the hearing. ``They (other expert witnesses)
made a very clear point. There's lots of research showing not just
first generation, but second and third generation (Hispanics) are
not doing well in school.''
   Raul Hinojosa of the University of California at Berkeley said
Hispanics of varying national origins are falling further behind
economically. He said Hispanics have been hurt by discrimination,
low educational achievement and changes in the national labor
market that have reduced the availability of middle-income jobs.
   He said the higher fertility rate among Hispanics is a more
important factor than the arrival of recent immigrants.
   Committee Chairman George Miller, D-Calif., said Hispanics face
``severe poverty'' and ``incredible disparity'' with other ethnic
groups, regardless of the statistics used.
   ``The numbers are overwhelming,'' he said.
   Chavez is a senior fellow with the Manhattan Institute for
Policy Research, a conservative New York research organization, and
is a former unsuccessful Republican candidate for the Senate from
Maryland.
</TEXT>
