<FIRST>r a PM-PalsyVictims     09-26 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palsy Victims,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cerebral Palsy Victims Trapped by Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFAX, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple suffering from cerebral palsy were
killed when the electric blanket on their waterbed caught fire and
they were unable to escape their apartment, according to police.
   Donald and Loral Roser, both 44, were trapped as the fire spread
early Monday through their apartment in a self-care facility for
about 150 elderly and handicapped people, said Lt. Michael Reilly,
spokesman for the Fairfax County Fire and Rescue Department.
   Investigators say the blanket may have been improperly tucked
under the couple's waterbed on one of fall's first cool nights,
said Reilly.
   Because of their cerebral palsy, the couple, who were married
for three years, needed wheelchairs to run errands and used canes
in their home. They appeared to have been overcome by heavy smoke
before they could flee the apartment, fire officials said.
   Residents of Lockwood House live in apartments structured for
their needs. In addition to smoke detectors, each unit is equipped
with emergency cords in the bedrooms and bathrooms that make an
electrical panel at the front desk light up and buzz, said Nevine
Lowe, a district manager for the company.
   A desk clerk heard the emergency buzzer about 1:30 a.m. Monday,
but found thick smoke when he want to the apartment after summoning
the fire department, said Reilly.
   Roser apparently was fatally overcome as he pulled an emergency
cord, fire officials said.
</TEXT>
