<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0240EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     09-26 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gallery Officials Want to Quiet Controversy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board which runs the city's oldest art
museum is trying to come up with a plan to defuse a controversy
over the cancellation of an exhibit which contained sexually
explicit photographs.
   However, the Corcoran Gallery of Art trustees reaffirmed their
support Monday for Christina Orr-Cahall, the museum's director, who
made the cancellation decision.
   The Corcoran has been criticized for three months in the wake of
Ms. Orr-Cahall's cancellation of an exhibition of Robert
Mapplethorpe photographs. The cancellation was made with the
consent of the Corcoran's board of trustees.
   The exhibit included sexually explicit and homoerotic
photographs and pictures of nude children, which drew protests from
Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., and other conservative members of
Congress.
   At a regularly scheduled meeting Monday, the Corcoran board
agreed to appoint a special panel of trustees to examine the
three-month controversy and recommend steps to defuse it.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Drug Suspect Held in Colombia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Justice Department officials say they are
likely to seek the extradition of an accused drug trafficker
arrested in Colombia last weekend.
   Carlos Humberto Gomez-Zapata was picked up by the Colombian Army
as part of that nation's crackdown on drug lords, Justice
Department officials said Monday.
   Gomez-Zapata was indicted by a federal grand jury in Florida in
1984. The indictment alleges that Gomez-Zapata led a drug ring that
shipped tons of methaqualone from West Germany and Austria through
Panama to Colombia, where it was then transported illegally into
the United States. The drug is also known as Quaaludes, a hypnotic
depressant that was believed by users to enhance sexual pleasure.
   The indictment was one of four returned by a federal grand jury
as a result of DEA's ``Operation Hammerhead,'' which the Justice
Department said identified 24 shipments of methaqualone pills and
powder totalling 54 tons of illegal drugs bound for this country.
</TEXT>
