<FIRST>r a PM-GreenRiver     09-26 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Green River,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Green River Slaying Suspect Will Be Transferred to Feds, Magistrate
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA BLANDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man under investigation in the Green River
serial killings will be transferred to federal custody in Spokane
to face charges he possessed a firearm while a fugitive, a
magistrate ordered.
   Police, meanwhile, disclosed that William Jay Stevens II talked
for the first time with Green River Task Force, which is
investigating the slayings of up to 48 young women in the Northwest
from 1982-84.
   The interview failed to clear up a number of investigators'
questions, said King County police Capt. Robert Evans, who heads
the task force.
   On Monday, Stevens completed a sentence at the King County jail.
He had been jailed there since his January arrest in Spokane for
escaping from a work-release facility while serving a term for
burglary in 1981.
   During a hearing Monday before U.S. Magistrate John L. Weinberg,
the 38-year-old Stevens agreed to the transfer to Spokane. If
convicted on the firearms count, he could be sentenced to 10 years
in prison and fined $250,000, said Susan Dohrmann, assistant U.S.
attorney.
   The Green River Task Force has characterized Stevens as a
``viable suspect'' in its investigation into the deaths of 40 women
and the disappearances of eight others.
   The description was contained in an affidavit filed to support a
search of two Spokane residences where Stevens lived while
attending Gonzaga University's School of Law.
   No charges related to the killings have been filed against
Stevens, who has denied he is the killer.
   Late last week, Evans said his officers needed two more weeks to
finish evaluating their information on Stevens.
   ``The decision would be to determine whether this person is a
murder suspect or merely a victim of some bizarre circumstances,''
said Evans.
   The Green River slayings take their name from the south King
County river where the first victims were discovered.
</TEXT>
