<FIRST>r a PM-FranklinBooks     09-26 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Franklin Books,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Benjamin Franklin Books Missing From Library</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Franklin's Will</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two books printed by Benjamin Franklin and
worth as much as $60,000 have been stolen from the University of
Pennsylvania Library.
   One of the books is a 1744 catalogue Franklin made to advertise
second-hand and imported books he wanted to sell, said Daniel
Traister, assistant director of libraries. The volume, ``A
Catalogue of Books to be Sold,'' is the only one known to exist and
is worth $25,000 to $50,000, Traister said Monday.
   The other, which Traister said is worth at least $10,000,
consists of two 1751 essays bound together: Richard Peters' ``A
Sermon on Education'' printed in Philadelphia by Franklin and D.
Hall, and Franklin's essay called `Idea of the English School.''
   The books have been missing since Aug. 16, when a library patron
using the name Greg Williams and giving a New York address checked
them out to study in the library's rare book reading room. The
theft was discovered Friday and reported to police, Traister said.
   Investigators haven't figured out how the thief got away, and
aren't sure if he gave his real name, Traister said, adding that
both volumes are small and easily hidden.
   Directory assistance listings in the New York City area don't
have a number for Greg Williams at the address given.
</TEXT>
