<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo-IsleofPalms     09-26 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Isle of Palms,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Barrier Island Residents Return to Hugo-Battered Homes</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CHT1</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLE OF PALMS, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents who got their first look at
the devastation wrought by Hurricane Hugo say it will be years
before this barrier island returns to being a quaint seaside
village.
   ``On a normal day, this was like being in heaven,'' said Paul
Traywick, whose first floor was buried under an inch of muck.
   ``It's not like that any more,'' Traywick said. ``Not for a long
time.''
   The island, heavily damaged by wind and water and cut off from
the mainland because of a downed bridge, was declared under martial
law.
   Island officials on Monday began a daily ferry service allowing
some residents to return home for a few hours.
   Hugo's 135 mph winds bashed the island, located across the
harbor from Charleston, and a wall of water swept through homes and
businesses.
   Few houses were left undamaged, most of the taller trees were
felled and huge potholes were scooped out of the roads. The beach
has shifted, and the entire marina dock was torn loose from its
pilings and swept to nearby Goat Island.
   ``It looks like what happens after artillery fire,'' said
resident Tom Harper, a retired Air Force officer who served in
Europe during World War II.
   For many residents, angry at what they consider government
inaction in getting them on the island, it was a relief to see what
Hugo had wrought.
   ``I'm glad to know what the situation is,'' said Traywick. ``At
least I know. Now we can sit down and get started on some plans.''
   For John Bozzelli, it wouldn't have made much difference when he
got to the island. His house, now split open like an overripe
melon, is about 50 yards from where it was last week.
   ``I pretty well figured it might be gone,'' he said.
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers began work Monday on a
temporary pontoon bridge linking Isle of Palms, and adjacent
Sullivan's Island, to the mainland. Isle of Palms City Councilman
Harry O'Neal said that should give most residents of the islands
land access by week's end.
   Monday afternoon, Army barges transported bulldozers to the
island to clear the fallen trees.
   Most residents said they would return to rebuild, even with the
first-hand knowledge of what a powerful hurricane can do.
   ``I think most people will be back,'' said Muriel Metz, who owns
a house and a rental duplex on the island. ``It's like an
addiction, the laid-back style and the quiet.''
   Al Collins, manager of the Sea Cabins development that once
existed on the beach, said the cabins would be rebuilt.
   ``It's the tranquillity of the island when it's not under a
storm seige,'' Collins said. ``It'll be back to that one of these
days.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
