<DOCNO> AP890926-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0306EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     09-26 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Higher, Dollar Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose
sharply to end at yet another high Tuesday, and the dollar ended
slightly lower against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 484.11 points, or 1.38
percent, the second-largest one-day gain this year, ending the day
at 35,444.82. It gained 188.92 points Monday.
   This year's largest one-day advance, 793.96 points, was recorded
March 28.
   The dollar closed at 142.80 yen, down 0.15 yen from Monday's
close of 142.95 yen. It opened lower at 142.25 yen and ranged
between 142.10 yen and 143.15 yen.
   The U.S. currency's low opening followed its overnight plunge
overseas after coordinated dollar-selling interventions, including
actions by the central banks of the United States and Japan,
traders said.
   The currency finished at 142.13 yen in New York on Monday,
almost four yen lower than Friday's 146.05-yen close.
   Finance ministers and central bankers from the Group of Seven
industrialized countries agreed in Washington on Saturday that they
will closely cooperate in foreign exchange markets to stem the
dollar's strength.
   Minori Takeuchi, a trader with Chemical Bank in Tokyo, said the
dollar inched up in the morning when quite a few dollar-buying
orders against the West German mark came from Singapore, but later
trading was mixed as participants made position adjustments.
   Ms. Takeuchi said the Bank of Japan intervened intermittently
and sold small amount of dollars to halt a new upswing, but the
amount of selling was unknown. The central bank does not comment on
its monetary actions.
   ``For a while, the dollar is unlikely to rise back much, because
the G-7 central banks will coordinate intervention actively,'' Ms.
Takeuchi added.
   On the stock exchange, ``The Nikkei seems to have entered its
uptrend finally,'' said Masahiro Umemori, a stock analyst with
Nomura Securities.
   He attributed the index's consistent rise to the yen's rebound
against the dollar following the G-7 monetary talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
