<DOCNO> AP890926-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0314EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China     09-26 0902</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China,0931</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jiang Denies Suppression Of Pro-Democracy Movement A Tragedy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party chief Jiang Zemin today denied
that the military suppression of the pro-democracy movement was a
tragedy, calling the assault an unavoidable response to an attempt
to overthrow the government.
   Jiang, in his first news conference since being named to head
the 48-million member party in June, also indicated that the party
had yet to decide whether Deng Xiaoping, China's supreme leader,
will be allowed to retire from his last official post.
   Jiang was joined by the other five members of the Politburo
Standing Committee, the ruling party's top decision-making group,
including conservative Premier Li Peng.
   Some 400 Chinese and foreign reporters attended the conference,
which was broadcast live on national television.
   Jiang, a former party boss in Shanghai who replaced the ousted
reformist Zhao Ziyang on June 24, said of the June clash between
pro-democracy protesters and the army: ``We believe it was not a
tragedy.''
   He called the pro-democracy movement a ``counter-revolutionary
rebellion aimed at negating the leadership of the Communist Party
of China and overthrowing the socialist system.''
   The June 3-4 military attack on student-led protesters in
central Beijing was unavoidable, he said, because of foreign forces
trying to undermine China's socialist system and a handful of
people within China who ``engaged in all kinds of conspiracies in
an attempt to overthrow the existing government.''
   The army killed hundreds of unarmed civilians in the assault.
   Jiang, 63, who reportedly has been named by Deng to succeed him
as top leader when he leaves the political scene, said ``much is at
stake'' in the question of when the 85-year-old Deng should leave
his last post, as chairman of the Central Military Commission.
   He noted that Deng had on numerous occasions expressed a wish to
pass on power to a new generation, but it was still up to the party
and state to decide when the architect of China's past decade of
economic reforms can step down.
   Jiang did not mention a party decision, revealed in May by Zhao,
to continue accepting Deng's leadership on major issues regardless
of his formal resignation from all but the military post.
   Deng's resignation from that post would not be likely to alter
his position as the final arbiter of political matters, but would
reflect his efforts to put in place successors he trusts.
   Jiang acknowledged that the party Central Committee, which could
make a formal ruling on Deng's retirement, will be meeting soon to
map out economic development plans for the next two or three years.
   Jiang and the others refused to answer repeated questions on the
number of people arrested and executed in the crackdown on dissent.
   Qiao Shi, who is responsible for legal matters within the party,
said ``we have dealt with some people'' but all those executed were
convicted of serious crimes. He said China has acted prudently
toward students and intellectuals and called a foreign report of
120,000 arrests since June ``unfounded nonsense.''
   Jiang, told by a reporter that a woman student had been sent to
the countryside after participating in the pro-democracy movement
and been raped there by peasants, described the case as ``a fairy
tale out of The Arabian Nights.''
   He stressed that China's policy toward students who demanded
democratic reform was ``to unite them and educate them.''
   Since taking office Jiang has pressed for greater attention to
ideological matters, particularly among young people.
   He indicated that in this way he could escape the fate of his
two predecessors, Zhao and the late Hu Yaobang. Both were purged
for failing to combat Western liberal ideas while trying to open
China up to the world.
   Jiang declined to say what will happen to Zhao. He said the
party was ``making further investigations'' into charges Zhao
supported the pro-democracy movement and thus split the party.
   Both Jiang and Li, Zhao's rival for power, blamed Zhao for
letting the political unrest get out of hand, but Jiang's tone
indicated Zhao may escape criminal charges.
   Jiang said the party recognized that Zhao had done some positive
things in his nine years as premier and party general secretary.
   Zhao, who has not been seen in public since he went to central
Tiananmen Square on May 19 to talk to student hunger strikers, is
leading a ``quiet and comfortable life,'' Jiang said.
   Jiang added that since Zhao had served the party longer than he
had: ``He enjoys better treatment, in fact he enjoys a better
salary than me.''
   On other topics, Vice Premier Yao Yilin, who heads the State
Planning Commission, reiterated that China will stick to such
economic reforms as developing export-oriented industries along the
coast.
   He said private enterprise would continue to play a ``necessary
and beneficial supplemental role'' in the socialist economy but
added that ``appropriate restrictions'' would check the growth of
private industry.
   Premier Li spoke at length on corruption, a major issue during
the spring protests, saying the party was taking the lead by
cracking down on nepotism, use of luxury imported cars, overseas
trips, gift-giving and banqueting at public expense.
   Jiang, like the other five speakers, was dressed in a dark
Western suit and tie. A former student in the Soviet Union who also
speaks good English, he used a Russian phrase in answering a
question from a Soviet journalist and used English words on several
occasions.
</TEXT>
