<HEAD>Rain in Northeast; Cold in North-Central U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers soaked parts of the Northeast today, causing authorities
to warn of flooding in New Jersey and Pennsylvania, while a cold
front in the north-central United States dropped temperatures to
near freezing.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms dumped rain Monday from
Mississippi to the southern half of the Atlantic Coast. One
thunderstorm along the coast of North Carolina spawned a tornado
near the town of Seaside.
   More than 2{ inches of rain fell at New Bern, N.C., and more
than 1{ inches fell at Cherry Point, N.C.
   The showers and thunderstorms spread to the Northeast early
today. Small stream and urban flood watches were posted for much of
southern New Jersey and east-central Pennsylvania, where up to 3
inches of rain were possible.
   Clouds and rain kept temperatures in the 50s and 60s over much
of the Southeast on Monday.
   Strong northwesterly winds ushered more cold air into the
central part of the country. A gale warning was in effect for Lake
Huron, and frost and freeze advisories were posted overnight for
northwest Wisconsin.
   Record high temperatures on Monday included Pocatello, Idaho,
which registered 89 degrees, and Tucson, Ariz., with 103 degrees.
   Reports at 2 a.m. EDT today included:
