<FIRST>r a PM-People-Ruffin     09-26 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Ruffin,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troubled Former Temptation Jailed After Showing up Late to Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ordered former Temptations lead singer
David Ruffin to jail because he showed up five hours late for a
hearing.
   Ruffin, who was in court on a probation violation charge, was
scheduled for a 9 a.m. hearing Monday before Judge John O'Brien.
   When Ruffin arrived just before 2 p.m., O'Brien ordered Ruffin
to spend the night in jail and said the court would take up the
matter today.
   ``It would look better if he had shown up on time, but there's
hope,'' said Ruffin's attorney, Jeff Collins.
   Monday's hearing was scheduled to decide if Ruffin should
undergo drug treatment instead of serving a jail sentence.
   Ruffin, 48, was convicted in May 1988 of misdemeanor possession
of cocaine. His sentence included two years' probation, 50 days of
community service and drug testing and treatment.
   A drug test last week was positive for opiates, Collins said.
Ruffin was arrested Sept. 16, the third time this year he has been
in court for probation violations.
   Last week, Ruffin denied he had a drug problem, then admitted it
later.
   The judge had postponed deciding Ruffin's case until Monday, so
Collins could check into the price and availability of a
drug-treatment center in New York City.
