<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0503EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NYCPoliceCommissioner     09-26 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYC Police Commissioner,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Resigns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA ROSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Benjamin Ward, the city's first black police
commissioner, has resigned after almost six years, leaving a legacy
of innovation despite budget constraints, a tough war on drugs and
his own verbal gaffes.
   ``I'm not always right,'' Ward once said, ``but I'm never dull.''
   Ward, 63, cited chronic asthma in a resignation letter sent
Monday to Mayor Edward I. Koch. His departure is effective Oct. 22.
   During Ward's time in office, crime rates soared and city
streets got more violent, fueled by crack.
   Ward said combating the drug war was his ``highest priority from
the start,'' noting that the Narcotics Division grew almost
five-fold during his term, which began Jan. 1, 1984. He also
created Tactical Narcotics Teams that are deployed to crack-ridden
neighborhoods.
   But, Ward added in his letter, ``I must acknowledge that the
greatest problem when I came in is even more serious as I depart.
... The plague of illegal drugs that has wreaked such tragedy,
violence and crime.''
   Koch, who called Ward ``one of the greatest police commissioners
that ever served,'' appointed First Deputy Commissioner Richard J.
Condon _ Ward's own choice _ as commissioner.
   Koch, who lost his bid for re-election in September's Democratic
primary to Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins, leaves office
at the end of the year.
   Koch said Ward indicated before the primary that he wanted to
resign but waited at the mayor's request. He said Ward would return
to private life, but would not elaborate.
   Ward has been working since June on his memoirs, tentatively
titled ``Cop,'' to be published next fall.
   Ward ran afoul of some black groups in July 1987 when he called
black crime against blacks ``our little dirty secret.''
   The next month, he apologized publicly for saying to a woman who
spoke at a town meeting about being afraid of rapists: ``You're out
here tonight. You can't be too frightened. You're the kind he's
looking for, under 30, beautiful, blonde.''
   In apologizing for what he called that ``insensitive'' remark,
Ward said the woman had been heckling him and that he had taken
asthma medication that ``may hype me up.''
   Ward joined the force in 1951 as the first black police officer
in a Brooklyn precinct.
   ``I think they were surprised to see me,'' he recalled in 1984.
``I had an Irish name, and I came from a predominantly white
veterans' housing project in Bath Beach, but when they saw me, they
developed a sudden shortage of lockers at the precinct house.''
   By the time he was through, the positions he held included
detective, head of the internal legal department, commissioner for
community affairs, city traffic commissioner, state correction
commissioner, chief of the city housing police and city correction
commissioner.
   The commissioner oversaw a department with 26,790 officers. In
resigning, he noted that it had grown by 2,129 officers during his
tenure and that the number of black officers rose 17 percent,
Hispanics 60 percent and women 85 percent.
   The uniformed force now is 11 percent black, 11.5 percent
Hispanic and 12.4 percent female, he said.
   Ward also cited increased educational requirements for certain
ranks, a ``stronger stand'' on domestic violence and a program to
put officers back on foot patrol in all 75 precincts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
