<FIRST>r a PM-NewspaperSale     09-26 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspaper Sale,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>McClatchy Purchases Three South Carolina Newspapers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McClatchy Newspapers Inc., publisher
of California'a Bee newspapers, has agreed to buy three daily
papers in South Carolina from the News &amp; Observer Publishing Co.
for $74.1 million.
   Being sold are The Herald of Rock Hill, the Island Packet of
Hilton Head and The Beaufort Gazette, Sacramento-based McClatchy
said in announcing the deal Monday.
   The sale will take effect Jan. 1, and will include five smaller
publications in York and Beaufort counties in South Carolina,
McClatchy said.
   The Herald has a daily circulation of approximately 28,000, the
Island Packet of 10,000 and The Beaufort Gazette of 9,000.
   ``These are quality newspapers in quality markets,'' said Erwin
Potts, president and chief executive officer of McClatchy
Newspapers.
   ``Our company's record in publishing small and medium-sized
newspapers suggests we can continue the improvement of these South
Carolina newspapers as they grow in size and importance to their
communities.''
   Frank Daniels Jr., president of the News &amp; Observer Publishing
Co., said he was ``pleased we are selling the newspapers to a
company with McClatchy's reputation for news and editorial
excellence, integrity and concern for its employees. Our people and
our communities will be well-served.''
   The company's papers include The News &amp; Observer in Raleigh,
N.C., and The Raleigh Times.
   McClatchy publishes six dailies and seven smaller newspapers in
California, Washington state and Alaska. Its flagship newspaper,
The Sacramento Bee, has a circulation of 250,000 daily and 300,000
Sundays. McClatchy's other dailies include the 60,000-circulation
Anchorage Daily News, which won this year's Pulitzer Prize for
public service.
</TEXT>
