<SECOND>PM-People-Janeway,0112</SECOND>
<HEAD>One-Time FDR Adviser Urges Drug Legalization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economist Eliot Janeway, an adviser to
President Franklin Roosevelt, says the United States should give
drugs away to cut crime and illicit drug profits.
   ``Let's fall back on an ancient, honorable, all-American
preference for getting something for nothing. Let's make users and
addicts an offer they can't resist,'' Janeway, 76, told the Detroit
Economic Club.
   ``Activate the U.S. government for a business it knows and does
best: handouts,'' Janeway said, describing efforts to fight drugs
as a ``fruitless operation.''
   Janeway said hard-line drug policies merely swell prison
populations and result in more young, poor, urban dealers.
