<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0512EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-26 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Hit New High, Dollar Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index closed at a
new high today after its second-largest one-day gain this year,
while the U.S. dollar fell marginally against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 484.11
points, or 1.38 percent, closing at 35,444.82. The previous record
close was 35,140.83 on Aug. 21.
   Tuesday's gain was the largest since a 793.96-point rise March
28. The Nikkei had climbed 188.92 points Monday.
   The dollar closed at 142.80 yen, down 0.15 yen from its finish
of 142.95 yen on Monday, when it fell 2.05 yen. It opened today at
142.25 yen and moved between 142.10 yen and 143.15 yen.
   Bank of Japan Vice Governor Yasushi Miyeno told reporters today
that the trend is toward a lower dollar and higher yen after the
``Group of Seven'' industrialized nations agreed in Washington
Saturday to cooperate in foreign exchange markets to stem the
dollar's recent rise.
   He said Japan's central bank would continue taking appropriate
measures, keeping close contact with other G-7 nations.
   Another Bank of Japan official said the central bank would
prefer the dollar to decline to its levels of ``six months ago.''
At that time, the dollar was trading at about 132 yen.
   The G-7 statement said, ``A rise of the dollar above currents
levels or an excessive decline could affect adversely prospects for
the world economy.''
   Minori Takeuchi, a trader at Chemical Bank, said the Bank of
Japan intervened intermittently today, selling small amounts of
dollars to halt a new upswing, but the amount of selling was
unknown. The central bank does not comment on its money market
activities.
   ``For a while, the dollar is unlikely to rise back much because
the G-7 central banks will coordinate intervention actively,'' Ms.
Takeuchi added.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the index rose mainly
because investors were reassured by the yen's recovery against the
dollar.
   Kazuhiro Nomura, a dealer with New Japan Securities Co., said
investors bought aggressively because today was the actual first
day of a new financial year for most businesses.
   The new business year starts Oct. 1 for most Japanese companies,
but stock transactions for the next business year start five days
earlier, Nomura explained.
   Investment trust companies were aggressive buyers today, mainly
purchasing high-tech, financial and electric power company issues,
Nomura said.
   Trading was moderate, with first section volume estimated at 900
million shares, a large increase from Monday's 550 million.
</TEXT>
