<FIRST>r a PM-PreppieMurderer     09-26 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Preppie Murderer,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Preppie Murderer Caught Twice With Pot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Chambers, the prep-school student who
strangled an 18-year-old woman in Central Park, was not allowed to
watch a TV movie about the case because he was caught twice with
marijuana in jail, officials said.
   Chambers was locked in his cell for 23 hours a day as punishment
after he was caught smoking marijuana in the prison yard May 16,
state Department of Corrections spokeswoman Amy Colodny said Monday.
   Less than a month later, guards found two marijuana cigarettes
in his cell, according to Colodny. That time, prison officials
disciplined Chambers by sending him to a special confinement area
for 15{ weeks, she said.
   Chambers returned to his cell Thursday, but continued to have
all privileges denied, except for one hour of recreation a day,
Colodny said.
   ``If he hadn't misbehaved, he could have watched the movie until
lockup at 10 o'clock,'' she said. ABC-TV broadcast a dramatization
of the case called ``The Preppie Murder'' from 9 to 11 p.m. Sunday.
   Guards also have found Chambers with a razor blade and
unauthorized legal papers, the spokeswoman said.
   Chambers, who turned 23 Monday, pleaded guilty to first degree
manslaughter in the Aug. 26, 1986, death of Jennifer Levin. He was
incarcerated in May 1988 at Great Meadow Correctional Facility in
upstate New York to serve his five- to 15-year term.
   Chambers' bad behavior will not change his parole eligibility
date of February 1993, Colodny said, but the parole board will
examine his record of conduct when deciding whether to grant parole.
   Levin's grandfather, Arnold Domenitz, said when told of
Chambers' infractions, ``This is an amoral character who doesn't
know right from wrong. ... I hope they throw the book at him.''
</TEXT>
