<FIRST>r a PM-CaptiveWoman     09-26 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Captive Woman,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Arrested For Allegedly Holding Woman in Slavery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AZUSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three people accused of kidnapping a
Guatemalan woman and keeping her enslaved for a year through
torture and rape have been arrested, authorities said.
   Two women, ages 28 and 32, and a man, 37, were arrested Monday
night after an informant's tip sent detectives to a camper truck
that matched the description of the one where the victim was
chained each night, said sheriff's Lt. Ray Grant.
   The woman escaped Sept. 2 by stealing keys from her sleeping
captors.
   ``She tried to escape once before but was beaten,'' said police
Detective Delia Perez.
   The 27-year-old woman told police she was kidnapped July 15,
1988, when a woman approached her at a bus stop and lured her into
the camper with the promise of a job.
   She was raped, tortured with electrical shocks and forced to
cook and clean for a man, two women and five children, police said.
At night, she was chained in the camper outside the group's home.
   Six children, ranging in age from infancy to 8 or 9 years old,
were taken into protective custody at the time of the arrests,
Grant said.
   Authorities withheld the names of the adults booked by Los
Angeles police for investigation of kidnapping, he said.
   Police said they do not doubt the victim's story.
   ``When I first read the report I said, `Aw, come on, these
things don't happen,''' said police Detective Dick Heidesch. ``But
several of us talked to the victim independently, a counselor
talked to her and everyone is convinced she is telling the truth.''
</TEXT>
