<DOCNO> AP890926-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0558EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Vietnam-Soldiers 1stLd-Writethru   09-26 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vietnam-Soldiers, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0474,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Glad To Be Home, Worry About Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To ADD background on earlier withdrawals INSERT two grafs after
17th, ```My officers ... change.''' Picks up 18th pvs, `Some soldiers ...'
^With PM-Cambodia-Vietnam, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOC BAI, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten years ago, Linh Trang was one of the
first Vietnamese soldiers to enter Cambodia in a surprise invasion
that toppled the Khmer Rouge government in Phnom Penh.
   ``It was hell in Cambodia, 10 years of it,'' said Trang, 33, who
commanded a battallion in the guerrilla-infested jungles of western
Cambodia. ``I'm just glad to be going home.''
   This morning, those 10 years in hell ended as Trang and 10,000
other troops marched home through the gates of this sleepy border
town.
   Up and down the border, Vietnamese troops are coming home in
what the Hanoi government says is the withdrawal of its last 26,000
troops in Cambodia.
   Returning by ship, ferry, truck and on foot, the soldiers faced
a government-orchestrated hero's welcome today but an uncertain
future.
   Like many of his comrades, Trang was stricken by malaria during
the war. He also said he's lost 15 pounds, which means a lot to his
small frame.
   But, he said, none of his health problems concern him. What is
important now is to find a job.
   Last week, the chief spokesman of the Vietnamese Defense
Ministry said Vietnam would demobilize an unspecificied number of
solidiers after its war with Cambodia.
   Major Gen. Nguyen Van Thai said returning veterans would be
given preference in finding work and economic assistance if they
had difficulties.
   But many wonder whether Vietnam, which is one of the poorest
countries in Asia and already faces an unemployment crisis, will be
able to provide jobs for the returning soldiers.
   ``I am not a young man,'' said Trang, ``so I don't think I can
return to school. I want to work in textiles, maybe as a tailor.
Before I entered the army I was a tailor in Ho Chi Minh City.''
   Still, he said, nothing had been settled.
   Luon Van Dang is a little more sure about what he wants to do
but just as worried.
   The 23-year-old from Can Tho province says he will try to stay
in the armed forces, his home for the last five years.
   ``I like a soldier's life,'' he said as he squatted in the
buffer zone between Cambodia and Vietnam. ``I lost my family during
the Vietnam War so the army is my family. They feed me and clothe
me. I believe in them.''
   Dang said he hoped he would not be demobilized.
   ``My officers know I love the Vietnamese Army,'' he said, ``but
after I walk through the gate to my country over there everything
could change.''
   Hanoi has demobilized more than a half-million soldiers in
recent years, Gen. Tran Cong Man, editor of Vietnam's official army
newspaper, said in a recent interview with The Associated Press.
   He said the armed forces' manpower peak was 1.5 million in 1979,
50,000 were demobilized between 1982 and 1987, and over the past
two years Hanoi had released 500,000.
   Some soldiers said they will miss Cambodia.
   Earlier last week, at a good-bye ceremony at Pursat, a
provincial Cambodian capital, Cao Viet sat weeping in the corner as
he hugged a Cambodian brother-in-arms.
   ``We are very close to the people in the countryside,'' said the
Vietnamese officer who spent six years in Cambodia and speaks good
Khmer. ``We died for these people and they know it. I will never
forget the people here.''
   Behind him, a Cambodian cultural troupe played salsa music.
Vietnamese soldiers danced with Cambodian women. Bottles of Western
scotch were passed from hand to hand.
   Fighting in the jungles was difficult, Viet said. Lack of
transportation makes for shortages of drinking water and food. Many
nights he and his men went hungry, he said.
   ``A guerrilla enemy is very hard to destroy,'' Viet said. ``They
would attack and then disperse and chasing them with difficult.''
   The Vietnamese Army began as a guerrilla force when it battled
the French and American armies but it used more traditional methods
in fighting its war in Cambodia. Viet said he saw no irony in this.
   ``We were the liberators of Cambodia,'' he said. ``We did what
we had to do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
