<DOCNO> AP890926-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0559EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PrisonNewspaper     09-26 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prison Newspaper,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmates Angered Over Columns Missing From Prison Newspaper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Texas Department of Corrections has decided to
stop publishing stories on legal issues in the prison system's
monthly newspaper, angering inmates who say it was the most popular
feature in the paper.
   ``Several months ago, they told me there would be no more
articles on legal issues generally,'' said Guy Marble, an inmate
who has been editor of The Echo for the past four years. ``That's
probably the most-read part of the paper, and it's definitely the
part we got the most complaints about if it wasn't there.''
   The legal section of the newspaper included a column by the
corrections department's staff counsel, articles by inmates
discussing recent court decisions and reprints of ``free world''
stories that address penal issues, Dallas-based Texas Lawyer
newspaper reported.
   Corrections department Deputy Director Andy Collins denied
Monday that he has banned law-related stories, but said the
articles on legal issues often were inaccurate. Collins said he
prefers to devote space to describing prison services available to
inmates to prepare them for the real world.
   ``I'm not going to do any free advertising for lawyers, and I'm
not going to teach people how to sue,'' Collins said. ``But we will
do articles on things like the services provided for inmates by the
inmate attorney.''
   Staff attorney Randy Farrar, whose state-supported office offers
legal advice to inmates, said he had completed columns for the May
and June issues when word came they wouldn't be used. Farrar said a
column on the Open Records Act might have displeased a corrections
department board member.
   The legal issues column addressed such subjects as the
consequences of filing frivolous appeals and changes in such
matters as deadly weapons findings by juries and whether notaries
are needed for certain legal documents.
   Marble said several inmates have indicated they plan to file
suit over the format change.
   ``I get sued every day and I'm sure I'll get sued over this,''
Collins said. ``It's part of my job.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
