<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     09-26 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Both Drop</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most major foreign
currencies in calm European trading this morning following reported
intervention by the Japanese and West German central banks, dealers
said.
   Gold prices eased on profit-taking.
   The Group of Seven finance ministers and central bank chiefs
announced their determination at a weekend meeting in Washington to
stop the dollar's rise, and dealers predicted the interventions
would succeed.
   ``There is a seriousness behind the statements that they really
want to pressure the dollar,'' said Gerhard Sunderdiek, a dealer at
the Bank of America in Frankfurt.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.15 yen to a closing 142.80 yen. It was
quoted at the same level later in London.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Monday:
   _1.9035 West German marks, down from 1.9055
   _1.6530 Swiss francs, down from 1.6565
   _6.4485 French francs, down from 6.4540
   _2.1499 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1480
   _1,375.00 Italian lire, down from 1,377.00
   _1.1750 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1776
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.6135 to buy one pound, compared with $1.6080 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $366.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Monday's $367.00. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $366.60.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $366.75, unchanged from late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 0.33 to close at a bid $367.53.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.27 a troy
ounce, unchanged from Monday.
</TEXT>
