<FIRST>r i PM-QuebecElection     09-26 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quebec Election,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quebec Re-elects Liberals; English Speakers Register Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Liberal Party governing Quebec retained its
majority over a steady challenge from the separatist Parti
Quebecois and a surprising protest vote from the province's
English-speaking minority.
   Results of Monday's vote in the largest and second most populous
Canadian province showed the Liberals led by Premier Robert
Bourassa with 92 seats in the 125-seat provincial assembly.
   The Parti Quebecois won 29 seats, a gain of six, and a new
Equality Party captured four in traditional Liberal strongholds.
   ``I believe that this is a sign of confidence,'' a smiling
Bourassa, whose early hopes for a calm campaign capitalizing on
four years of continuing prosperity in Canada's largest province
had been dashed by environmental protests and labor unrest, said at
his district headquarters.
   The Parti Quebecois had been reeling from its provincial
election debacle four years ago in which it lost power to Bourassa
and fell to only 23 of the then-122 seat assembly.
   Jacques Parizeau, who won an internal party battle to put it
back on a hard-line course last year, ran a strong campaign on a
platform of eventual independence for the majority French-speaking
province.
   ``We have progressed solidly toward the goal that we think is
the right one,'' Parizeau said Monday night in reiterating his
separatist aims. Supporters chanted ``Le Quebec aux Quebecois,'' or
``Quebec for Quebecers.''
   The Equality Party was formed by English speakers irate over
Quebec's language policies that still restrict all outdoor signs to
French. Supporters at party headquarters sang ``O Canada,'' the
national anthem, at their victory celebration.
   ``I have never been so proud to be a Canadian and a Quebecois in
my life,'' said Robert Libman, 29-year-old architect who formed the
Equality Party just months ago.
   Bourassa, an economist, counted on Quebecers being more
interested in pragmatic issues related to prosperity than to
independence. He pointed to a 4 percent annual economic growth
rate, the creation of 233,000 new jobs and the social stability
that lasted most of his term.
   But the idea of separatism for Quebec, thought to have been put
to rest in a 1980 referendum in which 60 percent of the voters
rebuffed it, held on to its current of support.
   The Parti Quebecois won 38.7 percent of the popular vote in the
December 1985 provincial election. Projections were that it had
increased slightly to 40 percent Monday.
   Bourassa's support among Quebec's English-speaking minority,
which traditionally had voted Liberal, was hurt by his refusal in
December to allow more than a token change in provincial laws
restricting commercial signs to the French language.
   His compromise solution allowed bilingual signs only indoors as
long as the French-language portion was significantly larger than
the English.
   Quebec, which has a population of 6.5 million, is 81 percent
French-speaking.
   Supporters of language restrictions argue they are necessary to
protect French and Quebec's special culture surrounded by English
elsewhere in North America. Those who oppose the restrictions say
they violate basic rights.
   Bourassa's term before the language uproar last winter was
unusually quiet as Quebec settled into a period of strong economic
growth, leading to speculation that the Parti Quebecois could be
facing its last days.
   The separatist party had controlled the provincial government
from 1976, at the height of the period when power in Quebec shifted
from the English-speaking minority to the French majority, to their
defeat in 1985.
   Monday's victory confirmed the comeback by Bourassa, whose
colorless style could almost be considered a trademark.
   He was the youngest premier ever elected in Quebec when he won
the 1970 election at the age of 36, but the Parti Quebecois then
ousted him six years later at the height of separatist sentiment.
</TEXT>
