<FIRST>r a PM-PhotoRetaliation     09-26 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Photo Retaliation,0354</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bus Rams Newspaper Office in Apparent Retaliation for Photos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MESA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The office of a newspaper that has been
criticized for running photographs of a man electrocuted in an
accident was rammed by a bus spray-painted with messages demanding
respect for the dead man.
   Police questioned a man whose wallet was found under the bus
that crashed into the lobby of The Mesa Tribune early Monday. The
man, whose surname is the same as the dead man's, refused to
cooperate, said police spokesman Mike Hayes.
   No one was injured in the incident.
   The Tribune printed two color photos last week with a brief
story on the death of Mark Tracy, 25, who was killed Sept. 18 when
he touched a power line while trimming a palm tree.
   The newspaper ran one photo showing Tracy's legs as paramedics
lowered him from the tree. The other photo showed a relative
leaning against an ambulance, hyperventilating, after seeing Tracy
die.
   Tracy's friends and relatives flooded the paper with angry calls
and letters about the photos.
   An anonymous caller to Phoenix television station KTSP claimed
responsibility for ramming the building because the newspaper
``disgraced'' Tracy, said Mary Morse, a morning producer.
   The wallet found at the scene led police to Lloyd Ray Tracy, 33,
Hayes said. Officers also found a bill of sale for the bus made out
to Tracy, though it was still registered to another man, Hayes said.
   Police were unsure of the relationship between Lloyd Tracy and
the dead man, Hayes said.
   The 1956 school bus was spray-painted with ``We love you Mark,
rest in peace,'' and ``We demand respect for Mark Tracy.''
   Tribune publisher Michael Laosa said the decision to publish the
photos was like ``any other decision that our editors have to make
on a daily basis.''
   Laosa added: ``They think it and rethink it and make a decision
to run or not run it. We will continue to make those kinds of
judgments as the situations present themselves. I wish there was an
easy answer.''
</TEXT>
