<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo-HeritageUSA     09-26 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Heritage USA,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hugo Hastens Closing of Bakker's Former Empire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MILL, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Hugo knocked out electricity
and phones at Heritage USA, hastening the closing of much of the
Christian theme park and retreat built by Jim Bakker.
   ``We were planning to close the hotel anyhow. It was a cash
drain,'' M.C. Benton, the bankruptcy trustee overseeing the
property, said Monday.
   The 11-year-old, 2,200-acre park was shut down Friday after
Hugo's assault. The Heritage Grand Hotel, full of charismatic
Christians and curiosity-seekers before Bakker's downfall in a sex
and money scandal, had been nearly empty in recent months.
   Bakker resigned from the ministry in 1987 and PTL filed for
bankruptcy. Bakker is on trial in Charlotte, N.C., on charges of
defrauding followers by diverting nearly $4 million in donations to
live in high style.
   Prosecutors said he oversold ``lifetime partnerships''
guaranteeing major contributors lodging at the Heritage Grand.
   Heritage USA in its heyday drew millions of believers. In
addition to Jim and Tammy Bakker, the attractions included the
ornate hotel, a water park, shops, a TV studio and church and
residential areas.
   Only the residential areas _ condominiums, houses and apartments
_ remain open.
   Toronto businessman Stephen Mernick last week said he had
withdrawn his offer of $65 million for Heritage USA.
   He won court approval in December to buy the park but could not
get the title insurance needed to close the deal because of a claim
to the land from an Indian tribe.
   ``There are still a few interested players yet,'' Benton said.
``I've gotten no written bid, but there has been expression of
interest.''
</TEXT>
