<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0924EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Fusion     09-26 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Institute Fails To Duplicate Results of Fusion Experiments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experiments at the University of Utah's
new National Cold Fusion Institute have shown no sign of producing
fusion, says the director of the research center.
   ``We have a conference coming up here next February,'' said
director Hugo Rossi. ``If we don't have any papers to present, then
this place will be closing up shop. I'm not saying I will do that.
I'm just saying I think that is what would happen.''
   The center was set up by the state after chemists B. Stanley
Pons and Martin Fleischmann announced at the university in March
that they had harnessed the energy source that powers the sun by
achieving fusion at room temperature in a jar.
   Rossi said Monday the institute's more than 20 electrochemical
cells, all variations of Pons and Fleischmann's experiment, have
produced no excess heat and no fusion products such as neutrons or
tritium.
   ``It's gotten to be time for us to start wondering if we're
doing anything wrong,'' said Rossi. He called the situation
``unnerving.''
   Scientists around the world have had difficulty duplicating Pons
and Fleischmann's experiments, which held out the possibility of a
cheap, relatively safe and virtually inexhaustible supply of energy.
   Conventional nuclear energy, or fission, splits atoms; fusion
produces energy by fusing them together.
   Rossi said the institute is negotiating with the Electric Power
Research Institute in Menlo Park, Calif., for funding. The
institute so far has only $4.3 million in state money to spend on
research. Neither Rossi nor Fritz Kulhammer, EPRI vice president
for exploratory research, would say how much money is involved.
   In another development, a scientist from the European laboratory
CERN said that a worldwide examination of attempts to duplicate
cold fusion shows there is little hope that it is real.
   Douglas Morrison, a self-described student of ``pathological
science,'' said that in most cases the experimenters found no
effect or found something early on but couldn't repeat it.
   Morrison, a physicist at the European Organization for Nuclear
Research in Geneva, was in Utah last week to visit with University
of Utah scientists. Pons and Fleischmann were in Japan and are not
expected to return until Thursday.
   Morrison said cold fusion fits the mold of other wrong
experiments in scientific history that appeared to hold huge
promise.
   ``It is normal when you have a wonderful dream to accept the
positive and suppress the negative,'' he said. ``Everyone does it.
Scientists are human, too.''
   Rossi said Morrison ``gave his talk as if the book has been
closed, and I think it's premature.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890926-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0934EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Politics 1stLd-Writethru   09-26 0629</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0414,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Soviet Discusses Budget and Economic Reform</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads thruout to UPDATE with legislature today addressing whether
to put private businesses under more control; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Soviet today began a stormy debate on
the future of small private businesses that President Mikhail
Gorbachev says are facing an ultimatum from Soviet consumers upset
about price gouging.
   Gorbachev questioned why soap, for example, is sold by the
businesses for as much as $9 when it should sell for $1.50 or less.
   ``We have to take into account the mood of the people,'' he told
the legislature as it began debating proposed amendments that would
decentralize control of private firms and give local governments
more power to regulate them.
   The amendments were to be submitted to a legislative committee,
but both opponents and supporters of the private businesses, called
cooperatives, used the joint session to debate the enterprises'
future.
   The debate came a day after the Soviet government presented a
``crisis'' budget including a reduction in defense spending by more
than 8 percent and measures to cut the budget deficit in half.
   Gorbachev initiated legislation that beginning in 1987 allowed
individuals to set up small cooperative businesses to provide goods
and services the government-run economy could not.
   He said he stands by cooperatives for the innovation and
competition they can bring to the Soviet economy, but that price
gouging and corruption must be controlled because of public outrage.
   Several groups, including trade union activists and a group of
farmers who met with Gorbachev last weekend, are demanding a
crackdown on cooperatives, which charge prices that are not
regulated by the state.
   Deputy Veniamin Yarin of Nizhni Tagilsk said that cooperatives
engage in ``open robbery of the working man.''
   But Deputy Anatoly Sobchak, head of the law school at Leningrad
State University, said cooperatives in some areas were facing
wholesale closure by local governments that were ignoring the law.
   Deputy Premier Leonid Abalkin, one of Gorbachev's closest
economic advisers, presented the amendments and told the deputies
that ``cooperatives are making the first step toward forming a
socialist market, which we have been talking about for so long.''
   Abalkin said problems that cause public outrage with
cooperatives actually are the problems of the entire Soviet
economy, such as severe shortages of basic goods and services.
   He said Soviet society must recognize that cooperatives are an
important part of the economy, agree to treat them equally with
state-run business, and allow local governments to regulate them in
order to take into account local needs and viewpoints.
   Finance Minister Valentin Pavlov, who presented the 1990 budget
proposal on Monday, described the country's economic problems as a
``crisis.'' The Supreme Soviet's two-month session will consider
about 80 bills aimed at altering some long-time tenets of Soviet
politics.
   With a need to generate more revenues and cut expenses, the
Kremlin plans to implement a progressive income tax for Soviets
earning $1,076 a month _ more than three times the average worker's
wage _ and float a $92 billion bond issue, the nation's first
domestic offering, to help finance new construction, Pavlov told
the lawmakers.
   The 542-member bicameral Supreme Soviet, chaired by Gorbachev,
has reconvened at a time of widespread turmoil and discontent
caused by the demands of various ethnic groups and by the state-run
economy's failure to meet many Soviets' basic needs.
   The government's plan for the economy in 1990 calls for a
one-fifth increase in factory-made consumer goods, according to
Deputy Premier Lev Voronin.
   Pavlov said the government plan to cut military spending from
$119 billion to $109 billion is in keeping with the directive from
the Congress of People's Deputies to slash defense spending by 14
percent by 1991.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
