<FIRST>r a PM-LakeSold     09-26 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lake Sold,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lake Liquidated in Bankruptcy Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHESHIRE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An entire lake has been liquidated, so to
speak, sold to two businessmen for $110,000 at a lakeside auction.
   The bidding for Hoosac Lake, a 120-year-old reservoir built to
provide water power for mills, was part of a bankruptcy proceeding
begun eight years ago by the now-defunct Arnold Print Works. The
sale is subject to court approval.
   The winning bid in Monday's auction, held on a causeway spanning
the 566-acre lake in the Berkshire hills of western Massachusetts,
was entered by Raymond Shea Jr. of Framingham and S. John Loscocco
of North Oxford.
   Shea said he and Loscocco own about half a dozen bodies of water
in central Massachusetts that are used mainly for recreation.
   ``We have an interest in water,'' Shea said. ``We haven't really
developed anything and we don't have any plans at this point to do
any developing.''
   Along with the lake, they get 50 acres on the shore.
   Some Cheshire residents were aprehensive about the sale, fearing
that a private owner might charge admission or erect large
developments.
   Some had hoped the auction would flop, proving the lake doesn't
have commercial potential and possibly opening the door for its
donation to the town or state. Cheshire had been paying $750 a year
to use the lake.
   Town officials had said the lake would be a bad buy because of
the cost of weeding, expected to be $31,000 this year, and because
of the age of its dam.
   The lake was created in the 1860s, when a group of manufacturers
bought land and dammed the Hoosac River to produce water power.
   In 1912 the Hoosac Reservoir Co. was formed to oversee
management of the water; Arnold Print Works was the last remaining
shareholder of that company.
</TEXT>
