<FIRST>u i PM-Yugoslavia     09-26 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slovenia Challenges Federal Authorities, Prepares to Vote on Secession</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defiant Slovenian lawmakers set a
vote Wednesday on whether Yugoslavia's most liberal republic should
be allowed to secede, despite warnings that authorities could
impose a state of emergency.
   The Communist Party's policy-setting Central Committee, the
Slovenian Central Committee and the federal parliament scheduled
emergency sessions today to discuss the political crisis sparked by
the proposed amendments to the republic's constitution.
   Slovenian lawmakers in the federal parliament said they would
boycott the Belgrade session.
   According to a proposed amendment, Slovenia would have a
``lasting and inalienable right to proclaim self-determination,
including the right of secession.''
   Another proposed amendment declares that Slovenian authorities
have the sole right to declare a state of emergency in the region
and to authorize the use of Yugoslav army units in the republic.
   Slovenia, which borders Italy, Austria and Hungary, is the most
prosperous and westward-looking of Yugoslavia's six constituent
republics. It has already allowed an unprecedented degree of
democratization, including the formation of several independent
political parties.
   Yugoslavia's state and communist party leadership has criticized
the amendments as being contrary to the federal constitution.
   The collective state presidency in charge of the armed forces
said Monday it will use all ``legal measures'' to prevent the
adoption of the amendments, indicating it might proclaim a state of
emergency in the northern republic.
   Slovenia's Central Committee said today, ``There are no
convincing reasons for delaying the adoption of the amendments nor
do they conflict with the Yugoslav constitution.''
   The Slovenian Communists said, according to the Tanjug news
agency, that the amendments ``do not represent a danger for the
future of Yugoslavia.''
   The Yugoslav federation is ``not being endangered by those
demanding additional guarantees for the respect of the equality and
sovereignty of its people.''
   A recent public opinion poll conducted in the republic said that
more than 70 percent of Slovenes favor the constitutional changes.
   Despite warnings by the eight-member presidency that the vote on
the changes must be postponed, Slovenian parliament President Miran
Potrc said he was certain the Slovenian legislature will adopt the
amendments.
   Meanwhile, an influential war veterans organaization in the
country's capital of Belgrade called for an urgent introduction of
emergency measures in Slovenia and for ``the arrest of all those
responsible'' for the amendments, the Vecernje Novosti newspaper
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
