<FIRST>u w PM-CongressionalMailing 1stLd-Writethru a0446 09-26 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congressional Mailing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0446,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angry Words Fly as Congress Moves to Save Free Mailings</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: LEADS with 3 grafs Sen. Wilson comments; picking up 2nd graf
pvs, The decision xxx</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The author of legislation virtually
eliminating congressional mass mailings and using the savings for
drug treatment programs criticized House-Senate negotiators today
for their decision to drop the measure.
   ``That is a disgrace,'' Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., told his
colleagues on the Senate floor.
   Wilson, who is running for governor of California next year and
hopes to leave the Senate, complained that federal aid for drug
treatment programs ``is not remotely sufficient.'' He said
lawmakers' refusal to transfer funds from mailings to drug efforts
is a signal to the public that as far as Congress is concerned,
``Our first priority is ourselves.''
   The decision Monday by a House-Senate conference committee to
save the mailings was an embarrassing about-face for the House.
Only two hours before, in a non-binding 245-137 vote, the House
instructed its conference members to back Senate language virtually
ending the free mailings.
   The conferees accepted a compromise to continue the mailings,
but drop the number from six annually to three. The proposal was
introduced by Rep. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., who pronounced the House
vote a fraud as soon as it ended.
   ``This was not a vote to instruct the conferees so much as it
was a vote to ... pose for holy pictures,'' he said. ``It's pure
demagoguery but it's great politics.''
   In the conference, however, Fazio and Rep. David Obey, D-Wis.,
saved their wrath for the Senate for starting the anti-free mailing
campaign on Sept. 7. At the time, senators voted 83-8 for an
amendment to ban all newsletters, town meeting notices and mailings
to more than 500 households _ 95 percent of the mass mailings,
according its sponsor, Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif.
   Fazio told Senate conferees Harry Reid, D-Nev. and Don Nickles,
R-Okla. that senators wanted the House to ``do your dirty work,''
by saving the mass mailings after senators went on record as
opposing the newsletters.
   Reid accepted the compromise to continue the mailings on a
reduced scale. Nickels opposed the move, but no formal conference
vote was taken once he admitted that Fazio's compromise would pass.
   The conferees must now submit their proposal separately to the
House and Senate, each of which would face the possibility of an
embarrassing reversal. The bill approved by the conferees would
appropriate $1.9 billion to run Congress in the next fiscal year.
   Wilson sought to transfer the estimated $45 million in savings
from the anti-mailing plan to a treatment program for pregnant
women addicted to drugs.
   Fazio said he was angry the Senate tried to meddle in House
affairs by controlling the mailings of both chambers, and Obey
threatened future amendments to change Senate rules, which are far
less strict in the use of campaign money for office expenses.
   ``They want to keep their slush funds while posing for
headlines,'' Obey said of senators.
   Obey said the Senate used the same tactic earlier this year, by
overwhelmingly rejecting a proposed 51 percent pay raise for
Congress, while secretly counting on the House to pass an increase.
The pay plan collapsed.
   Rep. Silvio Conte, R-Mass., who offered the House resolution on
mailings to follow the Senate's lead, said he would refuse to sign
the conference report because ``We gave away the store.''
   Conte, documenting what he called abuses of mass mailings, said
that in the 1988 fiscal year, which ended about a month before
congressional elections, the cost of House newsletters rose
steadily as the election approached _ from $5.9 million the first
quarter to $16 million in the last quarter. Senate mass mailings
rose from $3.8 million in the first quarter to $10 million in the
fourth quarter.
   ``We really created a Frankenstein,'' Conte said. ``The only way
we're going to free ourselves from this monster is to cut its head
off ... and use it for something worthwhile.''
   The language on mass mailing would establish separate mass mail
accounts: $54.5 million, or 65 percent of the total, for the
435-member House; and $29.3 million, or 35 percent, for the
100-member Senate. In addition, the provision calls for $31.7
million to cover mailing costs through the end of 1989.
   Currently, there are six mass mailings of newsletters a year,
but they would be reduced to three beginning next Jan. 1. There
would be a two-sheet limit.
</TEXT>
