<FIRST>r a PM-PostalPayments     09-26 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Postal Payments,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carriers to Pay 25 Cents for Misdeliveries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WORTHINGTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Letter carriers here have agreed to pay
25 cents out of their own pockets for each misdelivered piece of
mail.
   The bounty will be paid to residents of this Columbus suburb who
return the wrongly delivered letters.
   ``We're calling it the Worthington Letter Carriers Money Back
Guarantee,'' Michael Newman, a Postal Service spokesman in
Columbus, said today.
   The 60-day trial program along 11 routes is an outgrowth of a
national, voluntary program by the Postal Service and the National
Association of Letter Carriers.
   ``We wanted to indicate to our customers that we were concerned
about getting their mail delivered to them properly, and we wanted
to make sure that we were going to do everything we could in order
to do that,'' Newman said.
   Newman said a similar program in High Point, N.C., operated for
about a year and paid out $26.
   Under the program, which began Monday, carriers will pay for any
misdelivered first-class items that had been properly addressed.
   Customers will be given a form to fill out and an envelope in
which to return the misdelivered mail at no cost.
   About 3,000 to 5,000 customers will be involved in the project
   Newman said the the union would pay for misdeliveries by
part-time or substitute carriers.
</TEXT>
