<FIRST>r a PM-USAirCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0516 09-26 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USAir Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0516,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Evidence of Drug Ingestion in Delayed Tests on USAir Crash Pilots</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with tests showing no drug, alcohol use.
ADDS background on investigation. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Urine samples taken two days after a USAir jet
skidded into the East River contained no sign of drug or alcohol
use by the pilot or co-pilot, prosecutors say.
   The test results were made public by the office of Queens
District Attorney John J. Santucci on Monday, the same day he
announced that a grand jury would look into the crash that killed
two people last week.
   Tests on samples taken from the pilot and co-pilot on Friday
showed no evidence of drugs such as cocaine, heroin or
amphetamines, or alcohol, said Santucci spokesman Richard Piperno.
Results of similar tests by the National Transportation Safety
Board will not be available for several weeks.
   The captain, Michael W. Martin, and co-pilot, Constantine
Kleissas, were criticized by federal officials for failing to
submit to testing immediately after the crash, although they are
not legally required to do so.
   Medical experts said alcohol would not normally show up in urine
samples taken two days after ingestion but that traces of drugs
such as marijuana or cocaine probably would.
   The test means ``that they were free of drugs and or alcohol at
the time that the sample was taken,'' Piperno said today.
   The jet, en route to Charlotte, N.C., skidded into the East
River after the crew tried to abort takeoff at LaGuardia Airport on
Wednesday.
   Investigators said the co-pilot reported he inadvertently
punched a button that cut the throttle, and the pilot told
officials that he aborted takeoff because of a vibration and
because the jet began to veer for some reason.
   The pilots' lawyer, Frederick Hafetz, said the results ``come as
no surprise. We had fully anticipated they would be negative, and
indeed people's observations of the pilots on the night of the
flight was totally consistent with their being in full control of
themselves.''
   Piperno said he also knew of no evidence indicating the men were
under the influence at the time of the crash.
   In announcing the criminal investigation, Santucci said he had
no prospective targets and would not seek specific criminal
charges. Among the things the grand jury would investigate was how
the crew was picked for the flight, he said.
   The two men, flying together for the first time, had been chosen
from a pool of pilots with the least seniority. The co-pilot, who
had flown a Boeing 737-400 only once before on a regular passenger
flight, was attempting his first takeoff in that model with
passengers aboard. Both pilots had been working about 12 hours.
   Santucci's decision to investigate is unusual, if not
unprecedented, airline insiders said.
   ``We're not aware of criminal charges in the past ever being
brought here in the United States against an airline pilot''
following a crash, said John Macor, a spokesman for the Air Line
Pilots Association in Washington.
   Hafetz said he had no comment on the investigation.
   Charges that a grand jury might be asked to consider include
criminally negligent homicide, vehicular manslaughter and leaving
the scene of an accident, according to sources in Santucci's office
who requested anonymity.
   An airplane is considered a vehicle under New York law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890926-0089 </DOCNO>
