<HEAD>Inmates At NYC Jail Riot; No Serious Injuries Reported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officers used tear gas to quell a jail riot
early today and then negotiated an end to a standoff with 150 other
inmates who barricaded themselves in their dorms with piled-up
furniture, officials said.
   Six officers and six inmates were taken to a hospital as a
precaution, but no serious injuries were reported in the uprising
at the 2,700-inmate jail on Rikers Island, said Correction
Department spokeswoman Ruby Ryles.
   The damage was being assessed this morning, she said.
   About 50 inmates set fires and blockaded their dorm with
mattresses, complaining that one of two men removed earlier from
the unit for fighting had been unfairly punished, said Ryles.
   About 3 a.m., officers used tear gas to end the uprising, but
some 150 prisoners in three other dormitories barricaded themselves
in for more than an hour by piling up beds, chairs, tables and
other items, the spokeswoman said.
