<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-USEmigration Bjt   09-26 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-US Emigration, Bjt,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Embassy Setting New Emigration Procedures to Stop Flood</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Embassy officials trying to curtail a
constant line outside the embassy on Tuesday announced new rules on
emigration procedures aimed at lightening the work load in Moscow
and limiting the number of would-be emigrants.
   The announcement was made to an agitated crowd of several
hundred Soviets, who were gathered around the embassy seeking
permission to emigrate or visit the United States. Dozens pushed
and grabbed for the one-sheet explanation of the rules, which take
effect Oct. 1.
   According to the document, applications for emigration now will
have to be sent to Washington instead of being dealt with in Moscow
because of the flood of requests pouring into the embassy here.
   Lines of hundreds of people have been forming around the embassy
every day since Soviet officials began liberalizing emigration
policies last year. There have been reports recently that spaces in
line are going for hundreds of dollars.
   ``The United States will continue to receive applications from
all interested Soviet citizens, but priority in scheduling
interviews will be given to those with close relatives ... who are
citizens or legal residents of the United States, as well as those
of special concern to the United States,'' according to the
document handed out Tuesday.
   ``Many who have no close family ties in the United States will
face long delays and may wish to explore alternative destinations.
Not all those who apply will be given appointments,'' it warned.
   Soviets will be notified by mail from Washington if they are to
be interviewed in the embassy in Moscow.
   Soviets using Israeli visas _ mostly Jews _ will not be able to
apply for entrance to the United States in Rome or Vienna if their
Soviet exit visa is dated after Oct. 1, the document said. Many
Soviet Jews are waiting in those cities for admission to the United
States instead of going to Israel.
   The Geneva-based International Commission for Migration said
more than 30,000 Soviet Jews had arrived at its transit point in
Vienna from January through August.
   The head of the Soviet visa office, Rudolf Kuznetsov, said on
Aug. 22 that 200,000 Soviets are expected to emigrate this year.
Besides the United States, many want to go to West Germany. About
50,000 people, mostly ethnic Germans, had left for West Germany by
the end of August.
   A senior U.S. official in Moscow said earlier this month that
the embassy had received 10,000 new applications in August alone,
adding to a backlog of 32,000 cases.
   ``The number of people applying to go to the states is
skyrocketing and going far beyond the cap on refugees,'' he said.
``The great majority of people leaving cannot qualify under the law
to be refugees ... and most are not claiming to be refugees.''
   Compared to 1988, when 85 percent to 90 percent of the
applicants were Armenians, in August 45 percent of the applicants
were Jews, 35 percent were Armenians, and 10 percent were Russians,
he said. He said 70 percent of the Russians had no relatives at all
in the United States.
   A U.S. official said the embassy will monitor the list of
interviews granted by Washington and the number of people who
appear for an interview to determine whether the Soviet mail system
can be trusted to deliver notification.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890926-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1235EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Hungary 1stLd-Writethru   09-26 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0535,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Passes Liberal Emigration Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs to UPDATE with parliament allowing free
emigration; picks up 5th pvs: The legislators...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parliament today adopted liberal laws
that guarantee free travel abroad and emigration, the first of a
sweeping set of changes intended transform Communist Hungary into a
multi-party democracy.
   The new laws lifted most restrictions on travel, meaning that
Hungarians no longer require permission from authorities for
foreign travel or emigration.
   Hungary's liberal policies in this respect were demonstrated by
a government decision in May to begin removing barbed wire fencing
and other obstacles on its border with Austria.
   This Warsaw Pact country also allowed thousands of East Germans
seeking to emigrate to the West to cross legally into Austria,
angering its hard-line allies.
   The session that opened today is to decide a series of key bills
that are to pave the way for next year's elections in June, the
first free and open multi-party balloting in more than 40 years of
Communist rule.
   The volume of legislation prompted lawmkers to vote for an
extension of the session in October after a two-week break to allow
lawmakers to study the draft laws. The current session was
originally scheduled to end Friday.
   Legislators will have to vote on six key bills, including one on
the functioning of political parties, a new electoral law, the
establishment of a constitutional court and changes in the penal
code.
   The legislators today approved membership of four opposition
members who received a majority at recent by-elections, marking the
first time members of the opposition took their seats in the
Communist-dominated assembly.
   Gabor Roszik, the first opposition member elected in July, was
accompanied to the Parliament building by supporters waving flags.
   ``Democracy has returned to Parliament after a 40-year exile,''
Roszik told the house.
   ``This is one of the most significant steps of the revolution
underway in Hungary, as we move from dictatorial socialism to
democracy,'' Roszik said. ``The millions of Hungarians have never
paid such close attention to our work as they do now.''
   The bills before Parliament this week are designed to bring
legislation in line with preparations for the multi-party
elections, which would be the first since the Communists
consolidated power in 1948.
   More than 70 percent of the 387 members of Parliament are
Communists. So-called independent candidates elected after 1985
when Hungary instituted multi-candidate elections had to be
approved by a Communist-affiliated organization.
   Parliament is also expected to discuss the creation of a post of
president which would replace the current 21-man collective
presidency, and determine the date and form of his election.
   There has been considerable pressure for the president to be
elected before the end of the year to provide political stability
during the transition phase before the elections.
   Hungary, like Warsaw Pact ally Poland, has embraced and in fact
exceeded the liberal reforms and progressive politics encouraged by
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Both nations are seeking closer trade and investment ties to the
West to improve their economies as they pursue social reforms,
moves that have alienated them from such hard-line Warsaw Pact
nations as East Germany and Czechoslovakia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890926-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1236EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Burma     09-26 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burma Sentences Five to Death for Beheadings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military tribunal in Burma has
sentenced five people to death for beheading three people they
wrongly suspected of poisoning drinking water during last year's
pro-democracy uprising, state radio said.
   Rangoon Radio said in a broadcast Monday that two men and one
woman were beheaded at the junction of U Wisara and Shwedagon
Pagoda Roads in Rangoon ``during last year's disturbances.''
   ``The victims were falsely accused of poisoning drinking
water,'' the radio said.
   The report, received in Bangkok on Tuesday, did not give the
date of the incident. But Western news reports at the the time
described the beheadings on Sept. 8 last year, when crowds of up to
a million paraded through Rangoon demanding an end to years of
authoritarian rule.
   Rangoon Radio said the tribunal heard that Ma May Khine ``kicked
the woman accused of poisoning the water and barbarously severed
(her) head.'' Another defendant, Aye Cho, used a sword to behead
one of the men, it said.
   Two others, Nan Lwin and Shwe Toe, helped with the killings and
helped hang the severed heads on a signboard at the road junction,
the report said.
   The fifth convicted, Po Lu, also assisted in the murders,
``posed for pictures with the severed heads, tied one on a bamboo
pole and displayed it by marching along ... and helped burn the
corpses,'' the radio said.
   At the end of last month, a military tribunal in northwestern
Burma sentenced 11 people to death for beheading four policemen,
also during the uprising.
   Last year's demonstrations were crushed after a series of bloody
army clampdowns in which thousands were killed.
   The government has used the sporadic violence that occurred
during the largely peaceful protests to justify its use of force
against dissent, saying the country was on the verge of anarchy. It
continues to rule by martial law.
   Some dissidents have blamed the violence and rumors _ such as
those surrounding the poisoning of drinking water _ on
government-paid provocateurs.
   Western diplomats in Rangoon say several thousand pro-democracy
activists have been arrested since opposition leaders Aung San Suu
Kyi and Tin Oo were placed under house arrest July 19.
</TEXT>
