<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-DisabledProtest 2ndLd-Writethru a0562 09-26 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Disabled Protest, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0562,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disabled Allowed to Spend Night in Federal Building at Bush's Order</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with demonstrators blocking entrances,
federal officials arriving; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `This is ...'; Marca
is cq in 4th graf.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Handicapped people demanding wheelchair lifts on
public buses blocked entrances to a federal building for a second
day today after President Bush let them spend the night rather than
send them out into the rain.
   Two officials of the Urban Mass Transit Administration arrived
with a third, unidentified official just before noon today to meet
with protest leaders.
   But the 80 or so demonstrators, many in wheelchairs, made good
on a vow to block entrances of the main level of the Richard B.
Russell building at noon if their demands were not met.
   The activists began the demonstration Monday, when at least two
dozen chained themselves to doors or blocked exits with their
wheelchairs.
   ``This is a real national effort and we want people to know
about it,'' said Marca Bristo, 36, of Chicago, one of the protest
organizers.
   The demonstrators want a federal order requiring all new public
buses bought with federal funds to be equipped with wheelchair
lifts. Government officials have estimated this would cost $90
million a year.
   Bush intervened Monday night after authorities ejected several
protesters and organizers said they would continue demonstrating
outside, in a cold downpour.
   Gary Cason, regional administrator for the General Services
Administration, said the president ordered that the demonstrators
be brought in out of the rain.
   ``He's concerned about their plight and their safety,'' Cason
said.
   But protest organizer Mike Auberger of Denver, Colo., said his
group, American Disabled for Accessible Public Transportation,
would step up the protest to dispel the notion that Bush is openly
addressing their demands.
   ``The administration, up to now, was willing to throw us out. If
we don't do something, they'll just let us sit here,'' Auberger
said.
   ``We're going to close it back down again. They need to know our
issue isn't going away.''
   ADAPT members are demanding that U.S. Transportation Secretary
Samuel Skinner sign an executive order requiring the lifts. They
said they also want the administration to implement a 1986 law
requiring better disabled access at airports.
   The protesters say they wont't move until Skinner, who visited
Atlanta on Monday for the American Public Transportation
Association's convention, signs the order.
   Cason said no decision had been made as to whether the
protesters would be removed today.
   ``We'll play it as we go,'' he said.
   The demonstrators' blockade near the main entrances to the
building Monday forced employees and others to leave use an exit on
the lower level.
   ADAPT has also been trying to force the installation of lifts on
all new buses through the courts. In Philadelphia, a federal
appeals panel backed their lawsuit, saying federal law requires
lifts on new buses.
   But in July, the full 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
overturned that ruling, saying government officials did not have to
put lifts on all buses if they thought some other method of serving
the handicapped would be better.
   Michael Churchill, an attorney for ADAPT, said the group was
waiting to see what Congress did on the bus issue before deciding
whether to appeal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
