<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt-Mubarak     09-26 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Mubarak,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Seeks U.S. Catalyst Role in Peace Efforts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAURICE GUINDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With growing international prestige,
President Hosni Mubarak goes to the United States this week seeking
American help with an Israeli-Palestinian peace plan and dialogue
he has proposed.
   Mubarak will urge President Bush's administration to take
concrete action instead of just expressing cautious approval, as it
has done so far, Egyptian officials said.
   Egypt wants Washington to nudge Israel's Likud Party, led by
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, into accepting the dialogue and a
10-point guideline plan, according to Egyptian officials speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   Mubarak arrives in New York on Thursday and will meet Bush in
Washington on Monday. Egyptian officials call the Washington talks
crucial.
   ``It's crucial in the sense that it may make or break current
peace efforts involving the dialogue proposal, Israel's plan for
Palestinian elections and Mubarak's 10-point formula to spruce up
that plan,'' a senior government official said.
   Osama el-Baz, Mubarak's political adviser, told reporters that
Mubarak will talk with Bush ``to crystallize an American position
bolstering Egypt's efforts to open a Palestinian-Israeli dialogue.''
   A government official, who asked that his name be withheld for
diplomatic reasons, spoke bluntly. ``We want the United States to
step in with its full clout and put pressure on Israel.''
   Israel's Labor Party, junior partner in Shamir's Cabinet
coalition, generally approves Mubarak's suggestion of an
Israeli-Palestinian dialogue in Cairo to discuss Palestinian
elections in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Shamir has rejected Mubarak's key ideas in public remarks, but
his divided Cabinet is to take a final decision next month.
   In May, Shamir proposed elections to choose representatives to
negotiate with Israel on interim self-rule for the two territories,
where about 1.7 million Palestinians live. In July, Mubarak put 10
questions to Israel, urging affirmative answers that would make the
election proposal more palatable to the Palestinians.
   The Mubarak approach would guarantee freedom of the balloting
under international supervision and allow 140,000 Palestinian
residents of Israeli-annexed East Jerusalem to vote. It also would
link the election to an eventual final settlement based on Israel
giving up occupied territory for peace.
   Mubarak has said Palestine Liberation Organization leader Yasser
Arafat accepts the Egyptian blueprint. But the PLO, which wants an
official Israeli stand first, has delayed an official position
pending a meeting of its Central Council in mid-October.
   Mubarak, whose peacemaking efforts have turned Cairo into a
diplomatic beehive, has seen his stature grow considerably in the
Arab world in the past two years.
   Most Arab countries that broke with Egypt over its 1979 peace
treaty with Israel have restored diplomatic relations, and Cairo
regained its Arab League membership in May after a 10-year
suspension.
   In February, Mubarak arranged for visiting Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze to meet separately in Cairo with
Arafat and Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens.
   During his New York stop, Mubarak will thrash out his and
Israel's peace ideas at meetings with Shevardnadze, Arens and
Finance Minister Shimon Peres of Israel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
