<FIRST>d a PM-PhoneOutage     09-26 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Outage,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>12,000 Lose Service in Alleged Sabotage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREEPORT, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals sliced a cable inside a manhole,
cutting service to 12,000 telephone lines in what New York
Telephone Co. said today was the worst case of sabotage since a
strike against its parent began Aug. 5.
   ``Because of the way it was done, it could take several days to
restore service to everyone,'' said spokesman Tony Pappas.
   About 4,000 suburban New York City telephone customers plus
8,000 customers with data lines, such as computer services and
burglar alarm companies, lost service, he said.
   Nassau County police Officer John Lambert said the cable was cut
Monday night. Pappas said most of the lines cut were copper, and
crews will have to go through neighboring manholes and break
through walls to run new cable.
   ``You have to have a special tool to lift the manhole cover, and
then have cable cutters,'' he said. ``It was a professional job.''
   New York Telephone says it has sustained 325 acts of vandalism
statewide affecting about 75,000 customers since the Communications
Workers went on strike against NYNEX.
   A union spokeswoman did not immediately return a telephone call.
</TEXT>
