<FIRST>u w PM-US-Philippines     09-26 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Philippines,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Condemns Philippine Killings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Quayle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department today condemned the
murder of two American civilians in the Philippines, calling it a
``cowardly act of terrorism.''
   The civilians, whose names have been withheld pending
notification of their relatives, were killed in an ambush on a road
about 50 miles north of Manila shortly before Vice President Dan
Quayle arrived in the country to talk about the future of U.S.
bases there.
   The Americans worked for Ford Aerospace Corp., a contractor at
Camp O'Donnell, a U.S.-run communications facility. The road on
which the Americans were attacked runs between the camp and the
U.S. Clark Air Base.
   Richard Boucher, a State Department spokesman, said in a
statement that the civilian contractors of the Air Force ``were
murdered in a carefully planned ambush while driving in Tarlac
province.'' The ambush ``evidently required a certain amount of
preparation,'' he said.
   ``We deplore this senseless and cowardly act of terrorism,'' he
said. ``Acts like this will not deter us in our resolve to support
the democratic government in the Philippines.''
   In the Philippines, local authorities said the Americans' car
had been blocked by a dump truck and the jeep. Gunmen jumped out of
the jeep, sprayed their car with semi-automatic weapons fire and
then opened the car door and fired into the victims' bodies.
   The military believes the assailants were Communist rebels, who
operate in the Clark area, the officials said. Boucher said U.S.
authorities have joined local officials in the investigation.
</TEXT>
