<FIRST>u i PM-Refugees 3rdLd-Writethru a0545 09-26 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugees, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0545,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans Begin Returning to East Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with some Germans leaving embassy;
picks up 3rd pvs: Vogel is...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MANFRED HEES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An East German emissary today told
East Germans holed up in the West German Embassy that they can
legally emigrate to the West but first must return home, a
spokesmen for the refugees said.
   Wolfgang Vogel arrived today to speak to representatives of
about 1,200 East Germans who have crowded the garden of the West
German Embassy in hopes of obtaining safe passage to the West.
   After meeting with Vogel, between 50 and 60 East Germans boarded
a bus that reportedly took them to a Prague railroad station for
their journey back to East Germany. The others, however, remained
in the embassy quarters and it was unclear if they refused the East
German offer.
   Vogel is an East Berlin lawyer who has close contacts with the
East German leadership.
   Refugees who took part in the negotiations told reporters
waiting outside the embassy that Vogel gave them a personal
guarantee they could emigrate once they returned home.
   Already, more than 20,000 East Germans have fled to West Germany
via Hungary, which incensed East Germany's Communist leaders when
it opened its border to the West on Sept. 11.
   In Warsaw, Poland, dozens of other East Germans arrived Monday
outside the closed West German Embassy to seek passage to the West.
Some said they swam rivers by night or walked through forests on
the Polish-East German border.
   In Prague, a Western reporter on Monday afternoon witnessed some
40 new arrivals scale the 7-foot fence of the West Germany Embassy
in the conspicuous absence of Czechoslovak police who had earlier
patrolled the street outside, urging reporters to leave.
   By nightfall, the number of East Germans holed up inside the
compound had reached around 980, refugees reported.
   Some said they'd had to spend Sunday night in the open air for
lack of Red Cross tents, but new tents arrived during the day.
   In the area near the embassy, police have towed away all East
German cars.
   ``The situation is getting ever more difficult,'' said a
40-year-old East German, who, like all the others, asked for
anonymity.
   He said that his wife and children had successfully made it to
the West via Hungary, but he himself was intercepted by
Czechoslovak border guards as he drove in his car toward the
Czechoslovak-Hungarian frontier.
   Other would-be refugees were also caught.
   Fearing imprisonment at home, he told a reporter, ``Where else
should I have gone? The Bonn Embassy was the last way out.''
   Those camping in the embassy garden are mostly people aged
30-40, but there are also 200 children including several infants.
There was hardly any space left to put up new tents.
   In Warsaw, at least 300 East Germans are being accommodated,
either in a group of West German Embassy houses in the villa
district of Saska Kepa or in a park-surrounded former seminary in
Tarchomin, just outside Warsaw.
   The embassy was closed to the public last week to prevent more
refugees from entering.
   The East Germans were anxious to be allowed onto embassy grounds
on Monday, but guards stood inside the locked gates. However,
embassy officers after making an announcement in the afternoon
could be seen escorting small groups away from the embassy,
presumably to a shelter for the night.
   A tall young East German who identified himself as Paul, 23,
described his escape from his homeland.
   He said he blew up an air mattress, placed his belongings on it
and then swam with the mattress across the Neisse River that forms
the Polish-East German border in southwest Poland.
</TEXT>
