<FIRST>r a PM-SchoolBoycott     09-26 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Boycott,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agreement Ends Boycott Over School's Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black parents agreed to send their
children to class today for the first time in two weeks after
reaching a compromise over the school board's renaming of Dr.
Martin Luther King Jr. Elementary.
   Under the agreement, the school will be known officially as West
Lowndes Elementary, but the building itself will be named for the
slain civil rights leader.
   The compromise was approved Monday by the Lowndes County School
Board, the parents association and the county's NAACP.
   Officials said today that 350 students showed up out of an
enrollment of 425. Only 32 attended on Sept. 12, the first day of
the boycott.
   Last spring, the old school board, composed of three whites and
two blacks, voted to name the new school for King. But a newly
elected board with only one black member designated it Motley
Elementary, for the land's former owner, saying it wanted a name
that was not racially identifiable.
   The school is more than 95 percent black.
</TEXT>
