<FIRST>u a PM-ZsaZsaTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0464 09-26 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Zsa Zsa Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0464,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zsa Zsa: `Gorgeous' Cop Made Me Late</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Gabor's late arrival; PICKS
UP 8th graf pvs, `That man ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zsa Zsa Gabor arrived for Day 12 of
her cop-slapping trial complaining she was late because the
``gorgeous'' policeman who arrested her in June was working a speed
trap on Sunset Boulevard.
   ``Officer (Paul) Kramer made me late. He stopped the traffic
with a radar gun. There he was, looking his gorgeous self, with
radar,'' Miss Gabor told reporters when she reached the courthouse
at 9 a.m.
   Municipal Judge Charles Rubin on Monday had declared the trial
was taking too long and ordered that sessions start an hour early,
at 8:45 a.m.
   The former Hungarian beauty queen is on trial on misdemeanor
charges stemming from her June 14 arrest by Kramer, who stopped her
Rolls-Royce for having an expired registration.
   Miss Gabor said her mother, Jolie, and older sister Magda would
be in courtroom for the afternoon session. She said she spent extra
time picking an outfit to please her.
   ``Mother's very critical,'' Miss Gabor said. ``They're going to
sit here for support.''
   The trial, now in its third week, has cost taxpayers an
estimated $22,000 and provided fodder for journalists around the
world. They have dutifully reported Miss Gabor's sometimes
outrageous statements, which at one point drew a reprimand from the
judge for failing to heed his gag order.
   On Monday, Miss Gabor retracted an out-of-court remark that she
was afraid to go to jail because lesbians were there.
   ``I have nothing against gays or lesbians. I have lots of gay
boys working for me,'' the actress told reporters. ``I got letter
from the lesbians and gay association. They are going to boycott me
because I said there are lesbians in jail.''
   The trial originally was expected to last a week. Defense
attorney William Graysen said new witnesses located over the
weekend could extend it until Friday.
   In court, a defense witness Monday supported Miss Gabor's
account that she slapped Kramer in self-defense.
   ``That man was after blood I think,'' said David Katzman, a
free-lance screenwriter who has written for ``Knots Landing'' and
``Dallas.''
   Katzman said he stopped his car when he noticed the unusual
sight of a policeman pulling over a white Rolls-Royce Corniche, and
became concerned as he watched.
   ``The lady looked as if she was going to be threatened and as
though she would be hurt,'' he testified.
   Miss Gabor could receive up to 18 months in jail if convicted of
misdemeanor battery on a police officer, disobeying an officer's
orders, driving with an expired license and having an open
container of alcohol in her car.
</TEXT>
