<FIRST>r a AM-AlaskaBenefit     09-26 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alaska Benefit,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Music Stars to Raise Money for Alaskan Oil Spill Cleanup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERA GROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country musician Russell Smith says he
organized a benefit concert to aid cleanup of the Alaskan oil spill
because he believes Exxon has reneged on its promise to restore the
area.
   Besides Smith, other performers slated to appear Wednesday at
Nashville's Center Stage include Rodney Crowell, J.C. Crowley, Guy
Clark, Vince Gill, Maura O'Connell, Jonelle Mosser, New Grass
Revival and Alaska's Hobo Jim.
   Smith, whose new album is titled ``This Little Town,'' said
Monday he was moved by the plight of the wildlife and people living
along the hundreds of miles of shoreline soiled by the spill.
Nearly 11 million gallons of oil poured into Prince William Sound
after the tanker Exxon Valdez struck a reef on March 24.
   The bodies of more than 30,000 birds and about 1,000 animals
have been found. Biologists say those figures probably represent
only 5 percent to 10 percent of the deaths caused by the spill.
   ``When I found out about this I became concerned, more than
concerned. I became extremely angry about it,'' Smith said. ``Their
economy was shot to hell because of this. Everyone needed money so
bad. Fishermen have lost their boats because they missed the
fishing season.''
   Exxon spent at least $1.2 billion on the cleanup before stopping
its efforts earlier this month because of worsening weather and
dwindling daylight.
   Alaska Gov. Steve Cowper said the state would conduct a $21
million program ``to continue cleanup work left by Exxon.''
   Exxon has said it will re-evaluate the shorelines next spring
and decide then whether to resume the cleanup on a large scale.
   ``One of the main things we are trying to do is keep this before
the public's attention to keep pressure on Exxon to keep their
promise and clean it up,'' Smith said.
   The concert is expected to raise $16,000 to $20,000, 95 percent
of which will go to the Prince William Sound Cleanup and
Rehabilitation Fund administered by the Alaska Conservation
Foundation. Only the cost of printing and selling the
$20-per-person tickets was not donated, Smith said.
   The money will be used to help wildlife and clean the area. The
Alaska Conservation Foundation is a 10-year-old, non-profit group
that pays for environmental education and policy studies.
   Rounding up artists for the concert wasn't difficult, Smith said.
   ``Most of the people I have asked are pretty much concerned
people, concerned about the environment, period,'' he said.
</TEXT>
