<SECOND>AM-BRF--Sacred Statue,0169</SECOND>
<HEAD>University of Maine to Offer to Return Sacred Indian Statue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORONO, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Maine is offering to
return to the Zuni Indians a statue that the university museum
displayed for a year before learning that the tribe considers it
offensive to display the sacred piece.
   University trustees voted Monday to authorize return of the
statue to the New Mexico tribe and officials said Tuesday the
university will contact tribal leaders to make the necessary
arrangements.
   ``It's up to the Zuni Nation to come and pick it up,'' said
university arts publicist Maria Tijan-Wieck.
   The university's Hudson Museum placed the statue in storage
about two years ago after a visitor from the Southwest told
officials about its significance. Since then, officials said they
have learned that other museums also have voluntarily returned Zuni
statues to the tribe.
   The wooden carving of a male figure is about 32 inches tall and
is believed to be less than 100 years old.
</TEXT>
