<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1531EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolFire     09-26 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Fire,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmen Guarding School Officials, Facilities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAZLEHURST, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are guarding public buildings
following a week-long series of suspicious fires and telephone
threats against schools and school officials.
   ``This might be related to our attempt to break up a drug
pipeline at the school earlier this year,'' said School
Superintendent George French. ``There was an attempt (by drug
dealers) to get a foothold in it, and we've worked very hard to
eliminate drugs,'' he said.
   French also speculated the fires could be reprisals against
administrators for the expulsion of a gun-toting 14-year-old male
student several weeks ago.
   ``We had a student expelled because he brought his father's gun
to school with the intent to kill another student,'' he said. He
declined to identify the minor.
   French said the student fired one shot that hit a portable
classroom.
   ``The consensus is that the fires are all connected,'' said
state chief deputy fire marshal John Chamblee of Jackson.
   ``It's giving us indications that someone has a vendetta or a
loose screw,'' he said of the investigation, adding that his office
will post a $1,000 reward.
   Monday morning, someone pushed a burning wad of paper behind a
ceiling tile at the county's temporary welfare office downtown. The
fire did little damage and was being investigated as arson, said
Hazlehurst Public Safety Director Thomas Quarles.
   Another fire early Sunday gutted a vacant building being rented
by Woodrow Purcer, a candidate in a special election for
supervisor, Quarles said.
   Quarles said the fire is believed to be also arson-related.
   Purcer said: ``It had nothing to do with the election; it just
happened.''
   Four fires set at Hazlehurst Elementary School and Hazlehurst
High School early Thursday and a fire that demolished the Copiah
County Welfare Office early Friday were under investigation as
arson, police said. Authorities said there are no suspects.
   French said he received a series of telephone threats Sunday
night from a woman who threatened to ``destroy the schools'' and
kill him.
   ``This is the first time that I have confirmed that this is a
vendetta,'' French said, adding that he believes the threats and
fires are the result of a grudge against the school administration.
   ``In the second call, they said for me to meet them somewhere,
and they were going to kill me ... nothing but me,'' he said. ``And
in the third call, they said they were going to kill me and just
hung up.''
   A bomb squad combed the campuses and the athletic field for
explosives before a home football game on Friday, French said.
   French said authorities are working around the clock to protect
the campuses. And Quarles said city and county law officers are
guarding public buildings from dusk to dawn.
</TEXT>
