<HEAD>Fire Breaks Out at Luxurious Beachfront Hotel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE casualties; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire spread through several floors of a luxury
beachfront hotel Tuesday and injured 11 people, officials said.
   Guests at the Dan Caesarea Hotel, on the Mediterranean south of
Haifa, were forced to flee the eight-story building. The blaze
damaged 50 rooms, said Fire Chief Yossi Levy.
   Levy said the fire started on the second floor and quickly
spread through the building to the fifth story. He said the cause
was under investigation.
   The injuries were described as light.
   The Dan Caesarea Hotel has a five-star rating and is next to the
Roman ruins of Caesarea, the Romans' capital in Palestine for about
500 years.
   Nine workers and two Israeli tourists were injured in the hotel,
a spokesman at Hillel Yaafe Hospital in nearby Hadera said. Most of
the injured suffered from smoke inhalation.
