<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1533EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-SaveChanute 1stLd-Writethru a0433 09-26 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Save Chanute, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0433,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rural County Calls on Capitol Muscle to Save Doomed Military Base</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout with defeat of audit provision.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rural roads of Illinois are a world away
from the shiny floors of the Capitol, but folks who want to save a
military base understand one thing about Washington: clout can
carry a price.
   So they went after some, but lost a vote in the Senate, anyway.
   Residents of Champaign County, population 150,000, hired an
influential lobbying firm _ Patton, Boggs and Blow _ to help them
as senators considered a $288 billion defense bill.
   They hoped the Senate would retain a provision in the giant
defense bill ordering an audit of the costs of closing the bases.
But the provision was defeated today, 86-14.
   The version of the 1990 defense bill approved by the
Appropriations Committee said no base could be closed unless an
audit found that the costs of dismantling it would be recovered
within six years.
   The county and the cities of Champaign and Rantoul chipped in
$30,000, and readers responding to a full-page advertisement in the
local newspaper also sent contributions. Businesses, aware of
Chanute Air Force Base's impact on the area's fragile economy,
joined the effort, too.
   ``The role of our lobbyists is to do whatever they can _ that is
fair and appropriate _ to turn this thing around,'' says Carl
Webber, an attorney and chairman of the Urbana Chamber of Commerce.
   ``When you consider the unfairness of the decision and include
with that the phenomenal impact on this whole area, the amount
we're spending on lobbyists is a drop in a bucket,'' said Webber.
   ``We're not ever going to say die.''
   The decision to hire a lobbyist has sparked something of a
debate among lawmakers who represent the area.
   Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., said he doubted it would make much
difference.
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., seeking re-election, said the Chanute
forces need all the help they can get, adding, ``I wish we lived in
a pure society where no one would have to hire lobbyists. There is
no question a lobbyist can do some good.''
   Some in Congress, however, wondered if it was too late.
   ``We are just concerned with the ability of paid lobbyists to
turn a bad situation around in the bottom of the ninth inning,''
said David Almy, spokesman for Rep. Edward Madigan, R-Ill., whose
district includes Chanute. ``As paid advocates of our constituents
we don't want to see them getting less than their money's worth.''
Madigan favors saving the base.
   Lobbyist Tom Boggs, son of Rep. Lindy Boggs, D-La., did not
return phone calls requesting comment on the lobbying effort.
   Chanute AFB, about 120 miles south of Chicago, has about 8,500
military and civilian personnel and provides training in such
fields as firefighting and aircraft and missile maintenance.
   Last December, when an independent commission said the
government should close 86 bases and realign 59 others, Chanute was
on the list, cited for a shortage of buildings and recreational
facilities and inadequate housing.
   The conclusion by the Commission on Base Closing and Realignment
stunned many lawmakers, especially Madigan, who said the government
had spent $150 million on new buildings there during the last seven
years.
   Chanute defenders claim the commission made glaring errors. A
university study said closing the base could devastate the area.
   ``Hiring those lobbyists doesn't do anything more,'' Dixon said.
``Everything they talked to me about I've done.''
   But Dixon added: ``The firm is a good one. ... When you're
fighting for your life, you do everything you can do. If you live
in the city of Rantoul and you have a business, this is a serious
thing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
