<SECOND>PM-Colombia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0479,0793</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb In Tourist City Kills Two, Guerrillas Say Pardon Traffickers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with one graf to raise reference to assassination; picks
up 2nd graf: The military...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge in the city of Medellin dropped
assassination and other charges against the two reputed leaders of
Colombia's international drug network because of lack of evidence,
a Colombia newspaper reported today.
   The military, meanwhile, imposed heavy security on the Caribbean
tourist city of Cartagena today after another bomb blast blamed on
drug traffickers killed two people and injured one at a Hilton
hotel.
   The newspaper El Tiempo said a Medellin judge on Monday dropped
charges against Pablo Emilio Escobar Gaviria and Jose Gonzalo
Rodriguez Gacha, alleged leaders of the Medellin-based drug
operation that supplies most of the cocaine in the United States.
   The two men are on the U.S. Justice Department list of 12 key
drug figures wanted for prosecution in the United States.
   The president of Colombia's House of Representatives, Norberto
Morales, said last week that the two men contacted him and said
they would be willing to move their drug operations out of Colombia
in return for an end to the government's crackdown on trafficking.
   Escobar and Rodriguez had been charged with complicity in the
kidnapping last year of Andres Pastrana, who was a candidate for
mayor of Bogota. Pastrana was freed in an army raid and went on to
be elected mayor of the capital.
   Escobar and Rodriguez also were charged with planning the
assassination of Colombia's attorney general, Carlos Hoyos, on Jan.
25 in Medellin.
   El Tiempo said Judge Francisco Cardenas cited lack of evidence
in dropping the charges against the two men. None of the reputed
leaders of Colombia's drug operations has ever been prosecuted.
   The dropping of charges has no effect on U.S. extradition orders.
   Also today, a Cabinet minister was to meet with representatives
of the country's 4,600 judges in an effort to head off a strike
protesting what the judges call inadequate government protection
from drug gangs.
   Meanwhile, a guerrilla group that is about to sign a peace
agreement with the government of President Virgilio Barco said drug
traffickers should be pardoned, daily newspapers reported.
   The April 19 Movement, known as M-19, reportedly issued a
communique at its base camp saying peace talks should be expanded
to include the drug traffickers.
   The traffickers declared war on the Colombian government after
the government launched a crackdown following the assassination of
a leading presidential candidate, Luis Carlos Galan, on Aug. 18.
   The guerrilla communique was signed by the rebel group's chiefs
of staff, Carlos Pizarro Leon-Gomez, Antonio Navarro Wolf, Otty
Patino and German Rojas Nino, the newspapers El Espectador and El
Tiempo said.
   The signing of a peace agreement by the guerrillas and the
government has been postponed each of the last two days due to
last-minute changes in the agreement. Pardoning the traffickers is
not one of the guerillas' demands, the newspapers said.
   The news conference was held at the guerrilla base camp in the
tiny village of Santo Domingo in the Andes mountains in southwest
Colombia.
   The April 19 Movement takes its name after the date of a 1970
presidential election that dissidents said was fraudulent.
   The group seized Colombia's Justice Palace in Bogota in 1985.
Ninety-five people were killed, most in an army assault that ended
the takeover.
   There are six guerrilla groups in Colombia with an estimated
10,000 combatants. The government is not negotiating with any other
guerrilla group.
   Colombian marines, army troops and national police patrolled
Cartagena today, searching cars at roadblocks and frisking
pedestrians, said Col. Luis Herrera, chief of the national police
in Cartagena.
   The dead at the hotel were Colombian doctors attending a medical
convention, Herrera said.
   He said no one claimed responsibility for the blast.
   The hotel bomb and another that exploded at a Cartagena bank
Monday were the first bombings in that city since the drug war
began. One person was injured by the bomb Monday night at the bank,
Herrera said.
   A third bomb exploded Monday night in Bogota at a government
electric company's billing office, the national police said. No
injuries were reported.
   Many of the bombings since mid-August have been against
government-owned banks and utilities. The majority owner of the
Cartagena Hilton is the Colombian government's National Tourism
Council.
   The Hilton's 1,500 guests were evacuated to other Cartagena
hotels, Col. Herrera said.
   Thousands of U.S., Canadian and other foreign tourists visit
Cartagena and its beaches each year. The city also is a regular
stop for Caribbean cruise ships.

</TEXT>
