<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--MinutemanLaunch     09-26 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Minuteman Launch,0142</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Makes Successful Minuteman Test Launch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANDENBERG AIR FORCE BASE, Calif (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old ICBM
blasted off Tuesday in the predawn sky for a 30-minute test flight
of the Minuteman 3 missile system, the Air Force said.
   The missile delivered unarmed re-entry vehicles to a target
4,200 miles out in the Pacific. The flight ended with the vehicles
splashing down in a missile range in the Marshall Islands.
   The launch, visible to a wide area of California, was a test of
a missile taken from the Strategic Air Command inventory of
operational intercontinental ballistic missiles.
   ``It was a successful launch,'' said base spokesman Ernest
Dawson. ``The two unarmed re-entry vehicles came down without a
hitch.''
   It was the 140th launch in a series of Strategic Air Command
tests of the Minuteman 3 system.
