<FIRST>r i AM-AuschwitzConvent     09-26 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auschwitz Convent,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Monastery Vandalized to Protest Auschwitz Convent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vandals damaged the remains of a 13th-century
Carmelite monastery in northern Israel, apparently to protest a
controversial Carmelite convent near the Auschwitz death camp in
Poland, an official said Tuesday.
   Shalom Yankelevitch, commissioner of antiquities for the city of
Haifa, said the vandalism followed reports that Jewish religious
extremists had threatened Carmelite nuns carrying out an
archaeological dig at the monastery.
   The vandalism was discovered last week.
   Sister Damien, a Carmelite nun from Salt Lake City who is
leading the dig, told Israel television her order has always
opposed having nuns pray at the Roman Catholic convent on the edge
of Auschwitz.
   ``So for people to hurt our ruins here to try to make the
sisters come out, they are hurting the people who are trying to get
(the nuns) out,'' she said. Jewish leaders say the convent, with
its 12-foot-high cross, is offensive because of the presence of
Christian symbols at a place where 2.5 million Jews were killed by
the Nazis in World War II.
   Yankelevitch said the damage to the convent near Haifa came
after an article appeared in a local newspaper saying anonymous
religious groups demanded the nuns delay their dig until the
convent at Auschwitz is moved.
   The vandals caused extensive damage, Yankelevitch said.
   ``They toppled the entrance arch into the...cathedral, and the
arch leading to the 2nd floor of a sideyard, and stone steps. All
this from the 13th century was damaged and broken,'' he said.
   A group of American archaelogists has been excavating for two
years at the one-acre site on biblical Mount Carmel.
   The dig has uncovered new parts of the well-preserved Carmelite
cathedral and a fortress and ancient water system that are part of
an entire monastery complex.
   The Carmelite nuns are trying to prove that the site dates back
to the 5th century, which would predate by 100 years any other
Christain order on Mount Carmel.
   Mount Carmel is the spiritual center of Carmelites throughout
the world, and Carmelites here have written letters to Israeli
newspapers calling for moving the convent from Auschwitz. Some have
traveled to Auschwitz to press for transferring the nuns.
   Yankelevitch said he believed there was a connection between the
vandalism and threats by religious groups, but he did not rule out
other possibilities. The investigation is in police hands, he said.
   The damage was reported as the controversy over the convent in
Auschwitz seemed to be easing. Pope John Paul II said last week
that he believed the nuns should be moved to an interfaith prayer
center to be built in accordance with a 1987 agreement between
Jewish and Catholic officials.
   The statement overcame opposition by Polish primate Jozef Glemp
and Polish Catholics, who have argued the nuns should be allowed to
remain because they cause no harm and because many Christians also
were killed at Auschwitz.
   In the Netherlands, a Dutch Catholic University on Tuesday
canceled an invitation to Glemp, citing what it called his
``harrowing'' anti-Jewish statements.
   The Catholic University in Nijmegen, in the eastern Netherlands,
said: ``The (university) board is aware of Cardinal Glemp's
statement's on the Jews and the Jewish people ... and distances
itself emphatically from those statements.''
   In an Aug. 26 sermon, Glemp accused Jews of provoking
anti-Semitism in Poland and of speaking to the Poles as ``a nation
elevated over all others.''
</TEXT>
