<FIRST>u a AM-CityHermits Bjt   09-26 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-City Hermits, Bjt,0838</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sister's Death Brings Men Out of Urban Cave</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When John Ring showed up at his corner grocery,
singing ``I'm Just Wild About Harry'' in praise of his favorite
cat, it marked his chief contact with the world for the day. His
brother, Vincent, was never seen at all.
   It was only when their equally reclusive sister, Marie, died
last week that the brothers were delivered from a life in a filthy
home without running water or electricity. But now they face an
uncertain future.
   Said Matthew Ryan, a neighbor since the Rings moved to the
working-class Boston neighborhood in the 1950s: ``I couldn't
believe it. Who could get by today without electricity and gas and
water? ... I would have helped them, but they weren't people who
wanted you to get involved.''
   Gerri Abban, the cashier at nearby Bell's Market, says the
plight of the Rings was obvious but the best way to help them was
not.
   The market's owner since 1956, Matthew Cohen, gave John
discounts and looked the other way when one of his checks bounced.
But the Rings would not let anyone in the house, and social workers
and priests responded to Ms. Abban's pleas for help by noting that
the family had a right to privacy.
   ``I sold them charcoal in the winter so they could heat the
house,'' Ms. Abban said. ``I sold them rubbing alcohol, five
bottles at a time, so they could cook. I sold them bottle after
bottle of Anacin because they'd get wicked headaches from the smell
in the house. Paper plates, paper cups, bottled water. It was
unbelievable.''
   The isolation ended last week when John, 59, called police to
report that his 58-year-old sister's pulse was weak. Police said
they arrived to find her dead, and John and 62-year-old Vincent in
poor mental condition.
   The brothers refused to leave the house, though it reeked of
waste from the Rings and their two dozen cats. They were sent to
Boston City Hospital for evaluation, and a hospital spokeswoman
would say only that they were in stable condition.
   In an interview published Tuesday, John Ring said neither he,
his brother nor his sister had worked since the 1950s or early
'60s, choosing instead to live with their parents, who died more
than a decade ago.
   ``The cats took all our money ... cost us $60 a week worth of
cat food. That's why we couldn't fix the place up,'' Ring said.
``But we're going to now.''
   Asked why he didn't accept help, Ring said: ``I didn't want to
bother anybody. But pretty soon Vincent and I will be well again
and we'll go back and fix the house up. I'm sure that everything
will be fine as soon as we get out of the hospital.''
   City officials say however that the house is in such bad shape
it has been condemned. And the Animal Rescue League came for the
cats.
   Cohen, proprietor of Bell's since 1956, said the Rings didn't
have much, but they received some sort of veterans assistance and
weren't penniless. They paid with personal checks that occasionally
bounced, and Cohen gave them unofficial discounts.
   ``I'm not saying how many (checks bounced),'' Cohen said.
``Let's just say I've got a few in my file.''
   ``If John didn't take his medication, he went wild,'' Cohen
said. ``When he'd come down to the store to buy, he'd stuff his
pockets, he'd throw things around and yell at people. We understood
him. We did the best we could. We got him home.''
   Neighbors said John and his sister went to church each Sunday.
Cohen recalled Marie as ``a very fine lady, always well-spoken. She
seemed to be well-read and her whole life was taking care of her
two brothers. It's a mystery to me why, but she did it.''
   As for the other brother, ``I don't know anything about
Vincent,'' Cohen said. ``I saw the man once in a flashing instant
when I went to the house.'' John Ring said his brother had been
wounded in World War II.
   Cohen gave up trying to understand why the Rings lived the way
they did. ``You had a good daddy. I had a good daddy,'' he said.
``We can't all be lucky.''
   ``Everybody has a right to their privacy. It was my business and
it wasn't my business. I sent a plumber up there, I sent an
electrician, and they couldn't get in.''
   Ryan, a retired union leader, said that he thought Vincent had
died back in the early 1970s. Then some years ago, a fire broke out
on the street, and he saw a man with a beard down to his belt and a
blanket around him.
   ``I said, `Who is that?' And someone said, `That's Vincent.' I
never believed there was (a third person) in there.''
</TEXT>
