<FIRST>u a AM-Kiss-OffContest 1stLd-Writethru a0662 09-26 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kiss-Off Contest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Couples Agree to Divvy Up $10,000 Prize in Kissing Contest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to CORRECT to Tuesday.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto covering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three couples have been declared winners in
the first annual Great American Kiss-Off, but their lips are sealed
about what they'll take home for their efforts.
   The six contestants agreed to divvy up the $10,000 top prize
after smooching for 42 days then hiring a lawyer to legally unlock
their lips.
   ``I'm just glad it's over,'' Fernando Gonzales said Tuesday, one
day after all parties embraced the pact.
   He and his wife, Karen, were declared the official first-place
finishers after they and two other couples outlasted 11 other pairs
who entered the contest sponsored by a furniture company. The
company agreed to let the three top couples split the $10,000 as
they pleased and without revealing how.
   ``We thought it was going to be a two-week thing, but it turned
into a marathon,'' said Gonzales. ``I'm recovered now. But it still
feels like I'm kissing. ... It's like when you've been wearing a
hat for four or five weeks and then take it off. The hat still
feels like it's on.''
   But Gonzales, 39, said he still kissed his 36-year-old wife and
mother of their five children good night.
   ``I'm not tired of kissing her,'' he said. ``I think everyone
decided we should be the winners because they realized we could go
on the longest.''
   Gonzales, who is unemployed, said he survived financially
because he owned a tile fitting business in California before
moving to Fernley, Nev., in 1985.
   Reno attorney Pat Cashill said he was hired by parents of the
other two couples in their late teens and early 20s to help end the
contest so their children could get on with their lives.
   ``These people were really caught up in a horrible situation,''
Cashill said. ``It was like they were in bondage. They wouldn't
quit; $10,000 is a lot of money.''
   Under the agreement, the Gonzales couple got the deed to an
Idaho time-share condominium, which was the first-place prize along
with the money.
   The declared second-place finishers and winners of an
expenses-paid trip to Mexico were Lloyd and Laura Gubler of Reno.
Bret Watson and Lori Block of Reno claimed the third-place prize of
new living room furniture.
   The pact to end the Kiss-Off began developing Friday and the
contest was suspended pending the outcome of negotiations.
   Butch Lynn, a publicist for the Kiss-Off, said the furniture
company was a bit disappointed in the outcome of the contest.
   ``It was fairly anticlimactic,'' Lynn said. ``We were hoping
there would be a big winner and a ceremony with champagne to hand
out the $10,000 check.''
   Gubler expects to go back to his father's auto body shop, while
Watson will resume his career as a financial planner and Ms. Block
will look for a new job, having lost hers at a bank, Lynn said.
   Contest organizers thought the competition would last only about
two weeks, but relatively easy rules allowed the contest to
continue.
   Couples had to kiss for 12 hours each day, from 9 a.m. to 9
p.m., in the furniture store's parking lot, with five-minute breaks
each hour. On Aug. 26, three competing couples, including the
Gublers, married in a triple wedding ceremony.
</TEXT>
