<UNK>Father's Will Says Zola Budd Unwelcome at His Funeral</UNK>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The slain father of track star
Zola Budd said in his will that his three daughters were not
welcome at his funeral, which was scheduled for Wednesday, the
independent South African Press Association reported.
   Frank Budd, who had been estranged from his family for several
years, was fatally shot Thursday at a farmhouse outside the central
city of Bloemfontein where he lived alone. A man doing construction
work on the farm is being held in connection with the killing.
   Budd's fomer wife, Tossie, and their son, Quintus, were expected
to be at the funeral, but it was not known if Ms. Budd and her
sisters would attend, according to the news agency.
   Budd, 59, did not attend Ms. Budd's April 15 wedding in
Bloemfontein, saying he was not invited.
   Ms. Budd left South Africa in 1984 and was hurriedly granted a
British passport so she could compete in the Summer Olympics in Los
Angeles.
   South Africa is barred from the Olympics and most international
competition because of its apartheid policies of racial segregation.
   In the 3,000-meter run, the barefoot Ms. Budd collided with U.S.
star Mary Decker Slaney, and the American was unable to continue.
Budd finished seventh amid a chorus of boos.
   She later set several world distance running records while
living and training in Britain. But she was constantly dogged by
anti-apartheid activists who said she should not be allowed to
compete due to her South African connections.
   Ms. Budd, 23, returned to South Africa in May 1988 suffering
from what doctors said was ``complete mental exhaustion.'' She says
she plans to forego international competition and live in her
homeland indefinitely.
</TEXT>
