<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1856EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SmallRailroads     09-26 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Small Railroads,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Lines Vital to Rural America, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Miles of track cast off by the big railroad
companies and now operated by smaller lines are vital to rural
America, an Agriculture Department report said Tuesday.
   Martin Fitzpatrick, administrator of the department's Office of
Transportation, said the number and mileage of small railroads
began to increase in the 1970s but gained a full head of steam in
the mid-1980s.
   As for the future, he said that ``growth in the local and
regional railroad movement probably will be determined by the
outcome of court rulings as to the rights of rail labor in branch
line sales and in transactions that create new railroads.''
   Since the Staggers Act of 1980, which eased the way for big rail
companies to sell off unprofitable branch lines, nearly 200 small
railroads have been formed, the report said. A fifth of these are
owned by shippers.
   ``Local and regional railroads now operate over approximately 15
percent of the nation's rail system, or 30,000 miles, and employ
30,000 people,'' the report said. ``Last year, these carriers
generated $1.5 billion in revenues.''
   Small railroads are freight lines that earn less than $20
million annually and operate less than 350 miles of track.
   The report said that as much as 25,000 additional miles of rail
line are expected to be cast off by large railroads before they are
finished with restructuring plans. Eighteen thousand miles are to
be sold to small railroads over the next two years.
   ``These carriers will function primarily as feeder lines
originating in rural agricultural regions and funneling traffic
into the national rail network,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
