<FIRST>u w AM-Pierce-Cameras     09-26 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pierce-Cameras,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pierce's Lawyer Bars Cameras from Hearing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pierce-HUD, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television coverage, radio equipment and
newspaper cameras were barred from former HUD Secretary Samuel R.
Pierce Jr.'s confrontation with Congress on Tuesday _ a ban forced
by his lawyer against what he charged was the panel's ``circus-like
atmosphere.''
   ``We pulled the plug from their main act because, in fact, we
thought it would create a more somber forum,'' attorney Paul L.
Perito said.
   ``The circus-like atmosphere has been created by them, not by
us,'' Perito said before television cameras assembled outside the
congressional hearing where Pierce appeared under subpoena.
   With the cameras gone, Pierce invoked his constitutional right
against self-incrimination and refused to answer the subcommittee's
questions.
   Pierce's lawyer invoked a House rule that dates to the McCarthy
hearings of the 1950s. It allows witnesses subpoenaed to appear
before Congress to bar broadcast coverage and still photographs of
their appearance.
   Four television networks _ ABC, CBS, CNN and NBC _ failed in
their attempt to win a temporary injunction from a federal judge in
Washington on Monday to prevent Pierce from invoking the rule.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., chairman of the House Government
Operations subcommittee on employment and housing, which is probing
Pierce's tenure as secretary of housing and urban development, said
he favored repealing the rule and was reluctantly enforcing it.
   Lantos permitted full coverage of the subcommittee by radio,
television and photographers for an hour and 15 minutes while he
and other members discussed their investigation and Pierce's likely
refusal to testify.
   Pierce did not enter the committee room, however, until after
Lantos called a brief recess and ordered television, radio and
still photographic coverage to cease.
   Three television cameras remained in the room, apparently shut
off with their lenses pointing away from Pierce.
   Lantos then appealed to Pierce a final time to reconsider the
ban on coverage.
   ``On advice of my counsel, I ask that the rule be employed,''
Pierce said.
   Reporters remained in the room, however, and artists for the
television networks sketched the scene.
   Lantos permitted reporters to use tape recorders to record
Pierce's words.
   The subcommittee staff asked reporters who recorded the event to
sign a brief statement saying the audio recording ``will not be
broadcast in any manner.'' The document said reporters agreed
``under the penalty of perjury.''
   Pierce read a brief statement saying he would not answer
questions, then invoked his constitutional right each time as
Lantos posed eight questions.
   After Pierce left, camras and microphones were allowed to record
subcommittee members' criticism of the former HUD secretary.
   Pierce is under subpoena to appear again Oct. 27. Perito said he
would decide then whether he will seek to ban coverage again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
