<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1912EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Namibia-Elections     09-26 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia-Elections,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N., Namibian Officials in Accord on Election Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Nations officials and Namibia's
administrator reached agreement Tuesday on the laws governing the
territory's pre-independence elections in six weeks.
   The elections, set for Nov. 7-11, will pave the way for
independence in Namibia, which has been ruled by South Africa for
74 years.
   Namibia's South African administrator Louis Pienaar and the head
of the U.N. monitoring contingent, Martti Ahtisaari, finalized the
election laws Tuesday, but will not release the details until later
this week, Pienaar's spokesman Gerhard Roux said.
   Ten parties and coalitions have qualified to contest the
elections for a national assembly that will draw up Namibia's
constitution.
   The favorite in the polls is the South-West Africa People's
Organization, a leftist-oriented independence movement that waged a
23-year war against South African rule.
   Its main rival is expected to be the Democratic Turnhalle
Alliance, a moderate, multiracial coalition that favors a
free-market economy.
   South Africa agreed to grant independence to Namibia last year
under a regional peace accord that also calls for the phased
withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola.
   No date for Namibian independence has been set, but it is
expected to be early next year.
</TEXT>
