<HEAD>Hugo Haunts Couple on Stormy Honeymoon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newlyweds frightened by Hurricane Hugo
into canceling honeymoon plans in Puerto Rico found a romantic
getaway in South Carolina, until they had to ride out the fierce
storm in a motel bathtub.
   ``I'll never forget it for the rest of my life. I just won't
forget,'' Christina Kimball said Tuesday. ``We got back on Sunday.
I was never so happy to see my house in my life.''
   The Kimballs had planned a Caribbean vacation, but warned by
reports of Hugo's destructive power, they canceled those plans.
Then they were offered the chance to use Mrs. Kimball's
mother-in-law's beachfront condominium.
   ``It seemed like the sensible thing to do,'' Mrs. Kimball said.
   The condominium was on the Isle of Palms off Charleston _ the
bulls-eye of Hugo's first strike on the U.S. mainland.
   ``We got there (and) we were thrilled. The condo was right on
the beach. It was beautiful,'' Mrs. Kimball said.
   ``The first night we were out there running around on the beach
all night. The next day we went shopping in town and spent oodles
of money. The next morning, at 6 o'clock, they were evacuating the
whole island.''
   Chased from the resort island, the couple took a motel room in
Charleston Thursday night.
   ``We were still trying to hang in there,'' Mrs. Kimbsion
``cooked the books.''
   Behind the scenes, the lobbying firm of Patton, Boggs and Blow
urged members to vote against the Nunn amendment. Picking up the
lobbyists tab of about $30,000 were residents and businesses near
Chanute Air Force Base, Ill.
   But Nunn warned against the provision, calling it a ``backdoor
way to block a process that has been under way for a year.'' Sen.
John Warner of Virginia, ranking Republican on the Armed Services
Committee, said the provision would undercut any future base
closings.
   ``If we set a precedent now that you can reopen the package, I'm
fearful future commissions won't be as effective,'' Warner said.
   Voting against the base closings amendment were Sens. Bill
Bradley, D-N.J.; Dan Coats, R-Ind.; Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.; Alan
Dixon, D-Ill.; Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii; Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.;
Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.; Richard Lugar, R-Ind.; Spark Matsunaga,
D-Hawaii; John McCain, R-Ariz.; Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.; Paul Simon,
D-Ill.; Ted Stevens, R-Alaska; and Pete Wilson, R-Calif.
