<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1915EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-IndianVillage     09-26 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Indian Village,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Urban Life Depicted in New Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLLINSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The way of life in a city that
prospered centuries before Columbus is depicted in a new exhibit
that should correct the view of those whose only knowledge of
Indians comes from television Westerns, an organizer says.
   The Mississippian Indians who lived on what is now the Cahokia
Mounds State Historic Site between 900 and 1200 A.D. made a unique
attempt at urbanization, experts say. The site, with its
distinctive earthen mounds built for Indian ceremonies, is the
largest archaelogical site in the country.
   The $8.2 million visitors center that opened here last weekend
features a video program, reconstructed buildings and other
displays intended to show what life was like in the Indians' city,
which is believed to have had a population of 20,000.
   ``We're giving people an appreciation and insight into
prehistoric Indian culture,'' said Bill Iseminger, a staff member
at the new visitors center. ``We're trying to educate people about
Indian culture before the time of Columbus.''
   The Indians had a political and religious culture and a
well-defined social order of civil leaders, priests and nobles and
a working class, experts say.
   Visitors to the World Heritage Interpretive Center will get an
introduction to this culture with a widescreen video presentation
on the Indians' life, centered around thatched-roof huts and the
ceremonial mounds.
   ``Everybody thinks that Indians lived in tepees and rode horses.
And of course, these Indians didn't have those things,'' Iseminger
said.
   ``It's not the typical idyllic setting people usually associate
with Native Americans, because it had reached the urban stage,'' he
said, adding that this included some of the same problems plaguing
modern-day city dwellers, such as pollution and overcrowding.
   The exhibits will change about every three months. An outdoor
courtyard will be the site for classes and demonstrations of Indian
crafts and skills.
   The reconstituted village features several kinds of structures,
including a ceremonial sweat lodge and a grainery used for storage.
Huts have thatched roofs made of native prairie grass.
   ``We may even build a small mound,'' Iseminger said.
   Iseminger said the center should be an excellent educational
tool.
   ``We expect increased awareness and more people gaining
knowledge about Indian life in the prehistoric period,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
