<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--ShuttleContract     09-26 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Shuttle Contract,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Extends Space Shuttle Launch Processing Contract</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   L
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) _ NASA's Kennedy Space Center extended
for three years Tuesday a contract under which Lockheed Space
Operations Co. processes space shuttles for launch.
   The extension through Sept. 30, 1992, is valued at $1.6 billion.
   The original three-year contract was awarded Sept. 23, 1983, and
provided for four three-year options. Total contract value for the
original three years plus the first option is $4.37 billion.
   Under the contract, the Lockheed company, based in nearby
Titusville, is responsible for shuttle checkout, launch, landing
and recovery operations. It also handles maintenance and operation
of processing facilities and ground services at the space center.
   A small portion of the contract extension, totaling $5.6
million, is for maintenance of a deactivated, never-used shuttle
launch facility at Vandenberg Air Force Base, Calif. The Air Force
will reimburse NASA for this amount.
</TEXT>
