<HEAD>Father Pleads Guilty To Setting Fire To Pregnant Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man pleaded guilty Tuesday to dousing his
pregnant daughter with brake fluid and setting her on fire during a
family argument.
   Joseph Richmond, 41, of Akron pleaded guilty to felonious
assault, aggravated arson and child endangerment in the July 24
burning of Kimberly Richmond, said Gene Wise, spokesman for the
Summit County prosecutor's office.
   The daughter gave birth July 25 to a girl, delivered by
Caesarean section to prevent burn-related trauma, and had remained
hospitalized until last weekend with second- and third-degree burns
over 80 percent of her body.
   The father initially pleaded innocent by reason of insanity, but
Common Pleas Judge Glen B. Morgan reviewed a psychiatric report and
ruled he was competent to stand trial.
   Richmond said after his arrest that he only wanted to scare his
daughter, police said.
   Morgan scheduled sentencing Oct. 24. Richmond remained free on
bond, a Summit County jail spokeswoman said.
