<FIRST>r a AM-SchoolBoycott     09-26 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School Boycott,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Back in Class after Boycott Over Naming School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most students ended a two-week boycott of
Motley Elementary School on Tuesday after school officials and a
black parents group settled a dispute over naming the school for
civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr.
   The West Lowndes Parents Association and the Lowndes County
chapter of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People agreed Monday to accept a compromise reached during an
eight-hour negotiation Sunday with members of the county school
board.
   The compromise came after two days of meetings that mediator Wil
Colom, a Columbus attorney, said showed ``real leadership in
solving an emotional dispute.''
   Under the compromise, the school will be known officially as
West Lowndes Elementary, but the building itself will be named
after King.
   ``This retains the board's position on naming a school after the
area in which it is located,'' the compromise said.
   ``Other buildings at any school site can also be named for
individuals who are deceased and whose names will not inflame the
community,'' it added.
   The old school name of Motley reflected the name of the local
unincorporated community, but blacks protested that the community
was named for the family that owned a plantation in the area in
slave-holding times.
   Tuesday's attendance at the elementary school was 350 out of 425
pupils expected, officials said.
   Only 32 students attended Sept. 12, the first day of school,
because of dissatisfaction over the school's name and its
incomplete construction. There were 212 students at the school
Monday, officials reported.
   The compromise also says that when the board selects a new
assistant superintendent of education, primary consideration will
be given to a candidate's ability to communicate with and work with
minority students, parents and staff.
   The West Lowndes Parents Association and the NAACP had wanted a
black assistant superintendent.
   The deal still needs federal court approval under a 1970 court
desegregation order.
   School board approval came in a 45-minute closed session Monday.
Board President Gary Chism wouldn't give the vote tally or answer
any questions.
</TEXT>
