<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1910EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DeathRates     09-26 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Death Rates,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health Secretary Calls For Renewed Commitment to Improving Blacks'
Health</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health Secretary Louis Sullivan said Tuesday
the country must ``renew our commitment'' to improving the health
of black Americans, who are dying younger than white Americans.
   Sullivan cited a new government report showing life expectancy
for blacks is several years shorter than for whites and that blacks
have higher death rates than whites for infant mortality and for
several diseases, including AIDS.
   ``Even as the lines on almost every disease chart move toward
improvement, there is a continuing disparity in the burden of death
and illness experienced by blacks and other minority Americans as
compared with the improving health of Americans as a whole,''
Sullivan said.
   ``We must renew our commitment to close these health
disparities,'' he said.
   The report of mortality statistics for 1987 by the National
Center for Health Statistics shows that life expectancy at birth
rose slightly from 1986 to reach a record high of 75 years in 1987.
Life expectancy for white Americans was 75.6 years, but for blacks
it was 69.4 years, the same as the previous year, according to the
report.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome was the 10th leading cause
of death for blacks, while it ranked 15th for the U.S. population
overall in 1987.
   Of the more than 13,000 AIDS deaths, 65 percent were white
males, 25 percent were black males and the remaining 10 percent
were split evenly between white females and black females.
   Blacks also died at disproportionately higher rates from other
illnesses, including kidney disease, for which the black death rate
was 2.8 times the rate of the white population, and diabetes, for
which the black death rate was 2.3 times that for whites, according
to the report.
   The rate of infant mortality declined slightly in 1987 to 10.1
infant deaths per 1,000 live births, from 10.4 the previous year.
The rate for whites dropped from 8.9 to 8.6, while the rate for
blacks declined from 18 to 17.9.
   The report also shows the drug-related death rate for blacks was
more than twice the rate for whites, and the homicide death rate
for blacks was six times that of whites.
</TEXT>
