<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1938EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-OlderGraduates     09-26 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Older Graduates,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Finds Payoffs for Women Who Return to School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women who return to college and earn degrees
report increased self-esteem and more satisfying jobs, according to
a national study released Tuesday.
   The survey of nearly 3,400 selected graduates from 33 women's
colleges also found that 56 percent continued their formal
education beyond an undergraduate degree.
   The study, conducted by the Women's College Coalition, a project
of the Association of American Colleges, found that the typical
graduate among those studied returned to school in her mid-30s and
was married with school-age children. Of those who were married, 55
percent had been aged 18 to 21, the traditional college years, when
they wed.
   The survey, conducted last year, included women who entered
college after age 23 and graduated in the years 1970 to 1988.
   Eighty-eight percent of the women reported that their jobs
changed in positive ways after they graduated; 87 percent said
their education had contributed to an appreciation of their
abilities.
   ``Achieving that degree had a major impact on their
self-confidence, their sense of self-esteem and personal
fulfillment and their sense of being an independent person,'' said
Dr. Sally Wall of the College of Notre Dame of Maryland in
Baltimore, the principal researcher on the study.
   Fifty-seven percent of the respondents said their main reason
for returning to school was for personal fulfillment; 33 percent
cited career reasons.
   Some 50 percent of the graduates were aged 31 to 44; the oldest
was 85. The women typically were first-generation college
graduates, had previously earned less than one year of college
credit and completed their degrees in four years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
