<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-26 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Scattered Along East Coast After Heavy Rain In Southeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain was scattered along the East Coast on Tuesday, after a
night of heavy rain in the Southeast.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered during the afternoon
from the Florida Peninsula across coastal North Carolina to New
England.
   The heaviest rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT was
1.57 inches at Chatham, Mass. Other amounts during that period were
less than an inch.
   Late Monday and early Tuesday, showers and thunderstorms brought
rain to much of the Southeast, much of the middle Atlantic Coast
region and New England.
   During the 24-hour period up to 8 a.m. EDT Tuesday, one-inch
rainfall totals were common from Florida and Alabama to the middle
Atlantic Coast.
   Atlanta's Hartsfield Airport got 4.87 inches of rain Monday, the
sixth highest total on record there for any one day, and some
highway flooding was reported, the National Weather Service said.
   In coastal North Carolina, along the Outer Banks, rain has
fallen at Cape Hatteras each of the last 14 days, with a total of
15.51 inches in that period. So far this month, Cape Hatteras has
received 19.73 inches of rain.
   In the West, showers were widely scattered across western Oregon
and northern California, with a few showers over the central Rocky
Mountains.
   Late Monday and early Tuesday, scattered showers brought light
rain to parts of the Great Basin, covering Nevada and western Utah,
and the Pacific Northwest. Rainfall totals were generally less than
a tenth of an inch for the 24 hours up to 8 a.m. EDT.
   Dense fog was reported along the northern coast of California
early in the day.
   In the Southeast, Miami had a record high of 93 degrees.
   But Tuesday afternoon temperatures were only in the 50s from
eastern North Dakota and northeastern South Dakota through Michigan
to northern New England, with readings in the 40s in Upper Michigan
and northern Lower Michigan.
   Overnight into Wednesday, frost and freeze advisories were
issued for all of Michigan, and a frost advisory was issued for
northern and central Indiana.
   Late Monday and early Tuesday, freezing temperatures were
reported in Minnesota, North Dakota, eastern South Dakota, northern
Iowa and northwestern Wisconsin, with readings only in the mid to
upper 20s across northern Minnesota and northeastern North Dakota.
   Tuesday's official low for the Lower 48 states was 25 degrees at
International Falls, Minn., on the Canadian border.
</TEXT>
