<FIRST>r a AM-HanfordIndictment     09-26 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hanford Indictment,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Welding Inspector at Nuclear Reservation Pleads Innocent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former welding inspector on the Hanford
nuclear reservation pleaded innocent Tuesday to charges he lied
about his certification for the job.
   ``He completely and emphatically denies his guilt,'' said
Chelsea Korte, lawyer for Bruce Ronald Degnan. ``He really is
befuddled.''
   Degnan is charged with 18 counts of falsifying certification for
himself and 10 of employees from 1984 to 1987 while working as a
federal contractor at the plutonium production complex.
   At the time, Hanford was involved in producing plutonium for
hydrogen bombs. Most of the plutonium production facilities are now
closed.
   Working as Tri Testing Inc., Degnan and his staff inspected
welds at Hanford, but officials won't disclose whether Degnan's
company inspected welds in sensitive production plants.
   Degnan contends he is the victim of a government blunder.
   Degnan, 46, was released on his own recognizance after
arraignment.
   If convicted, Degnan faces a maximum of five years in prison on
each count. Westinghouse Hanford Co. operates the reservation for
the Department of Energy. The company took over in June 1987 and
stopped giving Degnan's firm work later that year.
</TEXT>
