<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Soviet     09-26 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Soviet,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel, Soviet Union to Exchange Chambers of Commerce</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and Israeli representatives on Tuesday
approved an agreement for a mutual exchange of chambers of
commerce, Israel radio reported.
   The radio said the agreement was approved at a meeting between
Israeli and Soviet trade delegations in Paris, which was sponsored
by the France-Israel Chamber of Commerce.
   The agreement was approved and signed by the deputy president of
the Soviet Chamber of Commerce and Industry, Vladimir Galanov, and
head of Israel's Chamber of Commerce, Dani Gilerman.
   The final agreement is to be signed in Israel and the Soviet
Union in November, the radio reported.
   It said the delegations would continue their talks, aimed at
developing commercial ties between the two countries, on Wednesday.
   The Soviet Union broke diplomatic relations with Israel in 1967
to protest Israel's seizure of lands from Moscow's Arab allies in
the Middle East war.
   The two countries exchanged interest offices in 1986 and 1987
and have since been developing cultural and tourist ties. But they
deeply differ in their views on how to achieve peace in the Middle
East, and the Soviet side says this prevents further normalization
of relations.
</TEXT>
