<FIRST>r a AM-ReadingPoll     09-26 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reading Poll,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: Kids Thinks Bookworms are Smarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Youngsters who enjoy reading are viewed by their
peers as more likely to do well in school rather than as nerdy
bookworms, a survey of children showed Wednesday.
   In addition, half the children surveyed, ages 6 to 10, said they
``really like to read'' and 42 percent ``sort of'' like to read,
said the study conducted for the American Library Association. Only
7.2 percent said they did not like to read.
   The survey was conducted among 500 children at 10 suburban malls
around the country in an approach that does not produce a
representative sample, a news release said.
   According to the study, 62.4 percent of the children said a kid
who reads a lot ``learns things in school more quickly,'' while
18.8 percent said such kids were called ``nerds or geeks.'' In
fact, 18 percent said children who did not enjoy reading were
likely to be called such names.
   Reading came in fifth of 12 activities when children were asked
their favorite things to do, finishing behind playing with friends,
outdoor sports, bicycling and watching television.
   Among the activities reading beat out in the popularity contest:
video games and listening to music.
   The study also indicated that of reading, writing and
arithmetic, math was the favorite subject of 48.2 percent, with
reading pulling in 35.4 percent and writing 16 percent.
</TEXT>
