<FIRST>u w AM-Helms-Meredith 1stLd-Writethru a0673 09-26 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helms-Meredith, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0673,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meredith Takes Job on Helms' Staff</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 2 pvs, A senior, with 4 grafs Meredith comment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Meredith, the black man who cracked the
color barrier at the University of Mississippi 27 years ago, has
been hired to what some see as an unlikely post: adviser to
conservative Sen. Jesse Helms.
   Meredith said in an interview Tuesday that he had been hired
officially on Sept. 5 to advise the senator on questions of race,
education, drugs and urban problems, after providing informal
advice for the last year.
   Meredith, 58, has changed his views markedly since becoming the
first black enrolled at Ole Miss in 1962. Since then, he has called
integration the ``biggest con job ever pulled on anybody.''
   ``My understanding of the senator's position ... is that every
citizen has the entitlement to every right,'' he said Tuesday. ``So
there's no need for any specific rights. And I agree with that.
   ``It is the specific intent of the liberal elite to establish on
a permanent basis a dual citizenship in the United States. They
need to keep blacks in a non full-citizenship status. It's not
Senator Helms who doesn't want blacks to be free in America. It's
the liberal agenda.''
   In a letter to acquaintances, he wrote that Helms, who is up for
re-election next year, ``wants to provide the best possible
representation to them as well as the entire black population.''
   Some civil rights leader were nonetheless astonished at
Meredith's decision to join Helms' staff.
   ``It's somewhat of a shock to me,'' said Benjamin Hooks of the
NAACP. ``I've watched (Meredith's) progression _ or maybe I should
say retrogression _ from being a militant civil rights advocate to
another stand altogether. But I didn't know he had changed to the
point he would fit in with Sen. Helms' staff.''
   ``Without question, Senator Helms has one of the worst civil
rights voting records in the Congress,'' said Ralph Neas of the
Washington-based Leadership Conference on Civil Rights. ``For years
he has led the right-wing opposition to effective civil rights laws
and remedies. He is a senator markedly out of step with the
bipartisan consensus on civil rights in this country.''
   While Meredith was battling segregation in the South during the
'60s, the conservative Helms was gaining a following as a Raleigh
television editorialist who harshly criticized the movement to
bring about racial change.
   Since his election to the Senate in 1972, Helms has vigorously
opposed civil rights bills and other domestic programs favored by
many blacks. He has defended the white minority government of South
Africa, fought making Martin Luther King Jr.'s birthday a national
holiday and criticized such national black leaders as Jesse Jackson.
   Meredith entered the all-white University of Mississippi after
spending nine years in the Air Force. His arrival on campus caused
rioting; two people died, and President Kennedy sent in troops and
federal marshals.
   Since then, Meredith, who was wounded during a freedom march in
Mississippi in 1965, has held numerous jobs in various parts of the
country, most recently living in Cincinnati, where he worked as a
financial planner and tree farmer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890926-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1706EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-SovietArmsControl     09-26 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet Arms Control,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Stress Ending Chemical Weapons Production</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-UN Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union, while accepting a U.S.
call to slash chemical weapons stockpiles, insisted Tuesday on a
different approach keyed to halting production of the deadly arms.
   A cessation of further output of poison gas must be ``part of
the parcel,'' senior Soviet negotiator Viktor P. Karpov said.
   Even so, the White House welcomed Soviet acceptance of President
Bush's initiative.
   At the White House, Bush said, ``I am very pleased with the way
things are going. ... We've got some good common ground that I
don't think we had before.''
   And Bush's press secretary, Marlin Fitzwater, said the Soviet
response ``shows that we are on the same wavelength. It was a very
constructive response. Our ultimate objective is total elimination
of chemical weapons. And it appears that both nations are now ready
to act.''
   The Soviet position was outlined by Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze in a speech to the U.N. General Assembly and then by
Karpov at a news conference.
   The two sides disagreed on whether the Soviet plan went beyond
Bush's initiative. But the two approaches clearly differed in two
significant ways.
   Bush would have the superpowers retain 2 percent of their
chemical weapons until all nations ``capable of building chemical
weapons'' sign an international ban.
   And, as the president explained his proposal Monday in a speech
to the General Assembly, the United States would keep producing
new, binary weapons while destroying older stocks.
   Binary weapons are deadly, but only when they are mixed.
   Shevardnadze praised Bush's move and said, ``The Soviet Union,
together with the United States, is ready to go further.''
   He called for a cessation of production. At a news conference
later, Deputy Foreign Minister Karpov said Soviet acceptance was
conditional on a halt to U.S. production of binary weapons.
   ``It is part of the parcel,'' said Karpov, the highest-ranked
arms control expert in the Soviet hierarchy. ``It will not be
sufficient to get rid of old weapons if the United States is going
to produce new ones.''
   A second key difference between the two sides centers on when
all U.S. and Soviet chemical weapons would be destroyed.
   Bush said the United States was ready to destroy 98 percent of
its weapons in the first eight years of an agreement with Moscow.
The remaining 2 percent would be retained until 40 nations now
negotiating in Geneva agreed on a treaty to ban chemical weapons _
and all nations with the capability to produce them signed the pact.
   This would mean an outright ban depended on the approval of such
nations as Iran and Iraq, and possibly Libya, which the Reagan
administration says is on the verge of production. Iraq and Iran
have been accused of using poison gas in their Persian Gulf War
that ended last year.
   Karpov said the Soviets were willing to destroy all their
chemical weapons once the treaty was completed.
   ``We wouldn't bar the treaty entering into force if there is one
nation capable of producing chemical weapons,'' he said.
   Karpov said the Soviets were not helping any country to
manufacture chemical weapons. He placed the Soviet arsenal at
50,000 tons.
   Bush administration officials have declined to divulge the U.S.
total. The general assumption is that it is about 30,000 tons.
   Shevardnadze also called on the two superpowers to ``renounce
the use of chemical weapons under any circumstances.''
   And, the Soviet foreign minister said, they should employ
``rigorous verification of the cessation of production of chemical
warfare agents.'
   Shevardnadze and Secretary of State James A. Baker III agreed
last week in talks in Jackson Hole, Wyo., on a two-step plan for
exchanging information about chemical weapons and for trial
inspections of stockpiles.
   Baker had a seven-minute meeting with Shevardnadze after the
foreign minister delivered his speech.
   He told reporters he had to study the Soviet chemical weapons
proposal and that it did not appear to go beyond Bush's initiative.
   But Karpov said ``our proposal is a wider one.''
   He said Moscow was ready to begin negotiations with the United
States to reduce stockpiles on both sides.
   Shevardnadze, in his speech, welcomed Bush's initiative and said
``we share the desire to rid mankind of these barbaric weapons.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
