<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1708EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Mars     09-26 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mars,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA Chief Says Budget Cuts Won't Help Mars Mission Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA Administrator Richard H. Truly resisted a
House subcommittee's efforts Tuesday to get him to estimate how
much it will cost to go to Mars, but complained that congressional
cuts in the agency's 1990 budget won't help.
   Noting that the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's
budget is no more than 1 percent of total federal spending, Truly
told the panel that ratio will have to increase if the nation is
serious about moving out to the moon again, and beyond to Mars.
   Already, he said, House and Senate appropriations committee
moves to slash NASA's $2.05 billion budget request by as much as
$400 million is forcing the agency to consider slowing its
construction schedule for the spacestation that is planned as a
forerunner to moon and Mars missions.
   However, Truly stoutly denied news reports that the pending
budget cuts are forcing the agency to redesign the station.
   ``We're not redesigning the station,'' he said. ``It's more a
matter of ... pacing the construction of the station.''
   Truly, the first former astronaut to head the space agency,
acknowledged that President Bush's goal for a manned mission to
Mars will take a commitment by a succession of administrations over
three or four decades and will be costly.
   However, he declined to give even a rough guess of how much NASA
budgets would have to grow to reach the goal. ``We are not far
enough to have a program plan,'' he said to several subcommittee
members who pressed him for an estimate.
   Rep. Bill Nelson, D-Fla., chairman of the Science, Space and
Technology space science subcommittee, predicted the NASA budget
would have to swell to at least $15 billion a year, and perhaps $30
billion.
   While supporting the goal of sending a manned mission to Mars,
Nelson told Truly it would be better to bypass the moon lest that
program eat up too much money.
   He did not press Truly on that point, however, saying,
``there'll be plenty of time to debate that over the next three
years'' before a final decision is made.
</TEXT>
