<DOCNO> AP890926-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1942EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-VenezuelaDebt 1stLd-Writethru   09-26 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Venezuela Debt, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0654,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs with Brady comment after 6th pvs, bgng: Because
of...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Finance Meetings,Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Venezuela has retreated from
its demand for a 50 percent reduction in its $21 billion debt,
hoping to rejuvenate stalled negotiations with commercial banks,
officials said Tuesday.
   Instead, Venezuela will offer banks ``a broad menu of options''
that will include lesser discounts in exchange for weaker
guarantees of remaining debt, said Venezuelan planning minister
Miguel Rodriguez Fandeo, who is in charge of his country's
debt-reduction effort.
   He also announced that a consortium of 15 banks has agreed to a
$600 million short-term loan to allow Venezuela to catch up with
missed interest payments by Dec. 31. The government is contributing
$400 million from its reserves to wiping out the missed payments,
he said.
   Briefing reporters at the annual meeting of the 152-nation
International Monetary Fund and its sister organization, the World
Bank, Rodriguez insisted that the new strategy did not mean
Venezuela had retreated from its goal of ``the largest possible
reduction in debt and debt service.''
   Debt reduction is the keystone of Treasury Secretary Nicholas F.
Brady's initiative, announced in March, a month after bloody riots
in Venezuela focused attention on the plight of developing
countries mired by a crushing $1.3 trillion debt burden.
   Because of the riots, Venezuela was one of the first countries
singled out for debt reduction by the Bush administration, but
commercial banks have concluded pacts with Mexico and the
Philippines first. Bankers have accused Venezuela of being
intransigent in its demands.
   Brady, in an afternoon speech to World Bank and IMF delegates,
admonished both developing countries and their creditors toward
flexibility, citing discussions between banks and Costa Rica,
Venezuela, Morocco, Uruguay and Chile.
   ``An important challenge at the moment appears to be the problem
of unrealistic expectations _ both among debtor countries and the
banks,'' Brady said. ``In one sense, improving expectations was
essential to restoring forward momentum in the debt strategy. ...
In another sense, however, we must recognize that rising
expectations need to be tempered by realism.''
   ``Excessive expectations can only promote delays, increase the
risk of breakdown in negotiations and ultimately raise the economic
costs to the banks and debtor countries,'' Brady said.
   Rodriguez said his country will continue to offer to buy back
its loans in cash in exchange for a 60 percent discount and issue
guaranteed bonds for a 50 percent debt reduction.
   However, it will also be willing to accept a lower discount if
banks accept bonds with weaker guarantees than the 50 percent bonds.
   In addition, Venezuela will accept new loans from the banks, but
only to the extent necessary to compensate for debt reduction less
than 50 percent, the planning minister said.
   He said his country is shifting its policy in hope of
accommodating banks which, because of tax and other regulations,
are unable to take a 50 percent loss on the loans. Rodriguez said
the new strategy should allow a greater number of banks to
participate in a debt-reduction pact, which he said Venezuela would
like to conclude by the end of the year.
   The $600 million short-term loan was offered by 15 banks, led by
Chase Manhattan Bank, Bank of America, Bank of Tokyo and Lloyd's
Bank, said Pedro Tinoco Jr., president of Venezuela's central bank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
