<FIRST>r w AM-US-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0674 09-26 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0674,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, West German Minister Would Help Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: First 9 grafs new, picking up 4th graf pvs, Poland owes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West German finance minister met with
President Bush on Tuesday to discuss ways to help Poland's new
non-communist government redirect its economy and reduce its $42
billion debt.
   Meanwhile, Polish Finance Minister Leszek Balcerowicz brought
his pleas for aid to the 152 governments in the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund meeting here. Poland has been a major
topic of discussion at the meeting.
   And eight Senate Democrats, including the chairman of the Senate
Agriculture Committee, proposed forgiving Poland's $2 billion
agricultural debt to the United States and providing food aid
beyond the $100 million in assistance proposed by Bush.
   As outlined in a letter to the president, the proposal calls for
the donation of $150 million in corn, grain, sorghum, wheat, butter
and pork products to Poland and urges authorization of an
additional $150 million in assistance.
   It also calls for the extension of preferential tariff treatment
for Poland and the extension of technical aid through the
Agriculture Department.
   The legislators, led by Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., the
Agriculture Committee chairman, also challenged U.S. private
industry to make available $10 million to Poland in money and
equipment.
   ``The president's plan is a welcome but stop-gap effort that
fails to give Poland the long-term help it needs to restructure its
agricultural economy and to sustain the world's newest democracy,''
Leahy said.
   The letter was signed by Leahy and Sens. Tom Daschle, D-S.D.;
Quentin Burdick, D-N.D.; Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn.; Bennett
Johnston, D-La.; Spark Matsunaga, D-Hawaii; Richard Bryan,
D-Nevada, and Dale Bumpers, D-Ark.
   Speaking with reporters after his half-hour meeting with Bush,
West German Finance Minister Theo Waigel said the two had discussed
ways to reduce the Polish debt. Waigel said he told Bush the World
Bank and IMF should help.
   Poland owes about $10 billion to commercial banks and the rest
to other governments, including the United States.
   The World Bank's International Finance Corp. offered earlier
this week to help Poland privatize its state-owned industry and set
up new banks and markets.
   There is general agreement that the IMF will have to assess
Poland's situation before there can be any large-scale
international help.
   Officials of Solidarity, the main force behind the new
government, have said Poland needs at least $10 billion over three
years.
   Waigel also said he told Bush that there should be a
strengthening of market forces in Poland and that the European
Economic Community should help.
   West Germany is discussing giving Poland credits and credit
guarantees to supply projects that would stimulate the economy,
Waigel said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
