<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1733EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Pentagon-B-2 440   09-26 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pentagon-B-2, 440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two B-2 Tests Cut Short</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two B-2 stealth bomber test flights were cut
short last week, once because of a renewed oil-pressure problem and
once because of high winds, the Pentagon said Tuesday.
   A planned 5{-hour flight Sept. 21 was scrubbed after three hours
after indications of low oil pressure in the plane's No. 1 airframe
accessory drive, said Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams.
   The bat-wing bomber is designed to pass through enemy radar
virtually undetected. The accessory drive is the gear box that
powers the jet's generators and controls.
   The same problem had forced the crew to scub the second test
flight of the $530 million plane on Aug. 16.
   ``As with the second flight, the B-2 was landed early as a
precaution,'' Williams said. ``The flight crew was in no danger.''
   Four new casings were installed for the stealth's fifth test
flight Saturday, and no oil-pressure problems were encountered,
Williams said.
   However, that flight ended after 77 minutes ``because of gusty
winds at the altitude at which the plane was flying,'' William
said, adding that he could not say what the wind strengths were.
   It was decided to cut that flight short as a precaution because
of the stress being placed on the bomber during the particular
maneuvers being conducted, Williams said.
   ``That doesn't mean that the plane can't fly at high winds,'' he
said.
   The crew did complete an air-refueling test under which the
bat-wing jet purposely stopped just short of its refueling KC-10
aircraft.
   Williams said the stealth won't be flown again for at least five
weeks while ``planned modifications'' and ground vibration tests
are done.
   The plane has flown a total of 12 hours, Williams said.
   ``The Air Force says (the stealth) has performed better than
expected in areas of handling qualities, especially smooth aircraft
control in the fueling position,'' he said.
   When questioned, Williams said the Air Force hadn't said in
which areas the plane hasn't performed up to expectations.
   The government has spent about $22.4 billion in the B-2 program,
which is 18 months behind schedule, and Congress has balked at
paying more than $500 million each for 132 bombers.
   Shrouded in secrecy for 10 years, manufacturer Northrop Corp.
and the Pentagon have begun an an intensive campaign to counter
those who question the plane's capabilities.
   The Pentagon wants $4.7 billion for the bomber in the coming
fiscal year, and may need $8 billion in each of the three years of
peak production, 1992-'94.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890926-0170 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1734EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Budget-Taxes     09-26 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget-Taxes,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Bill Debate Begins, Weighed Down by Other Issues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Capital Gains-IRAs Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House began debate Tuesday on a huge
budget bill weighed down by such unconnected issues as catastrophic
illness insurance, child care, pornographic telephone services and
the fight over President Bush's capital gains tax cut.
   ``It's so full of irrelevancies, it is hardly recognizable'' as
a budget bill, said Rep. Bill Frenzel, R-Minn. ``Let the games
begin,'' he added, as debate began.
   In an unusual procedure, the House opened debate on the bill
before agreeing to a schedule for the amendments. The budget
portion is designed to reduce the fiscal 1990 federal deficit by
$16.6 billion.
   During the day, Democratic leaders scrambled to find more votes
for their amendment which would derail the capital gains tax cut.
   House Speaker Thomas S. Foley said reaction to the Democratic
alternative, which would raise tax rates for the wealthy to restore
deductions for Individual Retirement Accounts, was ``encouraging.''
   From the White House, however, Bush sent letters to all House
members calling his tax cut ``the right policy for all Americans''
and saying he would veto the Democratic alternative should it be
approved.
   A vote on that provision, originally slated for Wednesday, was
delayed at least until Thursday while the behind-the-scenes
political wrangling continued.
   Rep. Jim Slattery, D-Kan., who opposes the Bush-backed plan to
drop the maximum capital gains rate from 33 percent to 19.6 percent
for the next 27 months, conceded the Democrats didn't have the
votes.
   ``But the other side hasn't got the votes yet either,'' he said.
   While capital gains has been the most partisan fight, other
issues have broad public impact, including at least three competing
child care amendments.
   The House is retreating from past actions with an amendment
expected next week to repeal the new Medicare catastrophic health
insurance program. Elderly groups have protested the new taxes
levied on the elderly to pay for their additional coverage.
   Business groups have lobbied successfully for a repeal of rules
mandating non-discrimination in their health plans.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee, said the House was ``signaling our willingness to
bow to any special interest group that is aggressive and
single-minded enough to hound us into submission.''
   ``But my disappointment with this bill ... is minor when
compared to my disappointment with the president,'' Rostenkowski
said. ``The president has squandered the first year of his
presidency on symbolic victories.''
   ``What will he have to show for it at the end of this year?''
Rostenkowski said. ``Legislation to protect the flag from a handful
of misguided exhibitionists, a blueprint for a drug war that is
doomed for failure because he refuses to pay for it, a plan to sail
to Mars, and if he gets his way, and a tax cut for the wealthiest 5
percent of our population in a year when our deficit exceeds $130
billion.''
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., the chairman of the House Budget
Committee, called on lawmakers to stick with the bill even if they
don't like some of the provisions or amendments.
   If the bill is not ``enacted in some form,'' he reminded the
House, the Gramm-Rudman law will require more than $16 billion in
automatic spending cuts in both domestic and military programs. The
law mandates those cuts if Congress and the president fail to
reduce the deficit to within $10 billion of the $100 billion target
for fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1.
   The deficit reduction is supposed to be in place by Oct. 15, but
Foley said Tuesday he didn't expect that do be done. The result
will be what he said will be ``a sort of technical'' cutback, but
he expected the House, Senate and administration to work out their
differences to avoid any permanent reductions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
