<FIRST>r w AM-DisabilitiesAct     09-26 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disabilities Act,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bus Operators Say Service Could Be Cut Because Of Law For Disabled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Operators of private bus companies complained
Tuesday before a House subcommittee that the proposed Americans
With Disabilities Act could force them to cut service, especially
to the poor and rural dwellers.
   Most of the testimony centered on the requirements under the
proposed legislation that inter-city bus fleets be made accessible
to the disabled within six or seven years of enactment.
   The bus operators interpret that requirement as a mandate that
all buses be equipped with wheelchair lifts, which they say cost
from $10,000 to $35,000 per bus to install, not to mention
maintenance costs.
   ``The mandatory lift requirement, with its attendant costs,
including installation, seat loss, and possible package express
loss, would spell the end of intercity bus service in the United
States,'' said Frank M. Henry, chairman of the American Bus
Association.
   The operators are proposing alternatives, such as a system of
leasing equipped buses or having a limited number in the fleet,
making those buses available on call.
   Advocates for the disabled say they have the same right to
spontaneous travel that others have, and a reservations system or
other limited availability would prevent that.
   With 200,000 buses in the total fleet operated by members of the
American Bus Association, the cost of installing lifts would would
range from $20 million to $70 million, said Henry, of Wilkes-Barre,
Pa.
   He told the surface transportation subcommittee of the Committee
on Public Works and Transportation that by contrast, the industry
had operating income of $41.5 million from 1982-1986.
   The bus operators say the installation of wheelchair lifts would
result in the loss of up to four revenue-producing seats, not to
mention cargo and luggage space and modifying restrooms.
   Owners also testified that where wheelchair access was in place,
demand was minimal.
   Advocates for the disabled told the subcommittee, however, that
the bill does not specify wheelchair lifts, but added that the lift
technology is so advanced that the cost estimates given by the
industry are exaggerated.
   Most of the testimony Tuesday and in a hearing by the
subcommittee last week dealt with the costs of lifts.
   A German-designed lift used on Denver buses costs $11,000,
removes only one seat and occupies no baggage space, said Marilyn
Golden of the Disability Rights Education and Defense Fund.
   She also said there is no requirement to modify restrooms,
adding that the disabled have had long experience coping without
bathrooms.
   She and several other witnesses disputed the claims of low
ridership, saying the disabled have been conditioned not be be able
to expect to travel.
   ``It takes time for them to believe the word `Yes','' said John
Winski, assistant director of the Massachusetts Coalition of
Citizens with Disabilities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
