<HEAD>Colombian President To Meet With Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 4th graf pvs to CORRECT spelling of Cartagena and Bogota</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombian President Virgilio Barco, facing
escalating violence by drug lords in his country, will meet with
President Bush at the White House on Thursday evening.
   Barco will stop in Washington on his way to New York to address
the United Nations, White House press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater
said Tuesday
   The visit comes as bombings and violence continue to rock the
drug-trafficking plagued South American nation, in the wake of
Barco's crackdown to rid Colombia of drugs.
   On Monday and Tuesday, three explosions, attributed to drug
traffickers, blasted Cartagena and Bogota, killing two people.
   Asked if Bush would press Barco to request help from U.S.
troops, beyond the military equipment the administration already is
sending, Fitzwater said no.
   ``We have said from the beginning we would respond only to
requests by the president. We respect his rights and wishes as
president of that country, and whether or not he requests any more
aid in terms of money or troops or whatever is entirely within his
purview,'' Fitzwater said.
   The recent bombings, the spokesman said, ``are an exclamation
point to the danger there and to the desperation that the country
faces in terms of its drug problem. It strengthens the commitment
of everyone to continue the fight.''
   Bush has repeatedly expressed verbal support for Barco's efforts
against the drug traffickers and recently ordered $65 million in
military equipment and weaponry be sent to assist him.
   He also has requested $251 million from Congress for next year
to help Peru, Colombia and Bolivia in their drug wars.
   Fitzwater said Bush and Barco, in addition to the drug
situation, will talk about trade and U.S. aid to Colombia.
   Bush will meet with Barco in the residence quarters of the White
House after his return from the two-day education summit meeting
with the nation's governors in Charlottesville, Va.
</TEXT>
