<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Hungary     09-26 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Hungary,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Propose Larger Aid Plan for Poland, Hungary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 24 nations pooling aid for Poland
and Hungary agreed Tuesday on the urgency of introducing more
measures to support political and economic reforms in the two
East-bloc countries.
   In a final communique at the end of a one-day meeting, senior
officials from the 24 donor nations also urged Poland and Hungary
to reach agreements with the International Monetary Fund to
reschedule their foreign debts.
   Hungary's foreign debt is about $18 billion _ the highest per
capita in Eastern Europe _ and Poland's foreign debt is a
debilitating $39 billion.
   The European Community's executive commission, which is
coordinating the aid efforts _ has said rescheduling debts is
outside its mandate.
   The communique noted that $271 million worth of food aid has
been pledged by the 24 nations to be delivered to Poland and
Hungary.
   It was the second meeting by the 24 nations with another
scheduled for November.
   European Community officials put a $648 million price tag on the
new aid plan with half to be financed by the 12 EC member states
and the remainder by the 12 other donor nations.
   The U.S. delegation, which did not announce any new measures to
add to the $169 million already pledged, indicated it could find
additional funds and said the $648 million should be seen as a
minimum amount, not a ceiling.
   By the end of the meeting $133 million was promised by Sweden,
Denmark, Norway, Finland and Austria.
   The EC proposed paying $216 million from its 1990 budget toward
the new plan and suggested the European Community's 12 members
could provide $108 million more on a bilateral basis. The other
donors also would supply $324 million.
   Jacques Delors, president of the EC executive commission, and
Frans Andriessen, the EC external relations commisisoner, issued a
statement calling the process of political reform and economic
liberalization in Poland and Hungary ``still very fragile.''
   They said Poles and Hungarians ``could well find their new
freedoms threatened by economic disorders.''
   ``It would be unthinkable to allow such disorders, which could
be alleviated through rapid action, to undermine the prospects for
change in Eastern Europe,'' they added.
   Following are major provisions of the five-point air program
proposed Tuesday:
   _ To supply such goods as pesticides and farm machinery in
addition to food being sent to the Polish government. The food is
to be shipped free on condition the government uses the money from
sales to improve the private farm sector.
   _ To improve market access for Polish and Hungarian goods by
eliminating quantitative restrictions on their exports and offering
trade concessions.
   _ To grant both countries loans from the European Investment
Bank and include them in loan operations usually reserved for
developing nations.
   _ To provide professional training including banking and customs
to prepare Poland and Hungary for market-oriented economies.
   _ Cooperation to clean up industrialized areas and preserve
historical and cultural sites in both countries.
   EC participitation in the plan requires approval by the 12
governments and the European Parliament. The other donor nations
that also must approve the proposals are the six members of the
European Free Trade Association, Austria, Finland, Iceland, Norway,
Sweden and Switzerland, along with Japan, the United States,
Canada, Australia, New Zealand and Turkey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
