<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Armenia     09-26 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Armenia,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Azerbaijani Blockade of Armenia Eases, First Trains Get Through</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Politics, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than 24 hours after President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev forcefully threatened to resolve the feud between Armenia
and Azerbaijan, cargo trains began running to Armenia ending an
economic blockade.
   Azerbaijani interference with cargo on the rail route into
Armenia had tightened to a total blockade over the past several
weeks.
   The Soviet evening news program Vremya on Tuesday said 14 trains
arrived in Armenia Monday night and Tuesday, delivering food,
medicine, newsprint and construction material desperately needed in
the area of Armenia devastated by last December's earthquake.
   But the film showed potatoes in the railroad cars were rotting
and crawling with maggots after three weeks of sitting outdoors.
The Vremya correspondent said none of the railcars contained fuel,
also critically needed.
   Gorbachev warned at Monday's session of the Soviet legislature
that the government would take tougher, unspecified steps to settle
the Armenian-Azerbaijani dispute if the two republics cannot do it
themselves quickly. He did not elaborate.
   More than 100 people have been killed in ethnic violence in the
two republics the past 19 months, with much of the conflict
centering on the disputed territory of Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Newspapers in Yerevan, the Armenian capital, stopped publishing
last week for lack of newsprint and reconstruction in the
earthquake zone came to a standstill because of a shortage of
materials.
   Neither Soviet television nor the official news agency Tass gave
any explanation of how the trains reached their destinations after
weeks of delay.
   Tass said 17 trains left for Armenia from Baku, the capital of
Azerbaijan, between 6 p.m. Monday and 6 p.m. Tuesday. It said their
750 railcars contained construction supplies, food, vehicles,
machinery and other cargo.
</TEXT>
