<FIRST>r w AM-EducationSummit-DC     09-26 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Education Summit-DC,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nation's Capital Left Out Of Education Summit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Education Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEROY TILLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The school system for President Bush's current
home town _ the District of Columbia _ was not on the invitation
list for the White House-sponsored education summit this week.
   ``What I was told by federal education officials is that the
district wasn't invited to the summit because the city doesn't have
a governor,'' D.C. public schools spokeswoman Patricia Lambe said
Tuesday.
   Bush has invited the governors of the 50 states as well as
Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands to the two-day conference
beginning Wednesday in Charlottesville, Va.
   Under the home rule charter from Congress, the mayor acts as
chief executive for the nation's capital. But relations have
appeared strained previously between Bush administration and Mayor
Marion Barry.
   When administration officials disclosed a series of steps to
curtail drug trafficking and violence in the District of Columbia
earlier this year, Barry wasn't present for the announcement.
   Ms. Lambe said she was ``taken aback'' after none of the
district's education officials was invited to the meeting.
   ``After all, when the federal Department of Education releases
education statistics, their figures include the district as well as
the other 50 states,'' she said.
   Standardized test scores for all students last year were about
10 percent below the national average. The nation's capital's
public school system was also plagued by a 40 percent student drop
out rate.
   Lon Anderson, director of public affairs for the U.S. Department
of Education, said, ``The fact is no education representative was
invited from the city because the district is not a state'' and has
no governor.
   Anderson said Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands were invited,
and noted that while they are not states, they have governors.
</TEXT>
