<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia     09-26 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slovenia Communists Approve Right to Secede from Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Slovenian communist leadership
on Tuesday unanimously endorsed proposed changes in the republic's
constitution that would give Slovenia the right to secede from
Yugoslavia, Tanjug news agency said.
   In addition, the federal presidency would have to seek Slovenian
approval to use Yugoslav army units in Slovenia.
   Belgrade radio said the Central Committee of the republic's
Communist Party ``expressed its determination'' to allow a final
vote on the amendments in the Slovenian parliament on Wednesday.
   Under the proposed amendments, Slovenia would have ``a lasting
and inalienable right to self-determination, including the right to
secession,'' Tanjug reported.
   Yugoslavia's collective eight-member presidency twice in the
past week issued statements saying the suggested amendments clashed
with the federal charter. The charter provides for the right of
each of Yugoslavia's six republics to secede, without specifying
how this could be accomplished.
   The national policy-setting Central Committee meanwhile met in
special session in Belgrade and wrangled over procedural issues
regarding the proposed constitutional amendments in Yugoslavia's
westernmost republic.
   Slovenian and Serbian party chiefs engaged in a sharp exchange.
   Slovenian party leader Milan Kucan said including the issue on
the agenda amounted to ``political pressure and restriction of the
sovereign will of the Slovenian people.''
   Bogdan Trifunovic, leader of Yugoslavia's largest Communist
Party of Serbia, said he considered Kucan's speech an open
declaration of hostilities.
   The Slovenian leadership said Tuesday the amendments in no way
contradicted the federal constitution.
   In a statement carried by Tanjug, Slovenia's ruling presidency
said federal criticism of the proposed changes could be construed
as indicating that the authorities were prepared to use force to
block their adoption.
   According to a report from Ljubljana, capital of Slovenia, the
Slovenian party Central Committee openly rejected criticism by the
federal authorities.
</TEXT>
