<FIRST>r i AM-Gadhafi     09-26 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gadhafi,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Calls for End to Moslem vs. Moslem Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi on Tuesday
decried Moslem vs. Moslem violence and said guns, bombs and
extremism should only be used to fight the enemies of Islam.
   The official Libyan news agency Jana, monitored in Rome, said
Gadhafi told an Islamic seminar in Tripoli that fighting between
Moslem factions only benefits enemies of the faith.
   There is in Islam a ``multitude of contradicting movements ...
some of which we made, some the Americans made and some were made
by the Mossad or the KGB,'' he said, referring to Israel's Mossad
Secret Service and the Soviet Union's KGB secret police.
   Gadhafi said the movements include fundamentalists who want to
return to the Islamic basics and maintain the religion's
traditions, morals and customs and other factions that have taken
``a secret, violent, terrorist and extremist trend'' for reasons of
power or wealth.
   ``If such extremism was against the enemies of Islam, then we
all must be extremists and choose violence against the Israelis to
liberate the Holy Land and Palestine ... against the Americans and
against the enemies of Islam to stop them where they are,'' he said.
   Jana said that Gadhafi addressed some 250 Moslem clerics,
activists and leaders from 48 countries who went to the Libyan
capital for the seminar sponsored by the World Council for Islamic
Call and the Organization of Islamic Conference.
   The agency quoted Gadhafi as saying, ``This religion is dying if
it resorts to bombs, guns, knives, working in the dark and
sabotaging Islamic activity from the inside. ... It also means that
this religion declares its end, its bankruptcy and its inability to
hold a dialogue, to offer and to launch a holy war.''
</TEXT>
