<FIRST>r w AM-Arafat-Visa 1stLd-Writethru   09-26 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arafat-Visa, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0633,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislators Say Arafat Should Not Be Granted Visa If He Asks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS seven grafs to identify senators signing letter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than two-thirds of the Senate urged the
Bush administration Tuesday to deny any visa request from Palestine
Liberation Organization leader Yasser Arafat to address the U.N.
General Assembly.
   Fifty-eight House members also wrote to President Bush,
contending Arafat should be denied a visa because he has not lived
up to his December promises to renounce terrorism and to recognize
Israel's right to exist.
   The 68 senators, 34 Democrats and 34 Republicans, made the same
point in a letter to Secretary of State James A. Baker III and
added:
   ``The PLO is on a collision course with the peace process.
Arafat and the PLO must reaffirm and implement, in deed and in
word, the statements of just nine months ago.
   ``Rewarding the PLO at this time would undercut the peace
process, call into question the seriousness of U.S. anti-terrorism
policy, be (contrary) to American interests and threaten the
security of Israel.''
   Both groups of lawmakers noted that former Secretary of State
George P. Shultz had denied Arafat a visa to address the General
Assembly last November. Shultz cited a U.S. law giving the
government the right to deny entry to anyone believed to have
engaged in terrorism, either as an individual or as a member of an
organization.
   Arafat has not applied for a visa this year but is widely
expected to do so. The denial of his visa request last year led to
an uproar at the United Nations and an invitation for him to
address a specially convened General Assembly session in Geneva.
   At a news conference, several of the lawmakers who signed the
letters said their intention was not to derail the dialogue between
Arafat and U.S. diplomats underway since his December pledge.
   ``This is not a message to halt the dialogue, but it is a
message that we want the dialogue to produce results,'' said Rep.
Mel Levine, D-Calif.
   Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., noted that the number of senators
requesting Arafat be denied a visa was 17 higher than the number
who had signed a similar letter to Shultz last year.
   ``This is an indication there is less trust for Mr. Arafat today
and an indication we believe his words are hollow,'' Mack said.
   Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., dismissed reports that Arafat had
agreed to endorse the terms of a 10-point peace proposal initiated
By Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
   ``Talk is cheap,'' Wilson said.
   Signing the letter to Baker were 34 Democrats and 34 Republicans.
   Democrats, in order of signing:
   Sens. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn.; Carl Levin, D-Mich.; Dennis
DeConcini, D-Ariz.; Wendell Ford, D-Ky.; J. James Exon, D-Neb.; Bob
Graham, D-Fla.; Herbert Kohl, D-Wis.; Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va.;
Paul Sarbanes, D-Md.; Alan Dixon, D-Ill.; Richard Bryan, D-Nev.;
Kent Conrad, D-N.D.; Daniel K. Inouye, D-Hawaii; Albert Gore,
D-Tenn.; Howell Heflin, D-Ala.; J. Bennett Johnston, D-La.;
   Also, Sens. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.; Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas;
Quentin Burdick, D-N.D.: Thomas Daschle, D-S.D.; John Breaux,
D-La.; Richard Shelby, D-Ala.; Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio; Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.; Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del.; Harry Reid,
D-Nev.; Jim Sasser, D-Tenn.; Tom Harkin, D-Iowa; John Kerry,
D-Mass.; Charles Robb, D-Va.; Bill Bradley, D-N.J.; Max Baucus,
D-Mont.; Donald Riegle, D-Mich.; David Boren, D-Okla.
   Republicans: Connie Mack, R-Fla.; Pete Wilson, R-Calif.; Charles
Grassley, R-Iowa; Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn.; Thad Cochran, R-Miss.;
Dan Coats, R-Ind.; Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.; Larry Pressler, R-S.D.;
Don Nickles, R-Okla.; Jesse Helms, R-N.C.; John McCain, R-Ariz.;
David Durenberger, R-Minn.; Conrad Burns, R-Mont.; Trent Lott,
R-Miss.; William Cohen, R-Maine;
   Also Phil Gramm, R-Texas; Orrin Hatch, R-Utah; Mitch McConnell,
R-Ky.; Robert Kasten, R-Wis.; Slade Gorton, R-Wash.; Malcolm
Wallop, R-Wyo.; Arlen Specter, R-Pa.; Ted Stevens, R-Alaska; Steve
Symms, R-Idaho.; John Heinz, R-Pa; Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska;
William Armstrong, R-Colo.; John Warner, R-Va.; Christopher Bond,
R-Mo.; William Roth, R-Del.; Bob Packwood, R-Ore.; Warren Rudman,
R-Vt.; Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H.; and Pete Domenici, R-N.M.
   A final listing of House members signing the letter to Bush was
not immediately available.
