<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 2009EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Shelter-FoodStamps     09-26 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shelter-Food Stamps,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Stay In Shelter Can't Jeopardize Food Stamps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A brief stay in a battered women's shelter
can't jeopardize food stamp benefits, a federal judge ruled.
   U.S. District Judge Harry MacLaughlin said the U.S. Department
of Agriculture violated its own regulations when it directed a
cutoff of food stamps for two women this year after they left
shelters for battered women.
   The USDA said payments by the state to battered women's shelters
had to be considered income when calculating the food stamp
eligibility of individual women who use the shelters.
   But MacLaughlin ruled Monday that the state's per-day payments
to 16 shelters around the state should be considered emergency
assistance, not a substitute for the shelter costs that are part of
a family's welfare grant.
   ``A battered woman does not come to a shelter to find housing,''
he wrote. ``She comes because she needs protection from imminent
physical danger and help in ending an abusive relationship.''
   The judge said fewer than half of the women who seek shelter can
be accommodated by existing facilities and the average stay is only
13 days.
   He gave the federal government and the Minnesota Department of
Human Services 60 days to come up with a plan for giving back to
welfare recipients the food stamps that were wrongfully withheld
from them while the policy was in effect, from Aug. 1, 1988, to
April 1 of this year.
   Charles Thomas, an attorney with Southern Minnesota Regional
Legal Services in Mankato, sued on behalf of the two women from
that southern Minnesota city of about 29,000 people.
   He said the lawsuit was a class action involving about 2,000
women and children in Minnesota who were hurt by the policy. The
ruling requires they be identified and reimbursed, he said.
   For one of the Mankato women, the amount was $250; for the
other, $124, Thomas said.
   ``While we may not look at the amount as especially significant,
to these women it may mean survival,'' said Assistant Attorney
General Gail Olson. Olson said the state agreed with Thomas'
position that the shelter services should not be considered income
but was forced to go along with the federal interpretation or face
sanctions.
   ``There was more at stake here besides benefits,'' said Loretta
Frederick, director of legal advocacy for the Minnesota Coalition
for Battered Women. Frederick said the federal policy had the
``absurd result'' of forcing women to choose between getting their
children out of an unsafe home or feeding them.
   Some women were not going into shelters, or were leaving shortly
after getting into them, because they could not afford to go
without food stamps, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
