<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Chemical     09-26 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Chemical,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chemical Weapons Will Be Hard to Ban in Middle East</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Arms Control</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTY KUFUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli officials on Tuesday welcomed President
Bush's proposal to eliminate chemical weapons, but experts
suggested the Middle East would pose a major problem area for
putting the plan into effect.
   Avi Pazner, a spokesman for Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, said
Israel backed the call for wiping out stockpiles but declined to
comment on the possibility of doing so within 10 years as Bush
proposed.
   ``Israel supports very much the banning of all chemical
weapons,'' he said.
   ``We have warned many times that Arab countries are arming
themselves with such weapons and have in some cases used them
against civilian populations.''
   Pazner noted Iraq and Iran used chemical weapons during the
8-year Persian Gulf conflict and reports also surfaced of Syria and
Libya manufacturing them.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said, ``Israel's position is that we are totally against
stocking or using chemical weapons and any action that leads to the
suppression of chemical arms is welcomed and supported by Israel.
   ``We hope that there will be a worldwide movement so that all
these weapons will be destroyed and never put to use again.''
   Bush proposed Monday that America would eliminate all of its
chemical arms within 10 years if the Soviet Union and other
countries do the same.
   Israeli military analyst Aharon Levran, a retired army brigadier
general, said Arab countries probably would balk at giving up
chemical weapons that they saw as a counter to Israel's reported
nuclear capability.
   He also suggested Arab countries may attach political
conditions, such as Israeli withdrawal from lands captured in war
with Arab states.
   Israel has never confirmed it, but foreign reports say Israel
has nuclear and chemical weapons as well as long-range missiles
capable of delivering them.
   Israel is considering nationwide deployment of protective masks
to counter the eventuality of chemical weapons. Civil defense
authorities are conducting a yearlong trial in which 3,000
residents of two towns were given such masks.
   Israeli soldiers have been equipped with modern, protective
masks and suits as well as detection and decontamination equipment.
   Iraq is known to have chemical weapons, including mustard gas
and the nerve agent Sarin. It used mustard gas against enemy
soldiers while fighting Iran, and against civilians in Kurdistan,
according to an assessment by Levran and members of an Israeli
research group.
   Syria has extensive stockpiles of chemical weapons, including
the nerve gas Sarin, the report said. Libya also is believed to
have poison gas. Egypt also has stockpiles of poison gas, according
to the report by the Jaffee Center for Strategic Studies in Tel
Aviv.
   Levran said he doubted Iraq would heed Bush's call.
   ``The Iraqis are afraid that one day the Iranians will amass the
forces and overrun them,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
