<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 2030EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-JusticeMisconduct     09-26 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Justice Misconduct,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vermont Supreme Court Suspends Former Justice for Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER GRAFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vermont Supreme Court on Tuesday
barred a former justice from hearing cases in retirement after
finding him guilty of misconduct while on the bench.
   William Hill, 72, received the harshest possible penalty for
seven violations of judicial canons, including his participation in
cases involving a a friend, who was then an assistant judge.
   Hill was the first justice of the Vermont Supreme Court to be
found guilty of judicial misconduct. Special prosecutor Douglas
Richards said he sought the reprimand and suspension to assure
judges are held to the highest standards.
   The allegations against Hill first came to light in January 1987
and he retired that April when his term ended. He was first
appointed in 1976.
   Hill has repeatedly refused to comment on the allegations.
   Michael Marks, Hill's lawyer, urged justices not to suspend him,
saying that his reputation has suffered irreparable harm.
   ``At most, Justice Hill was guilty of misjudgments,'' said
Marks. ``After 28 years in service to this court and to the
judiciary, this is the blemish of his record, the blemish on which
some people may remember him.''
   Hill was found guilty last week of ethics violations. He was
also found guilty of intimidating state Attorney General Jeffrey
Amestoy by personally delivering a letter to him urging a criminal
investigation of Jane Wheel be speeded up.
   Wheel was then an assistant judge, an elected official who helps
presiding Superior Court judges. She pleaded no contest to
allegations of judicial misconduct and faces a jail term for her
perjury conviction in a separate proceeding.
   As a retired justice, Hill could have been asked to preside over
cases but he had not been used since his retirement.
</TEXT>
