<DOCNO> AP890926-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 2031EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DrugPlans     09-26 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Plans,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Giving Airlines More Time To Develop Drug Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration is
extending its deadline for air carriers to submit plans for
anti-drug programs, including random testing of employees,
officials said Tuesday.
   FAA spokesman Fred Farrar said 22 of 130 carriers using planes
capable of carrying more than 30 passengers have failed to submit
their plans, orginally due Aug. 18. A federally mandated anti-drug
program for the aviation industry takes effect Dec. 18.
   The new deadline for submitting proposals is Oct. 9, Farrar said.
   He said just over 100 companies using smaller planes have
submitted proposals for implementing the program, which requires
employment, post-accident and random drug testing.
   FAA officials said it is difficult to tell how many of the
estimated 3,000 smaller aviation companies might be covered by the
law, since it covers only those with more than 50 employees.
   The agency has sent letters to hundreds of companies warning
them that it will take legal action if they fail to meet the Oct. 9
deadline.
   ``The FAA recognizes that since this is a new requirement and
involves comprehensive planning and implementation, the airline
industry has faced numerous difficult tasks in developing anti-drug
plans,'' the FAA letters say.
   Airlines that fail to comply face penalties of up to $10,000 for
each day their plan has not been submitted. Farrar said no fines
will be assessed until after the new deadline.
   The FAA has 60 days to approve each company's plan.
</TEXT>
