<FIRST>r a AM-CrashInvestigation     09-26 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crash Investigation,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Opens; Investigators Continue Picking Over Wreckage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators looking into the crash of
a USAir jet said Tuesday that almost all the tread on the front
tires was gone, but there was no indication the wheels had jammed.
   The finding about the front wheels would be consistent with the
pilot's statements that he had tried o bring the jet to a halt
before it skidded off the runway into the East River on Sept. 20,
said Ted Lopatkiewicz, a National Transportation Safety Board
spokesman.
   Two people were killed and 59 others were rescued from the water
after the pilot aborted takeoff of Flight 5050 at LaGuardia Airport.
   Although 95 percent of the tread on the front tires was gone,
the main landing gear under the wings looked normal, Lopatkiewicz
said. The wing flaps were all in normal takeoff position.
   Investigators reported earlier that the front wheels were locked
sharply to the right, indicating that the pilot had turned the
tiller to counteract a drift to the left.
   Capt. Michael W. Martin told investigators that he aborted the
takeoff because the aircraft was moving left and he felt and heard
a strange vibration.
   Investigators planned to look inside the engines of the Boeing
737-400 for additional clues to the cause of the crash.
   John J. Santucci, district attorney for the borough of Queens,
who has launched a grand jury investigation of the pilots' conduct,
said Monday that urine samples taken two days after the accident
contained no sign of drug or alcohol use by the pilot or copilot of
Flight 5050.
   Martin and his copilot, Constantine Kleissas, were criticized by
federal officials for failing to submit to testing immediately
after the crash, although they are not legally required to do so.
   Medical experts said alcohol would usually not show up in urine
samples taken two days after ingestion, although drugs such as
marijuana or cocaine probably would.
</TEXT>
