<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo-IslandRefugees     09-26 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Island Refugees,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>St. Croix Refugees Calling Shelters Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOMESTEAD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A noisy high school gymnasium is serving
as a shelter for a stream of refugees who fled hurricane-battered
St. Croix with little money or clothes and tales of destruction.
   More than 500 people have used the shelter since it was set up
Friday by the American Red Cross at Homestead Senior High School.
On Tuesday, 129 people remained, eating free food and resting on
cots while relief workers tried to contact friends or relatives
willing to take them in.
   ``We lost our house and we had nowhere to stay down there, and
with all the looting we had no money,'' said Ansylma John, 16, who
arrived with her mother and four younger siblings.
   ``We're looking for a house (in Florida). That's the main
thing,'' she said, keeping an eye on the children and a few
possessions stacked near their assigned cots.
   The Air Force has flown more than 1,000 people from the
Caribbean islands to Homestead Air Force Base south of Miami since
Hurricane Hugo struck Sept. 17. Other planes brought survivors to
MacDill Air Force Base in Tampa.
   Some children arrived alone, Red Cross officials said.
   ``We're trying to work with state officials to help the handful
of kids who have arrived unaccompanied,'' said Tom Donia, a
spokesman in Miami for the relief agency. ``We would pay for
transporting them to friends or relatives.''
   When Hugo slammed into the U.S. Virgin Islands, it destroyed or
damaged 97 percent of the homes on St. Croix before heading to the
U.S. mainland.
   Red Cross volunteers said most refugees want to return to St.
Croix, but several refugees said Tuesday the island had little to
offer them after being ravaged by the hurricane and the widespread
looting that followed.
   ``It looked like an A-bomb went off,'' said Daryl Barnes, 38, a
lawyer staying at the MacDill shelter who said looters took
advantage of the chaos. ``It was outrageous ... everything was out
of hand.''
   While children played tag or slept, parents told of plans to
rebuild their lives from scratch.
   ``I lose everything, my new refrigerator, my sofa, everything
gone,'' said Olga Melendez, 19, who watched her 2-year-old son
while her husband tried to reach an uncle in Tampa. ``Even my
wedding ring. It was in a jewelry box, gone.''
</TEXT>
