<DOCNO> AP890926-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 2023EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-PEN     09-26 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-PEN,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rushdie Case Not an Isolated Incident, Writers Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salman Rushdie isn't the only writer living in an
Islamic community who faces threats, intimidation and de facto
censorship, the PEN international writers association said Tuesday.
   Alexander Blokh, PEN's international secretary, said a writer
with an Islamic background ``can be in a very free city ... and yet
he lives in a very permanent state of terror, discreet terror.''
   The association, holding its world congress in Toronto,
recommended its member chapters invite writers from the Islamic
community to discuss such situations, their causes and the means to
find a solution.
   ``We would ask them to come and very discreetly tell us their
story if they want to,'' Blokh said at a news conference.
   Blokh said PEN learned about such cases in Paris and London as
it prepared protests of the death sentence by Iran over the
bestselling novel ``The Satanic Verses,'' which sent Rushdie into
hiding. The late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini ordered Rushie's death
in February, saying Islam was slandered by the book.
   He said he also knew of one similar case of pressuring a writer
in Moscow.
   ``I'm not going to tell you any concrete cases because they are
still quite secret,'' Blokh said.
   He said only the Rushdie case was known to have ``official
status,'' issued by a government, but other incidents of
``religious fanaticism'' could be considered a new threat to
freedom of expression that had not been anticipated at the end of
the 20th century.
   The known cases consist of ``pressures, intimidation, sometimes
direct threats'' against Islamic writers in English and French,
Blokh said. He said the new form of censorship discovered only
recently was ``something for which we're not prepared.''
   The threats were coming not from a government but from a ``very
hard to define'' community, he said.
   The recommendation on intolerance and fanaticism, as translated
by The AP from a French copy, said the Rushdie incident ``is not
isolated and revealed many other pressures, happily less grave'' on
writers that may stem from diplomatic, family, community, religious
or terrorist sources.
   The PEN conference moves Wednesday to Montreal before concluding
Friday. It is the association's first meeting in North America
since a heavily publicized 1986 New York event.
   PEN, founded in 1921, has 11,000 members in more than 60
chapters organized along language lines. It is an international
association of poets, playrights, editors, essayists and novelists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
