<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Drugs     09-26 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Drugs,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexican Attorney General Says Camarena Killers Will Get 150 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The killers of U.S. drug agent Enrique
Camarena Salazar each will be sentenced to an average of 150 years
in prison in the next two months, Mexico's attorney general said
Tuesday.
   Enrique Alvarez del Castillo conceded that numerous judicial
delays had occurred since Rafael Caro Quintero and 28 others were
convicted in the Camarena case, but said sentencing now was
expected in November.
   ``We Mexicans are convinced drug trafficking can only be beaten
through effective and energetic international action,'' he said in
a statement one week before President Carlos Salinas de Gortari's
first official visit to the United States.
   With drug trafficking a major item on the U.S.-Mexico agenda,
Alvarez outlined Mexico's progress 10 months into Salinas' term.
Salinas is due to meet President Bush in Washington and speak
before Congress.
   Alvarez said more than 8,000 people have been arrested on drug
charges, almost 22 tons of cocaine base have been seized,
enforcement and training has been toughened, and laws have been
changed to increase prison time for narcotics violators and corrupt
officials.
   He said funds to investigate and prevent drug-related offenses
were increased 133 percent, to more than $50 million. He noted that
15 Mexican drug enforcement agents were killed on duty in the last
10 months.
   U.S. officials have praised the Salinas administration's
efforts. One official called last April's arrest of Miguel Felix
Gallardo, named as a drug kingpin, nothing less than a ``miracle.''
   The 1985 killing of Camarena, a U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration agent who was working in Guadalajara, has been a
sensitive issue.
   Alvarez defended the Caro Quintero prosecution, saying it was a
complex case that involved numerous drug traffickers. In answer to
questions, he said sentences would ``average'' 150 years in prison
but gave no details.
   Camarena and his Mexican pilot were kidnapped on Feb. 7, 1985.
Their bodies, bearing signs of torture, were found a month later on
a ranch 60 miles southeast of Guadalajara.
   Alvarez said Mexico was working more closely than ever with the
United States on such issues as tracing laundered drug money and
drug lords' assets.
   However, he said allowing ``hot pursuit'' of suspected drug
traffickers' airplanes across the border was a ``stupid
discussion'' _ the United States would not permit such a violation
of sovereignty and neither would Mexico.
   Alvarez said Salinas ordered him to make a public report on the
administration's anti-drug efforts. He denied that Mexico was
putting on a ``show'' in advance of the meeting with Bush.
   ``This is not a `show' nor is there anything in the slightest
theatrical about this,'' said Castillo, who was sitting on a podium
surrounded by 6.3 tons of cocaine in thousands of white and brown
packages.
   The cocaine had been seized in the last two months, Alvarez
said, most of it along the U.S.-Mexico border.
   Alvarez said he did not know if increased enforcement efforts
had reduced the flow of drugs to the United States.
   ``We only know how much we seize,'' Alvarez said. ``We don't
really know how much gets through.''
   Drug use in Mexico is still very low compared to the United
States, Alvarez said, but prevention and rehabilitation programs
are also being reinforced.
   Alvarez said it will be two or three months before the effect of
the crackdown on drug cartels by Colombia in the last month can be
known. He said there had not yet been any visible effect on the
amount of drugs in the pipeline.
</TEXT>
