<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-PoliceChief     09-26 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Police Chief,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Mexico Police Chief Sentenced for Arms Smuggling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Police Chief Arturo Durazo, who was
said to have made millions of dollars from extortion, smuggling and
drug dealing while in office, was sentenced to six years in jail
Tuesday on arms possession charges.
   Durazo, who served as Mexico City's police chief from 1976 to
1982, has already served five years in prison but still faces
sentencing on charges of fraud, smuggling and extortion.
   He fled Mexico after his friend and patron, President Jose Lopez
Portillo, left office. FBI agents arrested him in Puerto Rico in
1984, but he fought extradition for 1{ years while held by U.S.
authorities.
   He watched from behind a grill as Judge Jose Luis Garcia Vasco's
sentence of two years and a 2,000-peso (80 cent) fine on each of
three counts was read.
   ``I don't agree with this sentence,'' Durazo told reporters.
   He said he will appeal.
   Durazo was charged with illegally possessing 52 pistols but said
as police chief he had a right to keep weapons and some of the
weapons were replicas.
   Durazo was a childhood friend of Lopez Portillo's and became one
of Mexico's most powerful men when Lopez Portillo became president.
   He built mansions, one with a race track, and had 1,200 personal
employees. Some servants wore gold-trimmed uniforms. All were on
the police payroll.
   Among other charges, police officers allegedly had to pay Durazo
fees every two weeks to keep their jobs.
   He is now held up by members of President Carlos Salinas de
Gortari's administration as a prime example of the bad old days of
corruption in Mexico.
   All his houses, including those outside Ixtapa and Mexico City,
have been expropriated.
</TEXT>
