<FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Election     09-26 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Election,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quebec Voters Show Support Still Lingers for Separatism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada must grapple again with tensions between
its English- and French-speaking populations after Quebec's
provincial election showed continued support for the separatist
Parti Quebecois.
   There also was a surprising vote in Monday's election for a new
Equality Party formed by English-speaking Canadians irate over
Quebec's language policies that favor French.
   Although Quebec Premier Robert Bourassa led his Liberal Party to
almost as large a majority as it won four years ago, it lost some
support to the revitalized Parti Quebecois and the Equality Party.
   The provincial assembly will have 92 Liberal deputies, 29 from
the Parti Quebecois and four from Equality.
   In the December 1985 election, the Liberals ousted the Parti
Quebecois, which had been in power for nine years, and won 99 of
the then-122 seats in the assembly.
   ``They said the idea (of an independent, French-speaking Quebec)
was dead; it is alive,'' a jubilant Jacques Parizeau said Monday
night. He led an internal Parti Quebecois struggle last year that
placed it back on a policy of eventual independence.
   Just months ago it appeared the Parti Quebecois faced extinction
but under Parizeau it won 40 percent of the popular vote Monday.
   The percentage was a slight increase from 1985 and was similar
to the vote in a 1980 referendum when the province's electorate
defeated the Parti Quebecois' policy of separatism.
   Parizeau won a seat in the Quebec assembly and is expected to be
a strong leader of the separatists.
   He calls for control to be gradually taken away from the federal
government over Quebec's family, language, cultural, social and
development policies with a provincial referendum to be held on
each issue.
   A constitution then would be drafted for Quebec and it would be
submitted to a vote.
   Parizeau has offered no timetable for his plan.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, a native of Quebec and leader of
the Progressive Conservatives, told reporters in Ottawa Tuesday
that the Parti Quebecois has had steady support since the 1970s and
Monday's balloting didn't change that.
   He was asked if he was concerned and replied, ``The answer of
course is no, not at all.'' The Progressive Conservatives and
Liberals are Canada's largest political parties.
   About 81 percent of Quebec's 6.5 million people speak French
while English is the dominant language in the country's nine other
provinces.
   Bourassa said the election Monday was a ``truly decisive
victory'' for the Liberals and ``confirms the confidence of the
majority of Quebecers in the federal regime.''
   But the wins by the Equality Party will make it more difficult
for Bourassa to maneuver between the French- and English-speaking
sentiments in the province.
   Quebec's Liberals traditionally count on support from the
English-speaking minority and the Equality Party drew from that
source.
   In December, Bourassa refused to allow more than a token change
in provincial laws restricting commercial signs to the French
language. His compromise allowed bilingual signs only indoors with
the French-language portion significantly larger than the English.
   Robert Libman, leader of the Equality Party, was happy with
Monday's results and in a speech delivered in English and French he
said:
   ``A significant segment of Quebec's population who share a
vision of Canada and Quebec now have the political representation
that they need. The English and French must speak to one another.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
