<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Spending 2ndLd-Writethru a0798 09-26 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Spending, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0798,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bipartisan Anti-Drug Compromise Frees 1990 Spending Bills</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS two grafs with negative votes in lieu of roll calls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate passed two long-delayed spending
bills Tuesday as a 13-day partisan standoff began to ease, while
the House braced for a looming budget mess by approving legislation
to keep the government in business next month.
   On an 89-11 tally, the Senate approved a $14.4 billion foreign
aid measure for next year that would provide $45 million in
assistance to Poland's new non-communist government. It then voted
81-19 for a $157.4 billion bill for labor, health and education
programs containing slightly liberalized abortion rules.
   Across the Capitol, the House voted 274-152 to send the Senate a
bill pumping enough money to federal agencies to let them function
through Oct. 25. The vote came just five days before the start of
the new fiscal year.
   The Senate had completed debate on the two spending bills last
week. But votes on final approval were delayed while Democrats and
Republicans held private talks on rival proposals to beef up the
government's efforts against illegal drugs. Those negotiations
neared completion Tuesday.
   The assistance to Poland provided by the foreign aid measure far
exceeded the $10 million President Bush has proposed making
available. The measure would also boost U.S. military aid to El
Salvador by $5 million to $90 million.
   Under the eased abortion rules, women who are pregnant because
of rape or incest would qualify for federal aid to pay for
abortions, expanding the current criteria by which such assistance
is paid only when a mother's life is in danger.
   The bill would also withhold some federal aid from states that
do not require the notification of people whose spouses have AIDS.
   Both bills can't be sent to Bush for his signature until the
Senate and House work out resolve their different verswions of each.
   Final action on an $11.9 billion transportation bill was
withheld as party leaders work out final details of an anti-drug
package. Passage of a $67.2 billion measure for veterans, housing
and space programs was also postponed while lawmakers considered
bolstering it with aid for communities hit by Hurricane Hugo last
week.
   Congress has sent President Bush just one of the 13 annual
spending bills for the new fiscal year, even though they are
supposed to be completed by Oct. 1, the start of fiscal 1990.
   The rest of the measures have been slowed by Congress' earlier
distraction with the problems of former House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, its work on an emergency spending bill for this year and
the question of how much money the government should spend battling
the drug problem.
   Missing deadlines for approval of spending bills is nothing new
for Congress. When lawmakers finished all 13 of the measures for
1989 one minute before midnight last Sept. 30, it was the first
time they had done so in 12 years.
   Because of that, during Tuesday's brief House debate on the
temporary spending bill, the ranking Republican on the House
Appropriations Committee, Rep. Silvio Conte of Massachusetts,
suggested a new version of ``Auld Lang Syne'' for the new federal
fiscal year.
   ``Should all deadlines be forgot and never met on time,'' Conte
told his colleagues.
   The temporary spending measure has the support of the Bush
administration. Lawmakers hope that by the time it expires, they
will have completed work on the remaining 12 spending measures.
   Here are the negative votes in the 89-11 passage of the foreign
aid bill: William Armstrong, R-Colo.; Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.; Alan
Dixon, D-Ill.; Jake Garn, R-Utah; Jesse Helms, R-N.C.; Earnest
Hollings, D-S.C.; Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H.: James McClure, R-Idaho;
William Roth, R-Del.; Steven Symms, R-Idaho and Malcolm Wallop,
R-Wyo.
   Here are the negative votes in the 81-19 passage of the labor,
health and education bill: Armstrong; Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn.; Kent
Conrad, D-N.D.; Dixon; David Durenberger, R-Minn.; Garn; Slade
Gorton, R-Wash.; Orrin Hatch, R-Utah; Howell Heflin, D-Ala.; Helms;
Humphrey; Richard Lugar, R-Ind.; John McCain, R-Ariz.; McClure; Don
Nickles, R-Okla.; Roth; Symms; Wallop and John Warner, R-Va.
</TEXT>
