<FIRST>r a AM-Brites SUB a0639 09-26 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites, SUB, a0639,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS NEW CASTLE, Ind.-dated item to CORRECT division, line,
model order; CORRECTS that Valiant was a Chrysler product, sted Chrysler.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW CASTLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most automotive speed machines come in
colors other than passionate pink, but no one laughs when John
Mitchell arrives in his magenta Plymouth Valiant Duster.
   The 1970 Chrysler product, with a rare model of engine, may be
worth several times its price paid back in those days when a car
could be had for under $3,000.
   ``The paint name is magenta, nicknamed panther pink,'' said
Bruce Friar of Anderson, who helped Mitchell restore the original
sheen.
   ``We had to call (the manufacturer) and get the formula. They
only painted 12 originally, and being the kind of car it is, it's
extremely rare.''
   The number of these classic pink muscle cars yet remaining could
probably be counted on one hand. Mitchell says his, which has just
40,000 miles on it, may be the only one that's been completely
restored.
   ``A friend of mine (who) deals in high-performance cars said
that it's worth at least $15,000 to $20,000, and said if it's the
only one, you could probably name your price,'' Mitchell said.
   Not that it's for sale, said Mitchell, who has worked for
Chrysler Corp. in New Castle for 23 years.
   ``I'm probably going to hang onto it,'' he said. ``I'd hate to
get rid of something and not know what it's worth.''
</TEXT>
