<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     09-26 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report 40 Killed a Day Before Cease-Fire to Take Effect</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police reported at least 40 people
were killed Tuesday in ethnic violence a day before a cease-fire
declared by the government in its battle with Sinhalese militants.
   The predominantly Sinhalese government declared a unilateral
cease-fire beginning Wednesday in central and southern Sri Lanka
but there has been no response from the People's Liberation Front.
The front was formed by militant Sinhalese who accuse the
government of granting too many concessions to the Tamil minority.
   Police and military officials said most of the 40 people killed
Tuesday were members or supporters of the People's Liberation Front.
   They said the bodies of 17 Sihnhalese militants were found in
two villages in Kandy, a district 55 miles northeast of Colombo,
and 13 bodies of Sinhalese were reported in several southern
hamlets.
   The Information Ministry reported security forces killed six
Sinhalese radicals in two incidents and blamed Sinhalese militants
in the deaths of four civilians. It also said 297 suspected
extremists had been arrested.
   Military helicopters on Tuesday dropped 200,000
Sinhalese-language leaflets, in areas where the People's Liberation
Front has been active, urging the militants to surrender.
   ``Take advantage of this opportunity and give yourself up,''
said the leaflets. ``You will be warmly received and will be fully
protected.''
   Most of Sri Lanka's Tamils live in northern and eastern zones of
the island and Tamil separatists began fighting six years ago for
their own homeland. The Sinhalese militants opened their revolt
against the government two years ago, accusing it of bowing to
Tamil demands.
   Tamils, most of whom are Hindus, form 18 percent of the
country's 16 million people and the predominantly Buddhist
Sinhalese 75 percent.
   More than 5,000 people, most of them government officials and
security personnel, have been killed in the Sinhalese uprising.
   At least 11,000 people have been killed in violence related to
the Tamil insurgency.
</TEXT>
