<FIRST>u w AM-JailedMother 1stLd-Writethru   09-26 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jailed Mother, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0730,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Released From Jail Says Daughter is Fine</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS ``alright'' to ``all right'' in 2nd graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother jailed for more than two years in a
bitter child custody dispute said Tuesday her daughter is fine and
she is proud of her.
   Dr. Elizabeth Morgan, who was released from the District of
Columbia Jail on Monday, said her daughter Hilary ``is not only all
right she is more than all right.''
   ``Two years ago, she was a terrified, traumatized victim of
incest,'' Morgan said on WUSA-TV. ``Today she is a proud, happy
girl who knows she is worth protecting, and I am very proud of
her.''
   Morgan was jailed in August 1987 after she failed to produce
Hilary, now 7, for a supervised court-ordered visit with her
father, Dr. Eric Foretich. Morgan claims Foretich sexually abused
the child; Foretich has repeatedly denied the allegation.
   Morgan's release was the result of a law passed by Congress and
signed by President Bush last week limiting civil contempt jail
terms in the District of Columbia to 12 months. The law expires
after 18 months.
   Foretich, appearing Tuesday on ABC's ``Good Morning America''
program, said he was glad Morgan was out of jail.
   ``I only wish this could be coupled with some concern for my
missing daughter. I would have been in support of that bill if the
bill had a provision mandating a government agency such as the FBI
be required to find my daughter,'' Foretich said.
   Morgan has declined to reveal the girl's whereabouts.
   At a news conference late Monday, Morgan said that for the
immediate future, she would spend time with her fiance, federal
appeals court judge Paul R. Michel.
   ``I will go wherever my fiance takes me,'' Morgan said. When
Michel was asked about his plans for the couple, he only smiled and
shook his head.
   ``I'd rather not say,'' Michel said.
   Morgan said she wanted a thick steak, salad and a bottle of red
wine.
   ``Oh, I suppose I'll get my hair cut, my teeth cleaned, the
kinds of things I haven't been able to do for the past two years,''
she said. ``Beyond that, I cannot say.''
   Morgan credited a groundswell of grassroots support with
creating the climate for the drafting of the congressional
legislation that ultimately freed her.
   ``I am very happy, and very grateful, for those who backed me
and stayed with me,'' Morgan said. ``They made the difference.''
</TEXT>
