<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 2234EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-UNRdp     09-26 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN Rdp,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Envoy Warns Movements Against Terrorism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze on Tuesday condemned violence by national movements
and liberation struggles and said noble ends do not justify violent
means.
   He did not praise the Palestinian struggle against Israeli
occupation of captured Arab lands in his speech to the General
Assembly, and the message to the Palestine Liberation Organization
and other movements was unmistakable:
   ``Freedom must not be sought at the expense of others.
   ``No support or sympathy should be extended to the so-called
movements that allow actions humiliating other nations, or use
terrorist, barbaric and inhuman methods in waging their struggle.''
   It was the most explicit renunciation yet of violence by groups
which Moscow has supported in the past _ from those in Africa to
the Middle East.
   ``The time has come finally to realize that not all means are
good for attaining even the most noble ends ... The international
community condemns and outlaws terrorism.
   ``We need equally determined action against any kind of
violence, whatever the motives or excuses for it,'' he said.
   Shevardnadze did not discuss specific conflicts, but emphasized
the importance of international cooperation and moral behavior by
all nations and groups.
   He addressed condemnation of violence in his speech even before
disarmament and acceptance of President Bush's call to slash
chemical weapons stockpiles.
   Diplomats said it signified a greater Soviet commitment to live
up to its words about norms of international civilized behavior and
common human values.
   They also cited Soviet desire to improve relations with Israel
and to seek a comprehensive settlement in the Middle East.
   ``Violence by the state against its own people must be ruled out
altogether,'' Shevardnadze said. ``Violence on national, ethnic or
religious grounds must no longer be tolerated.
   ``We advocate freedom of choice.
   ``However, we reject its interpretation as a license to use any
means, to commit any violence or to shed blood.''
   Shevardnadze admitted Moscow was disappointed by the setback of
the Polish Communist Party, but said, ``We are in no way
prejudiced'' against the new government, led by non-communists.
   ``We wish it every success and are ready to cooperate with it. .
.. We see nothing threatening in the fact that a coalition
government has been formed in accordance with the will of the
Polish people.''
   He said that if tolerance ``is mandatory for us in our attitude
toward the current government of Poland, why are others so
intolerant as regards, say, Cuba?''
   It was a clear reference to U.S. dislike of Cuban Communist
leader Fidel Castro.
   In his first address since he became Japan's foreign minister
last month, Taro Nakayama explained the new, activist foreign
policy of his government Tuesday, including a greater, non-military
role in U.N. peacekeeping worldwide.
   Nakayama also said Japan would welcome simultaneous or separate
U.N. membership for both South and North Korea and said Tokyo was
trying to improve its own relations with Pyongyang.
   He said Japan seeks to improve its relations with Moscow and
resolve the issue of the Soviet-occupied Northern Territories.
   Nakayama said ``recent events in China'' disturbed the Japanese,
a reference to the violent suppression of a student-led democracy
movement in June. But he said Japan expects China's policies of
reform and openness to remain unchanged.
   Nakayama announced that Japan is prepared to provide $600
million from 1990 to 1992 to help the poorest countries in
sub-Saharan Africa and elsewhere restructure their economies.
   ``As Japan interacts with the rest of the world more intensively
and in a broader spectrum of fields,'' he said, ``it realizes that
it must play a more active role in international affairs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890926-0220 </DOCNO>
