<HEAD>`Cosby' Returns To No. 1 Spot, `Chicken Soup' Chilling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, `A special...' to CORRECT that ``Doogie Howser''
tied with ``Murder She Wrote'' for 6th place sted ranking alone in 7th
place. Picks up 11th graf, `NBC also...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Cosby Show'' turned up the Nielsen
ratings heat with its sixth season premiere, taking its first No. 1
spot since February and pushing ``Roseanne'' into No. 2. ``Chicken
Soup'' showed signs of chilling.
   ``The Cosby Show,'' featuring the return of Lisa Bonet's
character Denise with a new husband and child in tow, had a 26.1
rating and 44 percent of the Thursday night audience for NBC.
``Cosby's'' last No. 1 rating was Feb. 27.
   NBC had six of the Top 10 shows, including returning veterans
``Cheers,'' ``The Golden Girls'' and ``Matlock.'' ABC had three
shows and CBS had one.
   Ratings are the percentage of the estimated 90.4 million homes
with television sets in the United States. The share is the
percentage of sets in use.
   New shows in the Top 20 were a premiere of ``Hardball'' on NBC,
in 16th place, and CBS' ``Major Dad,'' which captured 20th place.
   A Bob Hope special dedicated to the late comedian Lucille Ball
on NBC was ranked 11th with a 19.3 rating.
   ``Roseanne,'' on ABC, captured a 24.7 rating and a 38 percent
share of the audience, according to figures released Monday by the
A.C. Nielsen Co.
   Comic Jackie Mason's ``Chicken Soup,'' after placing No. 2 in
the ratings last week behind ``Roseanne,'' fell to 14th place in
its second week. ``Chicken Soup'' follows ``Roseanne'' on Tuesday
night, but lost 6.3 rating points in the transition, with an 18.4
percent rating and 29 share.
   ``Chicken Soup'' played opposite a season premiere of
``Matlock'' on NBC and CBS' new series, ``Wolf.''
   A special Tuesday preview of ``Doogie Howser, M.D.,'' producer
Steven Bochco's latest entry for ABC, tied with CBS' ``Murder She
Wrote'' for sixth place. The show about a teen-age doctor got a
20.7 rating and a 32 share of the audience. Its regular time slot
is Wednesday night, where it earned a 14.4 rating and 23 share for
33rd place.
   NBC also scored with its 15th anniversary show for ``Saturday
Night Live,'' broadcast in prime time Sunday night against ABC's
``The Preppie Murders.'' The ``Saturday Night'' special was No. 8,
while the movie about the slaying of a young socialite in Central
Park was 26th.
   The Top 10 shows and their ratings were: ``The Cosby Show,''
NBC, 26.1; ``Roseanne,'' ABC, 24.7; ``Cheers,'' NBC, 24.1; ``Golden
Girls,'' NBC, 23.5; ``Sister Kate,'' NBC, 23; ``Murder, She
Wrote,'' CBS, 20.7; ``Doogie Howser, M.D.'' ABC, 20.7; ``Saturday
Night Live 15th Anniversary Show,'' NBC, 20.3; ``Matlock,'' NBC,
19.6; and ``Who's the Boss,'' ABC, 19.5.
   New shows featuring television veterans did not grab top spots
with viewers. NBC's ``The Nutt House,'' starring Cloris Leachman
and Harvey Korman and produced by Mel Brooks, checked in at No. 24.
   ``Island Son,'' marking the return of Richard Chamberlain to
series television was in 42nd place for CBS. ``A Peaceable
Kingdom,'' starring onetime bionic woman Lindsay Wagner, was a
less-than-overpowering 65th place for CBS.
   Under network programming tactics, new shows are either
premiered or previewed _ the latter signifying a show broadcast
outside its assigned time slot. Some new series had two broadcasts
during the week.
   The highest ratings for other-new-show previews and premieres
for the week include ``The Famous Teddy Z,'' CBS, No. 22; ``Perfect
Strangers,'' ABC, No. 29; ``Free Spirit,'' ABC, No. 30; ``The
People Next Door,'' CBS, No. 31; ``Family Matters,'' ABC, No. 38;
``The Young Riders,'' ABC, No. 40; ``Baywatch,'' NBC, No. 48; ``Top
of the Hill,'' CBS, No. 55; ``Snoops,'' CBS, No. 57; ``Life Goes
On,'' ABC, No. 61; ``Saturday Night with Connie Chung,'' CBS, No.
72.
   Fox Network's ``Booker'' premiered in 77th place.
   CBS' ``48 Hours'' special on Hurricane Hugo was in 39th place.
   The nightly network news shows were ranked as follows: ``CBS
Evening News,'' in first place with an 11.2 rating; ``ABC World
News Tonight'' in second with 10.2; and ``NBC Nightly News'' in
third, also with a 10.2 rating. The ABC rating is based on four
nights due to satellite problems Wednesday. Nielsen Co. has told
ABC it will revise the numbers at a later date.
   The five lowest-rated network shows for the week were: ABC's
``Mission: Impossible,'' CBS' ``Wolf,'' CBS's ``Saturday Night with
Connie Chung,'' an ABC ``College Football Special, Michigan Vs.
UCLA,'' and an NBC ``Alf'' special.
   Overall, NBC continued first in the ratings for the 66th week in
a row, with 16.7 rating and a 28 percent share of the audience,
followed by ABC with a 13.1 rating and a 22 percent share. CBS was
third with an average weekly rating of 12.9 and a 22 share.
