<FIRST>r a AM-BankRobbery 1stLd-Writethru a0762 09-26 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank Robbery, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0762,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank Employees Abducted and Run Over After Robbery</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to CLARIFY that gunman met employees as they
arrived, UPDATE with name of injured and condition, other details. No pick
up.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA ZAGAROLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PERRY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman robbed a bank Tuesday, fled with
four employees and later ran over two of them with his car, killing
one and injuring the other, police said.
   State police in Battle Creek said a man was arrested at a
roadblock later Tuesday and was being held for questioning.
Authorities recovered some cash and a weapon when the man was
arrested.
   Lt. Michael Johnson said a man wearing a hood met the employees
as they entered the First Federal Bank of Michigan branch in Perry
in central Michigan shortly before 9 a.m. When the vault opened,
the gunman took an undetermined amount of money. He forced four
employees to go with him when he fled in his auto.
   He returned minutes later and ordered three of the employees to
get into one of their cars and follow him, keeping one with him to
make sure the others followed, police said.
   After traveling about 30 miles, the two cars stopped north of
Battle Creek, drove a little father in one car and the man ordered
all four employees to lie side-by-side on the shoulder of the road.
He then tried to back his car over them, hitting two, the
lieutenant said. Two others ran.
   The gunman shot at them but missed, he said.
   The victim was identified as Marilyn Parks, 55, of Owosso. Betty
Green, of Perry, was in serious but stable condition at Lansing's
Ingham Medical Center, where she was transfered from a Charlotte
hospital, said Dr. Charles Gerwick.
   Two others were shaken up but not injured, said Johnson.
   Hal Helterhoff, agent in charge of the FBI in Michigan, said
possible charges against the man include bank robbery, abduction,
and murder.
   Police were alerted to the robbery by a customer who found the
bank's doors locked at 10 a.m.
</TEXT>
