<FIRST>r a AM-ChineseStudents 1stLd-Writethru a0659 09-26 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chinese Students, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Immigration Official Relents; Chinese Student To Be Released on Bond</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with INS official changing his
mind and deciding to grant bond. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, `Federal Immigration...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An immigration official ``had a change of
heart'' Tuesday and decided to release on bond a 27-year-old
student from China who was detained when she arrived seeking
asylum, her attorney's office said.
   David Ilchert, regional director of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, earlier ruled against bond for Hoy Yu Yi
after a doctor reported her to be in good health. But later Ilchert
``had a change of heart,'' said Hoy's spokesman, Bob Ryan. The
regional director is the only person who can approve bond in
immigration cases.
   Federal Immigration Judge Bernard Hornbach suggested the checkup
last week after a hearing in which Hoy appeared pale, grimaced and
said she was suffering from severe ulcerlike symptoms.
   Hoy and her fiance, Luo Jian Guang, 32, were taken into custody
Aug. 7 when they arrived in San Francisco saying they feared
reprisals for anti-government protests if they return to their
homeland. Immigration officials have the right to detain
asylum-seekers who arrive without visas or to release them on bond.
   While the INS said it has not taken a position on the asylum
request, the State Department has filed a report saying it does not
believe the students have proven they have a well-founded fear of
persecution if they go back to China.
   Their attorney, Eugene Wong of San Francisco, said he will
continue to fight deportation and pursue bond for Luo. He said Hoy
has relatives with whom they could stay.
   President Bush decided after the Beijing massacre in June to
allow the estimated 73,000 Chinese students in the United States to
remain even if their visas expired. But that decision did not
affect people who arrived later.
   Hoy and Luo were studying in Tokyo when they helped organize a
rally deploring the June 4 massacre of hundreds, perhaps thousands
of people by government troops on their way to recapture Tiananmen
Square from pro-democracy students.
   They said Chinese Embassy officials in Tokyo took pictures of
them, and they received phone calls at home that threatened them
for their protest.
   Both students' fathers were jailed during the Cultural
Revolution in the '60s, and they testified last Friday that they
expect to be jailed if they return to China.
</TEXT>
