<DOCNO> AP890926-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 2315EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-MilitarySpending 5thLd-Writethru a0810 09-26 1107</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military Spending, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0810,1,040</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 9th graf: ``During a,'' with vote on non-binding resolution
requiring presidential report on U.S. military presence in South Korea.
Stands for AMs. Debate on the bill resumes Wednesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic-controlled Senate on Tuesday
endorsed an additional cut of nearly $300 million in President
Bush's Star Wars program as part of a $288 billion military
spending bill.
   By a vote of 66-34, the Senate rejected an amendment that would
have restored that sum to Bush's Star Wars program to meet the $4.5
billion total approved by the chamber in its authorization bill
passed in August.
   Instead, the Senate accepted a total for the Strategic Defense
Initiative that falls about $900 million short of Bush's request
for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
   The spending bill's total is about $4.1 billion _ $3.7 billion
for the Pentagon's SDI program and $355 million for the Energy
Department and military construction.
   The Senate accepted those totals on a voice vote and continued
debate on the bill, which was expected to take several days.
   Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., a member of the Armed Services
Committee who voted against restoring the $300 million, said
``there isn't any question'' that suport for SDI is ``extremely
weak'' in the Senate.
   Later, the Senate rejected, 71-29, an amendment that would have
cut $2.7 billion from Bush's request for $4.7 billion next year to
buy and test the first 13 models of the B-2 stealth bomber.
   Proponents of the bat-winged aircraft argued that a U.S.-Soviet
treaty reducing strategic arms would be impossible without the
plane. Opponents complained that the cost of $530 million for each
of 132 planned bombers was excessive.
   During a session that lasted late into the night, the Senate
approved by a vote of 65-34 a non-binding resolution calling on
Bush to report to Congress before April 1, 1990 on the U.S.
military's presence in South Korea. Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., had
proposed a reduction of 3,000 in the 43,800 U.S. troops stationed
in the Asian nation, but the ``sense of Congress'' measure was
adopted instead.
   Earlier in the day, the Senate overwhelmingly endorsed shutting
down 86 military bases and scaling down five more, approving the
cost-saving plan to close bases. The vote was 86-14.
   The Senate totals for Star Wars are still far more than what was
approved by the House _ $3.1 billion _ and the House has not
compromised on the issue, according to one Senate negotiator.
   ``It's now clear that the House is not about to accept the
number that the authorizers agreed to in our bill,'' said Sen. Alan
Dixon, D-Ill., a member of the Senate Armed Services Committee.
   The defeated amendment, sponsored by Republican Sens. John
Warner of Virginia and Malcolm Wallop of Wyoming, also included a
series of changes to the bill approved by the Appropriations
Committee.
   Warner and Wallop would have restored $910 million for the
submarine-based, long-range Trident 2 nuclear issile, reduced funds
for the Apache helicopter and earmarked $395 million for
conventional weapons such as Stinger, TOW and HARM missiles.
   The defeated amendment also would have reduced the money for
fast transport ships from $1 billion to $20 million and provided
money for one rather than two icebreakers.
   On Star Wars, Wallop had argued that the increase in the
substitute amendment would have provided ``barely a minimum to
sustain confidence'' in the program.
   The House, according to Wallop, ``funded it at a level which it
cannot succeed. What they are doing to the American people is lying
to them.''
   But Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, said the amount for Star Wars
was a ``prudent position considering the current status of that
program.'' And Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La., noted that the Soviets
this past weekend indicated that they were divorcing Star Wars from
any U.S.-Soviet treaty to reduce strategic arms.
   ``The Soviets are not so concerned about SDI anymore,'' Johnston
said.
   In other action, the Senate approved:
   _Transferring $135 million from the Defense Department to the
Energy Department for the restart of the three tritium reactors at
the Savannah River nuclear plant.
   _Providing $20 million in military assistance for Jordan. This
amendment was introduced at the request of Bush and approved by
voice vote.
   _Approved aid to repair and rebuild military facilities in the
Caribbean and United States damaged last week by Hurricane Hugo.
The total cost of the aid plan was not immediately available but
Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., the plan's sponsor, said that $50
million was for a Navy shipyard in Charleston and $25 million was
for Shaw Air Force Base.
   On base closings, the Senate approved an amendment that
effectively eliminates a provision that would have held up $300
million for the base closings until the General Accounting Office
certified that the savings exceeded the cost.
   A federal commission, in making its recommendation last
December, estimated a savings of $5.6 billion over 20 years. Then
Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci accepted the panel's plan and
the House last spring upheld the proposal.
   The Senate action on the measure sponsored by Sen. Sam Nunn,
D-Ga., chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee, came
despite appeals from a handful of members petitioning on behalf of
their home-state bases.
   Prior to the Senate action, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said
further cuts in the defense budget by the Democratic-controlled
Congress may force him to close more bases.
   ``Given all the demands to redirect dollars from the defense
budget to other areas, I've got no choice but to find ways to close
additional bases,'' Cheney told reporters the day after Senate
Democrats and the administration reached a tentative agreement to
boost President Bush's anti-drug effort by $900 million. The plan
requires a cut of about $1.3 billion in the Pentagon budget.
   In te debate over base closings, Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii,
argued that a mistake had been made and the provision simply asks
``that the comptroller general analyze.''
   Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., who has fought plans to close Chanute
Air Force Base near Rantoul, Ill., charged that the commission
``cooked the books.''
   Behind the scenes, the lobbying firm of Patton, Boggs and Blow
urged members to vote against the Nunn amendment. Picking up the
lobbyists tab of about $30,000 were residents and businesses near
Chanute Air Force Base, Ill.
   Voting against the base closings amendment were Sens. Bill
Bradley, D-N.J.; Dan Coats, R-Ind.; Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.; Alan
Dixon, D-Ill.; Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii; Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.;
Robert Byrd, D-W.Va.; Richard Lugar, R-Ind.; Spark Matsunaga,
D-Hawaii; John McCain, R-Ariz.; Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.; Paul Simon,
D-Ill.; Ted Stevens, R-Alaska; and Pete Wilson, R-Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
