<FIRST>a e BC-WeekendTV-TyMiller Adv13-14   09-26 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Weekend TV-Ty Miller, Adv 13-14,0749</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct. 13-14, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ty Miller of ABC's `Young Riders' Went From Motorcycles to Horses</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ty Miller, who plays a character called ``The
Kid'' on ABC's ``The Young Riders,'' says that although he grew up
with horses he was more interested in motorcycles.
   He's in the saddle every day now for this new Western series
about the founding of the Pony Express. Miller plays the central
character of six young men in the show who sign up to carry the
mail from St. Joseph, Mo., to Sacramento, Calif., in April 1860.
The show's original title was ``The Kid.''
   ``I ride but I don't ride very well,'' said Miller, who grew up
in Southern California in a family that ran a Christmas tree
business. ``We always had horses, but it's like when you have a
swimming pool and you spend your time at the beach. I spent more
time riding motorcycles than horses. We had 2{ acres and a stable.
The horse I rode is now 26 and can't be ridden anymore.''
   Miller and all the members of the cast were sent to cowboy camp
for a quick course in how to stay in the saddle. It was run by
Richard Lundin, head wrangler for the series.
   ``I'm finding you just have to get on a horse and ride and
ride,'' Miller said. ``It's not a textbook thing. In the pilot we
only used stunt men for a few shots. They did the dangerous falls.
We did all the flat-out riding.''
   Miller was more concerned with going to Tucson, Ariz., to film
in 100-degree weather in his leather costume. His character and
co-star Stephen Baldwin's character, William Cody, later to become
famous as Buffalo Bill, wear buckskin.
   This is the first Western for Miller, who appeared as bellhop
Eric LLoyd in the final season of ABC's ``Hotel.''
   ``My role on `Hotel' was pretty limited,'' he said. ``Mostly I
stood in the lobby and said, `Good morning, how are you? May I take
your bag?' Those of us who worked in the lobby weren't involved in
the main stories.''
   Miller acknowledges the ``The Young Riders'' series takes
license with the facts for dramatic reasons.
   ``They keep most of us around the station, more so than would
happen in real life,'' he said. ``That's for the sake of the
stories. We'll say there isn't a mail pouch to take out. I think
the riders spent more time on the road.''
   Pony Express riders usually averaged 75 miles, changing horses
at relay stations every 10 to 15 miles. Occasionally, a rider was
required to ride a longer distance. There were 80 riders to cover
1,966 miles in 10 days. The service ended in October 1861 with the
completion of the telegraph from coast to coast.
   ``Not one rider was killed and only one mail pouch was lost,''
Miller said.
   He describes his character in the series this way: ``The Kid is
very honest and trustworthy. He's the moral center of the group.
He's level-headed, kind of reserved. He doesn't act on impulse.
He's the natural leader of the riders.''
   Miller grew up in Los Angeles. His mother was an artist and his
father ran the Christmas tree business.
   ``My brother runs the business now,'' he said. ``It's the
largest Christmas tree retail business in the country. We sell two
million trees a year on 52 lots from San Diego to Sacramento.''
   Miller himself appeared headed for a business career when a
girlfriend at the University of California urged him to audition
for a commercial. He went to 40 auditions before he got his first
job, a silent part in a commercial for a canned ham. After that he
did guest roles on such shows as ``Growing Pains,'' ``Our House,''
``Valerie'' and ``Macgruder and Loud.''
   Miller was the last one cast in ``The Young Riders.'' He read
for the role five times and it was down to Miller and another actor
before he was approved.
   Like ``The Virginian,'' his character has no name. He's known
only as ``The Kid.''
   ``I'm thinking about what I'll do ... if it comes up that I have
to sign my name,'' he said. ``I guess I'll just put down an `X.'''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Oct. 13-14</NOTE>
