<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--HomeVideo Adv00   09-26 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Home Video, Adv 00,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: ``Baby It's Your''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How much you enjoy the 1982 comedy ``Baby It's
You'' may depend on your appreciation of three alumni of New
Jersey's working class: Frank Sinatra, Bruce Springsteen and
director John Sayles.
   The year is 1967 and Jill Rosen (Rosanna Arquette) is a senior
at a Trenton high school, an aspiring actress from an upper-middle
class family who seeks acceptance to Sarah Lawrence College.
   She catches the attention of Albert ``Sheik'' Capadilupo, the
swaggering, sharply dressed garbage man's son who ranks ``Jesus
Christ, Frank Sinatra and me'' as the most important people in his
life.
   On the surface, another ``bad boy meets nice girl'' story. Sheik
gets Jill, Sheik loses Jill, Sheik wins her back. But ``Baby It's
You'' has much more to offer. With humor and intelligence, Sayles
touches on the conflicts of class and sex. What to do with choices,
too many and too few.
   Sayles (``Matewan,'' ``Eight Men Out'') collaborated on the
story with Amy Robinson, whose experiences were closer to Jill's.
   ``Certainly I could relate to both of them,'' Sayles said in a
recent phone interview. ``A lot of kids ended up in Vietnam or
working in a factory or married with kids right out of high school.
Your potential is cut off.''
   Rock 'n' roll, from the Trashmen to Procul Harem, is everywhere,
but Sinatra's ``Strangers in the Night'' frames this video. It's
heard three times: in a diner by the Jersey shore, at the high
school senior prom and at the Sarah Lawrence dance that closes the
film, with a bewildered pyschedelic band honoring the request of
Sheik and Jill.
   ``There's definitely a line running through,'' Sayles said.
``One of the fascinating things was looking at all the different
songs that came out around that time. Strawberry Alarm Clock,
Motown, the Rolling Stones. There were so many kinds of music.''
   Sinatra and Springsteen are Sheik's theme music. He glides
through high school to Springsteen's ``Hard to be a Saint in the
City,'' mouths Sinatra songs at a rundown Miami nightclub and races
up to Sarah Lawrence and a final reconciliation with Jill as
Springsteen grinds out ``Adam Raised a Cain.''
   Jill gets a little bit of everything, pouting like Diana Ross as
she mimes the Supremes' ``Stop in the Name of Love!,'' joining her
friends in a light-hearted chorus of ``Going to the Chapel'' and
walking arm-in-arm with Sheik to Ben E. King's ``Stand by Me.''
   The film's happy ending is possible only through an acceptance
of limits. Jill fails miserably in her attempt to impress her
sophisticated Sarah Lawrence friends; Sheik's Miami nightclub act
is a washout.
   ``He has to realize that he's not Frank Sinatra and she learns
to take a little control over reinventing herself,'' Sayles said.
   ``What's nice about `Baby It's You' is you get a chance to tell
about other people's stories. Amy and I were talking about how the
girls and guys in school always wanted to know what went on in the
other lockerroom. This gave each of us a chance to do that.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Baby It's You'' (Paramount Home Video. VHS-Beta. No suggested
retail price, intended for rental market. Rated R).
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
