<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1314EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   09-26 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Lassus _ Missa Osculetur Me'' (Gimell) _ The Tallis Scholars,
directed by Peter Phillips.
   ``Lassus _ Masses and Motets'' (Nimbus) _ Christ Church (Oxford)
Cathedral Choir, directed by Stephen Darlington.
   
   It was after solving the case of the Bruce-Partington plans that
Sherlock Holmes completed his monograph on the Polyphonic Motets of
Lassus. Experts, according to Dr. Watson, rated it ``the last word
upon the subject.''
   It's unlikely that Lassus' motets will ever be exhausted. He
composed 700 or so, of which only a few dozen have been recorded,
in addition to his 60 settings of the Mass, 101 settings of the
Magnificat, plus hundreds of madrigals and chansons.
   Born in 1530, Lassus was perhaps the most popular composer of
his time. He not only wrote a lot of music, he wrote well, as two
new recordings prove.
   The choir of Christ Church Cathedral offers two Mass settings,
three motets and a madrigal.
   The Missa Venatorum, barely 10 minutes long, shows Lassus at his
most economical, the kind of music that might elevate the mind
without aggravating the knees.
   Technically, the Oxford choir cannot match the Tallis Scholars'
professional polish, but it is closer to the sound Lassus would
have known.
   The Missa Osculetur Me, recorded by the Tallis Scholars,
illustrates Lassus' frequent technique of musical parody. In this
case the Mass reworks his own motet set to the opening verses of
the Song of Solomon: ``Let him kiss me ....''
   The performances are ravishing, which is to say that they are up
to the Scholars' usual mark. Is it peevish, then, to complain that
the disc holds only 49 minutes of music? Encore, Mr. Phillips,
encore!
   _ By Robert Barr, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Southside'' (Mercury) - Texas
   
   The Scottish band Texas lives about as far from its namesake as
one can get, but it has ambitions as large as the Lone Star state.
   Texas' new album, ``Southside,'' is one of the most promising
debuts of 1989. Texas shows a remarkable amount of maturity and
self-assuredness for such a young band, and what ``Southside''
lacks in originality it makes up in consistent quality.
   The quartet's sound, like so many other mainstream rockers these
days, is rooted in the acoustic guitar of frontwoman Sharleen
Spiteri. But it's augmented by the distinctive blues guitar of Ally
McErlane and the sort of throbbing bass that's more common to
synthesizer bands.
   Those ingredients are most evident on ``I Don't Want a Lover,''
this record's first single. That's not the best song on the album,
however. The vote here goes to ``Thrill Has Gone,'' an understated
country-flavored tune about the souring of a relationship.
   At times, McErlane's guitar and the wide open spaces of Texas'
sound bring the state to mind. Spiteri also understands well the
differences between singing and shouting.
   Her lyrics travel the traditional terrain of relationships with
neither great insight nor embarrassing simplicity.
   Texas sometimes follows the traditional tendency of young bands
to show their influences a little too openly. Texas obviously
listens to Bob Dylan, since the musical hook of ``Everyday Now''
vividly recalls ``I Shall Be Released.'' And the ringing guitars of
``Fool for Love'' sound a lot like U2.
   But this record is filled with strong melodies and performances.
There are no weak cuts, a track record that would make most young
bands _ as well as too many established ones _ envious.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
