<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1413EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--ObsessiveArt Adv06-08   09-26 1003</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Obsessive Art, Adv 06-08,1035</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct. 6-8, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: A Jeweled Grotto Filled With Memories</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY20 of Sept. 25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
  Joseph E. Furey worked night and day covering all
surfaces in his apartment with painted cardboard hearts, bow ties,
stars and squares; small plaster birds; dried lima beans and peas;
clamshells from Coney Island; mussel and oyster shells; and pieces
of tile and glass.
   Heartbroken over the death of his wife, Lillian, Furey spent six
years creating a memorial for her with mementos he found.
   Then, with nearly 80,000 objects on every wall, ceiling,
cupboard and mirror, he left it all behind. He saw his work as an
obsession fulfilled.
   The Brooklyn Museum sees it now as art unpreserved, and is
taking steps to save Furey's creation.
   ``I was absolutely astonished when I first saw it,'' said
Barbara Head Millstein, the museum's associate curator of painting
and sculpture. ``It looked like a jeweled grotto.''
   The work was discovered last February after Vincent Kelley, a
real-estate developer, bought the building in which Furey had
lived. After entering Furey's apartment, he called the museum.
   Millstein hurried over. For the last few months, she has been
trying to persuade the borough of Brooklyn to buy the apartment and
preserve it on site. The lath walls and heavy plaster would crumble
if removed, she said.
   She said she will document the work with photographs and a
transcript of a lengthy interview with the 83-year-old Furey, once
an ironworker on the Golden Gate and the George Washington bridges.
   Furey, who moved out of the apartment nearly a year ago after it
was broken into twice, and now lives with his son, Joseph Jr., in
Chester, N.Y., is amused by all the attention. As for being an
artist, he's had no formal training, and the only museum he has
ever visited is the American Museum of Natural History.
   He spent 14 to 18 hours a day on his project from 1982 to 1988,
cutting out the cardboard figures of hearts, diamonds and bow ties
(made in honor of his friend Bow Tie George), and painting each one
in a planned color scheme _ but few people then thought his work
art.
   ``Most people looked at it, but they didn't see it,'' he said.
   Millstein said most people, including some members of Furey's
family, ``thought he was bananas.''
   But not now.
   His work is called obsessive or personal art, Millstein said,
adding that such art is rarely preserved.
   ``There's hasn't been enough encouragement to save it because
you can't take it to Christie's or Sotheby's and sell it,'' she
said of the noted auction houses in New York City. ``It can be, as
a matter of fact, quite ugly. It has more to do with obsession than
it does with beauty.''
   Furey's outpouring is in the same vein as Simon Rodia's Watts
Towers in Los Angeles, made out of concrete, seashells and broken
glass; Thomas Trapani's complex and decorative furniture, which he
made in his New Jersey home after his wife died in 1918; and
Korczak Ziolkowski's 35-year project of carving a Black Hills
mountain in South Dakota into a likeness of Sioux Indian leader
Crazy Horse _ a work his family has continued since his death in
1982.
   ``It's a private thing these people are doing. It's outside of
the main art world,'' said Jordan Davis, manager of the
Cleveland-based Spaces, a gallery that promotes site-specific art.
``Most of these people don't consider themselves artists. But they
are very creative people. ... You look at their work, and you say,
`Holy smokes!'''
   Millstein said Furey is ``one of a group of artists who spring
up all over the world, compulsively forced at some time in their
life to finish a project. They usually have some kind of trauma in
their life and they are driven to finish a project. A lot of them
are older people who have a last burst of artistic creativity.''
   Walking into Furey's apartment is like stepping into a miniature
museum that didn't put any of its collection in storage. The floor
is the only bare space.
   He started in the bathroom, moved to the living room, then the
kitchen, then the hallway, he said. He covered doors, both sides.
He pasted cutouts around the edges of mirrors, and for ceiling
work, he rigged up a scaffold.
   ``This is not slapdash, you know,'' Furey said. ``I would wake
up at two, three, or four o'clock in the morning and start making
cutouts. I'd paint them different colors and work for eight, or 10
or 12 hours. Then I'd take a nap in the recliner chair for a couple
of hours and start up again.''
   On the ceilings, he made rings around the light fixtures of
shells, bow tie-shaped cardboard cutouts and cardboard stars.
   In the hallway, he nailed cement-filled shells to the walls.
Some of the shells came from a neighborhood deli.
   A dining room wallpaper of a Western scene is partly covered
with the decoupage. Furey also pasted cows, poodles, chipmunks and
monkeys next to the wallpaper horses.
   Hearts are everywhere. Many are bright red. Many others are
black.
   ``The whole project was more or less to kill time and to get
over my grief of losing her,'' Furey said of his wife, who died in
1981. ``I had a lot of time on my hands, not much to do, and I
missed her.''
   Millstein said the objects represented different parts of
Furey's life, and many were for Lillian. The small birds, for
instance, represented the couple's peaceful life together.
   The two had married during the Depression and moved into the
apartment in the mid-1930s. They raised five children there.
   ``We had a good life together,'' Furey said.
   Furey's art reveals that it was, Millstein said.
   ``It's a five-room love story,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Oct. 6-8</NOTE>
</DOC>
