<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Whittaker Adv06-08   09-26 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Whittaker, Adv 06-08,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv06</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct. 6-8, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Roger Whittaker Is a Sales Wonder</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY1 of Sept. 25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roger Whittaker is a sales wonder. In 25
years, he has recorded 43 albums and sold 30 million LPs worldwide.
   One single record alone, ``The Last Farewell'' in 1978, sold 11
million copies.
   ``It's staggering, astonishing,'' said the 53-year-old Whittaker
in a telephone interview from Germany. ``I face it as it comes
along. It's great to know you can do it. If you think about it, you
get a swelled head.''
   His top-selling albums in the United States are ``The Best of
Roger Whittaker'' and ``All My Best,'' both nearing sales of 1
million. Many of his records are sold through TV marketing,
including ``Best Loved Ballads'' and ``All Time Heart-Touching
Favorites.''
   He has just released for over-the-counter sale another album,
``I'd Fall in Love Tonight,'' produced in Nashville. It includes
country music standards like ``Blue Eyes Crying in the Rain,''
``There Goes My Everything'' and ``Have I Told You Lately That I
Love You.''
   The singer-songwriter-guitarist now records for Universal
Records after 19 years and 19 albums with RCA. Singing in three
languages _ English, French and Spanish _ has widened his appeal.
   Whittaker also has gained a larger audience through hawking his
albums on TV. Universal Records thinks he's someone who can get
consumers to buy records at the retail level rather than just
picking up the phone and dialing the number shown on the TV screen.
   ``We're looking forward to adding to our collection of gold and
platinum albums,'' said Jimmy Bowen, Universal president.
   Whittaker is a star in North America, Europe, Australia and
various points in between. One Nashville record store recently had
four different Whittaker albums and five different compact discs.
   ``I can go anywhere,'' he said. ``It's a wonderful feeling. I've
made 10 tours of Canada. We did better business on this 10th tour
than any one we've done.''
   Singing love ballads and not making drastic changes in style
have helped him do well, he said.
   ``I've stayed in the style and never tried to conform to
convention. I've sung the kind of songs I write even when out of
vogue. Fifteen percent of the record-buying public buy my kind of
music. I've stayed faithful to that core of people.
   ``Every once in a while a song comes along that every one takes
to, like `The Last Farewell,''' he said.
   He described ``The Last Farewell'' as ``a happy marriage of
lyrics and melody.''
   ``It was number one in places like Finland where they don't
speak English,'' said Whittaker. ``They still play it in Russia, so
the tune must have a lot to do with its success. The
English-speaking nations identified with the chorus, `For you are
beautiful and I love you dearly.'
   ``The lyrics were emotive to me and I identified with them.''
   In his writing and singing, Whittaker looks for songs that
express realism.
   ``If I can relate to what a person is saying, then I sing it.
Like `Downtown' or `The Last Farewell.' If it reflects something of
my own experience, then I sing it.''
   Whittaker, born in Nairobi, Kenya, now lives in London. He has a
degree in biochemistry from the University of Bangor in Wales.
   ``I did become a biochemist,'' he said. ``But I wanted to go
into the entertainment business to get it out of my system. The
more I got into it, the more I fought to succeed.
   ``The less I succeeded, the more I fought,'' he said. ``It
became a real mania for me. My father threatened me about getting
the right job. When I finally found success, he came around a bit.''
   Apart from his recording and concert tours, his TV special,
``Roger Whittaker in Kenya, a Musical Safari,'' was shown by the
British Broadcasting Corp., and in the United States by the Disney
Channel on cable TV.
   He is active in efforts to help save Africa's black rhino,
donating proceeds from program sales at concerts and recording
royalties to a trust fund to create sanctuaries for the rhino in
Kenya.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Oct. 6-8</NOTE>
