<FIRST>u f PM-AutoSales     09-26 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Up Based on GM Results, But For How Long?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of North American-made cars and trucks rose
12.7 percent in mid-September, based on a strong showing by General
Motors Corp., but at least one analyst wondered how long it could
go on.
   The eight major U.S. automakers said Monday they sold cars and
light trucks at an average daily rate of 37,948 during the Sept.
11-20 period this year, compared with a rate of 33,670 during the
same time last year.
   GM buyers propelled the company's truck sales up 46 percent and
car sales by 11.2 percent. Combined, GM's vehicle sales were up
21.7 percent during the period this year over last year.
   ``They had incentives that were closing, that had been scheduled
to end this week and a lot of dealer incentives,'' said analyst Ron
Glantz of Montgomery Securities Inc. in San Francisco.
   The dealer incentives, which manufacturers give to their
retailers to use as they please, have helped move cars and trucks,
said Bill Meier, general manager of Ray Green Chevrolet in
Jacksonville, Ill.
   ``I think, finally, they realized that when you put the money in
the dealers' pockets, they're going to sell them,'' he said of the
cars on his lot. Meier said an inventory of 35 1989 model vehicles
on his lot at the beginning of the month had shrunk to eight by
Monday.
   ``They (dealers) asked us to give them money so they could sell
in their marketplace,'' said GM spokesman Terry Sullivan. ``At
least in the first 20 days (of September), they're proving that may
have made some sense.
   ``We're just having a very strong September,'' he said.
   But Glantz and other analysts have said for weeks that the boom
that has gone on during the past several sales periods may stem
from incentives and reports of price increases on 1990 models that
are pushing consumers into buy-now thinking.
   ``The industry has an above average amount of inventory, there
are unprecedented incentives and a whopping price increase for the
1990s,'' Glantz said. ``(Sales) are going to fall off a cliff in
October.''
   So far this year, car and truck sales by the eight manufacturers
are down 1.5 percent compared to the same 1988 period. A 0.4
percent increase in truck sales was more than offset by a 2.6
percent decline in car sales.
   GM and Chrysler Corp. already have begun offering incentives on
their 1990 models, sometimes even before the vehicles officially go
on sale. Ford Motor Co. is expected to jump into the incentive fray.
   Dealers have worried that consumers are getting so conditioned
to incentives that cars and trucks must have them in order to be
attractive. Meier was bullish on the future of the industry.
   ``The (1990) price increases are one thing, but when people come
out and see what they are getting and with the incentives, there
isn't that much different,'' he said.
   Ford said sales of its cars and light trucks were up 3.4 percent
in mid-September over last year. Car sales were up 2.6 percent and
truck sales rose 4.5 percent. For the year, Ford's vehicle sales
were down 0.7 percent.
   Car and truck sales at Chrysler were up 0.7 percent in
mid-September. Car sales were up 2.1 percent and truck sales were
down 0.7 percent. For the year, vehicle sales at Chrysler were
running 5.9 percent behind last year's pace.
   For the year, GM has sold 3.9 percent fewer vehicles than it did
through Sept. 20, 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
