<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     09-26 0846</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0883</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar plunged on world markets as
the United States and its major allies demonstrated determination
to push the currency's value lower in a bid to solve America's
trade deficit problems.
   The sell-off began in hectic trading in Tokyo and was later
matched in European and New York markets Monday in what traders
described as a rout for the dollar.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Auto sales by the eight major U.S. manufacturers
soared 12.7 percent in mid-September over last year, with much of
the gain due to a 46 percent rise in light truck sales at General
Motors Corp.
   Overall, cars and light trucks sold at an average daily rate of
37,948 in mid-September, compared with a 33,670 vehicle-a-day rate
last year, according to reports released Monday. Car sales were up
10.2 percent and truck sales rose 17.1 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lower interest rates lured buyers back into
the existing home market in August when sales rose 3.3 percent to
their highest level in six months, a real estate group reported.
   The National Association of Realtors said Monday that existing
single-family homes sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
3.44 million units last month, up from July's revised 3.33 million
units. Fixed-rate home mortgages have fallen to near 10 percent
from a peak of 11.2 percent in March.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC ministers were reported close to an agreement
that could raise production for the rest of the year after a flurry
of private bargaining sessions to break a deadlock in their talks.
   The Qatar News Agency quoted unidentified sources Monday as
saying the ministers were about to reach an agreement on a higher
producion ceiling of 21 million barrels a day to begin on Oct. 1
and run through the end of the year.
   But an evening meeting where OPEC delegates were expected to
formalize the plan was abruptly postponed, surprising some
ministers who had already gathered. Officials said there were
last-minute snags in negotiations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Columbia Pictures Entertainment Inc. stock shot
higher as the movie and television programmer said it was in active
discussions about selling the company, triggering speculation that
the suitor was Japan's Sony Corp.
   Columbia Pictures and Sony, which previously had indicated an
interest in buying a movie studio, each declined to comment Monday
on a report that the electronics giant had offered to buy Columbia.
   Coca-Cola Co., the Atlanta-based soft drink maker that owns 49
percent of Columbia's stock, said it was aware Columbia was in
discussions and that it would consider whatever recommendation may
be made.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. said it had made the last major
asset sale under a $5.5 billion divestiture plan as an investor
group led by Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. agreed to buy its Del Monte canned
food business for $1.48 billion.
   Del Monte's senior management, Citicorp Capital Investors Ltd.
and Kikkoman Corp. also are members of the investor group.
   RJR Nabisco said Monday that proceeds from the sale will bring
to approximately $4.9 billion the amount of money it has earned
from its divestiture program.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coors Brewing Co. offered $425 million to
buy Stroh Brewing Co., a move analysts said effectively creates a
``Big Three'' group of dominant U.S. breweries.
   The purchase price announced Monday includes cash plus
assumption of long-term debt and certain other liabilities. The
transaction is subject to a definitive agreement and approval by
the boards of directors of both companies and government regulators.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration said it
has tightened security standards since the December bombing of Pan
Am Flight 103, but a General Accounting Office investigation said
the FAA doesn't know if airlines are meeting the standards.
   The GAO report, the details of which are being kept secret by
Congress, was summarized by Rep. Cardiss Collins, D-Ill., at a
hearing Monday of her House Government Operations subcommittee on
government activities and transportation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is asking United Airlines to
disclose how much foreign influence over the airline a planned
employee-management takeover would allow, officials said.
   The inquiry came as The Wall Street Journal reported Monday that
Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner had asked Northwest
Airlines' new principal owner, Alfred Checchi, to cut by $225
million the $400 million investment made in NWA Inc., the airline's
parent corporation, by KLM Royal Dutch Airlines.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market sustained a broad loss Monday in the slowest
trading in more than 2{ months. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials dropped 22.42 points to a five-week low of 2,659.19.
   Bond prices fell sharply as the dollar plummeted in foreign
exchange due to dollar-selling by the central banks of several
industrial nations. Interest rates rose.
   Cotton futures prices made strong gains on the New York Cotton
Exchange; copper futures fell; gold and platinum rose; energy
futures advanced; grains and soybeans were mixed; and livestock and
meat futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
