<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0753EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f BC-Janeway     09-26 0111</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Janeway,0117</SECOND>
<HEAD>One-Time FDR Adviser Urges Drug Legalization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economist Eliot Janeway, an adviser to
President Franklin Roosevelt, says the United States should give
drugs away to cut crime and illicit drug profits.
   ``Let's fall back on an ancient, honorable, all-American
preference for getting something for nothing. Let's make users and
addicts an offer they can't resist,'' Janeway, 76, told the Detroit
Economic Club on Monday.
   ``Activate the U.S. government for a business it knows and does
best: handouts,'' Janeway said, describing efforts to fight drugs
as a ``fruitless operation.''
   Janeway said hard-line drug policies merely swell prison
populations and result in more young, poor, urban dealers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890926-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0853EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Trade     09-26 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Trade,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain's Trade Deficit Falls, But Still Wider Than Forecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's merchandise trade deficit eased to $3.69
billion in August from a revised shortfall of $3.99 billion the
previous month, but it was still the fourth-largest gap ever, the
government said Tuesday.
   The Central Statistical Office said the deficit of the current
account, which includes services and overseas investments, was
$3.20 billion, the third largest ever, but down from July's revised
deficit of $3.50 billion.
   The pound and stock prices fell sharply on the news.
   The government said August's figures, like that of the previous
month's, could have been distorted by a three-week strike by dock
workers at some British ports which disrupted trade flows this
summer.
   Exports totaled $12.04 billion in August, down from $12.39
billion in July and up from $11.01 billion dollars) in August 1988.
   Imports totaled $15.72 billion in August, down from $16.40
billion in July and up from $13.68 billion in August 1988.
   Since the beginning of 1989, Britain's merchandise trade balance
has been in deficit by $26.79 billion, compared with a deficit of
$20.73 billion a year earlier.
   The current account has been in deficit by $22.33 billion so far
this year, compared with a gap of $13.74 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890926-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0902EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-AT&amp;T     09-26 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-AT&amp;T,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>AT&amp;T To Buy Istel for $290 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. announced
Tuesday it plans to buy Istel Group Ltd., a British information
technology company, for $290 million in cash.
   The acquisition represents AT&amp;T's first major purchase in
Britain and would strengthen the company's presence in the
information movement and management industry in Europe.
   ``We think Istel can support AT&amp;T in important ways as AT&amp;T
seeks to become a more global player,'' John Berndt, president of
AT&amp;T International Communications Services, told a news conference.
``We are trying to expand our capabilities outside the United
States.''
   The offer price varies for each class of Istel shares.
   The board of directors of the British-based data networking
company recommended that its shareholders take up AT&amp;T's offer and
said shareholders who own 53.7 percent of Istel's outstanding
shares already have agreed to accept the bid.
   Rover Group, a unit of British Aerospace PLC, said it would sell
its minority shareholding of 21.7 percent in Istel to AT&amp;T once the
American telecommunications company obtains a majority stake.
   Under the terms of the offer, Istel would become a wholly owned
subsidiary of AT&amp;T with no change in its name or management.
   ``We think it's a tremendous step forward,'' said John
Leighfield, Istel's chairman.
   He said his company was motivated to find a partner by
widespread consolidation in the telecommunications industry, which
meant, ``we'd have formidable competitors in the mid-1990s.''
   ``We wanted to put Istel in the best position to fulfill its
potential to the maximum,'' Leighfield said.
   Istel, which is based in Redditch in the English Midlands and
employs 1,800 people, is a leading British supplier of information
technology and services and is known for its systems integration
skills. It operates in a variety of markets, including automotive,
financial services, health care, manufacturing, travel, leisure,
retail and distribution.
   Istel had pre-tax profit of $14 million on revenue of $134
million last year.
   AT&amp;T has a transmissions systems development and manufacturing
facility in western England, employing 500 people. Its European
software operation is based in London.
</TEXT>
