<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1023EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-OperatorServices 1stLd-Writethru f0012 09-26 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Operator Services, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0012,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Seeks to Regulate Alternative Long-Distance Plans</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS lede to delete reference to calling cards. A version
moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is taking aim at alleged
price-gouging among a new crop of telephone companies that serve
the traveling public.
   The House, on a voice vote Monday, passed a bill that would
regulate prices and require extensive disclosure to callers using
any of the more than 35 alternative-operator companies which have
sprung up in the wake of the 1984 breakup of the Bell System.
   The bill would require the Federal Communications Commission to
investigate the industry's charges and determine if such companies
dominate the market enough to require regulation. A companion bill
is pending in the Senate.
   The companies would have to file their prices with the FCC
within 30 days and, if the commission finds them ``unjust or
unreasonable,'' the companies would have to justify the rates,
which can be far greater than the fees for similar calls from
customers' homes.
   Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., said the legislation was
designed to ``protect consumers from price-gouging'' by ``fast-buck
artists'' without jeopardizing the future of the operator services
industry.
   One caller told the FCC he was charged $27.53 for a 27-minute
call from a Florida hotel to Connecticut using an AT&amp;T calling
card. AT&amp;T would have normally charged $4.60.
   The measure also would order the FCC to extend to the entire
operator services industry disclosure requirements imposed on five
of the companies in February.
   There are more than 35 operator services companies in the United
States providing approximately 5 percent of the $12 billion market
for ``dial-0'' services such as credit card, third party billing
and collect calls.
   The FCC does not regulate these companies' rates because the
commission says they don't dominate the market.
   But critics say they do dominate in places, such as schools,
hotels and airports, where they often control all long-distance
calls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
