<DOCNO> AP890926-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1114EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-CapitalGains 1stLd-Writethru f0010 09-26 0762</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Capital Gains, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0010,0779</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer, Labor Groups Announce Opposition to Cut in Capital Gains
Tax</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with comments from news conference
today. Picks up 6th graf pvs, The Republicans say ... A version moving
on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer, labor and government watchdog groups
announced today their opposition to President Bush's plan to cut
the capital gains tax, saying it would be a windfall for
high-income taxpayers.
   ``Capital gains proponents are asking Americans to ignore the
unjustified financial windfall this tax break will provide to
individuals who need it the least,'' said Fred Wertheimer,
president of Common Cause, a self-styled citizens lobby involved in
government ethics isssues.
   ``Congress is once again hearing the claim that there is nothing
wrong with the economy that a tax cut for people with incomes over
$200,000 won't cure,'' said Joan Claybrook, president of Public
Citizen, a Ralph Nader organization.
   ``The vote is a critical test of whether the Congress is truly a
representative body _ or whether it is a captive of big money
lobbyists and the wealthy,'' she said. That vote could come as
early as Wednesday.
   ``If Congress approves of this new tax break, members of
Congress may find it hard to explain to working people back home
why they voted for yet another bargain with high-income
taxpayers,'' said a statement by the Friends Committee on National
Legislation, a Quaker group.
   The groups held a news conference in the Capitol as the battle
over the capital gains tax moved to the airwaves, with Republicans
and Democrats advertising for popular support on an issue that is
dividing Congress sharply along partisan lines.
   ``George Bush wants to raid the Treasury by reducing capital
gains taxes for the superrich and he wants working Americans to pay
for it,'' House Majority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., argues in
a television spot produced by the Democratic National Committee.
   ``Why are foreign economies growing faster than the U.S.? One
big reason is taxes,'' says a Republican ad that pictures an
American flag slipping behind flags from Japan, Taiwan and Korea.
``We have one of the world's highest capital gains taxes,'' it
says, while the comparable taxes in those other countries are
miniscule.
   The parties were buying time for the ads in Washington, where
the target will be the votes of a few mostly conservative Democrats
who could decide the outcome when the House votes. It is the
biggest test for the new House Democratic leadership under Speaker
Thomas S. Foley of Washington, and for a Republican strategy that
seeks to weaken the majority leadership by courting conservative
Democrats.
   The Republicans say Democrats, by fighting the Bush-supported
plan to cut the maximum capital gains rate from 33 percent to 19.6
percent over the next 27 months, are attached to a ``tax and
spend'' philosophy.
   The Democratic alternative would raise marginal tax rates on the
wealthy to the same 33 percent paid in the bracket that covers the
upper-middle-income. That revenue would then be used to restore tax
breaks for Individual Retirement Accounts.
   The Democratic plan also includes a capital gains cut _ to 28
percent, so it would not cut the marginal rate paid by the most
wealthy.
   ``It's clearly a reconfirmation that they want to raise taxes,''
Bush's budget director Richard Darman said Monday. ``Who's going to
believe they want to stop there?''
   Foley denounced Darman's comments as ``stuff and nonsense.''
   The Democrats oppose the Bush-backed plan because it is ``ill
timed, ill considered and damaging ... helping only the richest of
our citizens and unfair to the middle class,'' he said.
   The capital gains tax cut is part of a huge budget bill before
the House. The package would be contentious even without the tax
fight, because it also contains changes in the Medicare
catastrophic health coverage plan, new federal child care programs,
and dozens of other issues with divided support.
   Nearly buried beneath the controversial issues is the bill's
underlying purpose, which is reducing the federal deficit.
   Rep. Bill Frenzel, D-Minn., said a review of the bill showed
that much of the deficit-reduction in the package was
``disingenuous,'' and after three years the bill would be adding to
the red ink.
   Still, Frenzel said he would probably vote for the bill if it
includes the GOP-supported capital gains tax cut. He didn't put
that in the ``disingenuous'' category, but included figures showing
that it, too, would begin adding billions of dollars to the deficit
after an initial period of added revenues.
</TEXT>
