<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 11am,0341</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was higher in moderate trading
today as investors searched for bargains following Monday's
sell-off.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 17.29 points to
2,676.48 at 11 a.m. EDT. The blue-chip indicator was 8.55 points
higher an hour earlier after dropping 22.42 points on Monday.
   Advancing issues outpaced decliners by a margin of nearly 2 to 1
on the New York Stock Exchange, with 749 issues up, 391 down and
550 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 47.63 million shares.
   The stock market got a slight boost early in the day from a
government report that showed surprising strength in new factory
orders for durable goods.
   The Commerce Department reported that factory orders for ``big
ticket'' durable items such as cars, airplanes and machinery, rose
3.8 percent in August, the biggest advance this year.
   However, the July data was revised downward from down 2.2
percent to down 2.5 percent, more than expected. Orders in june had
risen 1.3 percent.
   Moreover, a closely-watched section of the report showed that
non-defense capital goods had dropped 9.8 percent to $37.4 billion.
Economists use this category as a barometer of business investment
plans.
   ``What we're seeing is a bargain-hunting phase helped along by
program trading,'' said Larry Wachtel, vice president at
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   A sharp rise in Japan's stock market overnight was also giving
some support to the U.S. market, analysts said.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 1.12 to 192.40.
   On the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was 1.13
higher at 382.53.
   Among actively traded issues on the New York Stock Exchange,
Columbia Pictures was down \ to 26[ after an offer by Sony of Japan
to buy the company.
   Paramount Communications, meanwhile, was up 1~ to 56|, IBM had
gained 1 to 117\ and Upjohn had added { to 37\.
