<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1135EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-PentagonProbe     09-26 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pentagon Probe,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guilty Pleas Entered in Pentagon Probe Involving Electronic Contracts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A subsidiary of Whittaker Corp. and two
former executives pleaded guilty today to charges they bribed a
Marine Corps contracting official to increase the value of Pentagon
electronic contracts their company obtained.
   Whittaker Command and Control Systems pleaded guilty to
conspiracy to defraud the government and two counts of bribing
former Marine Corps official Jack Sherman with nearly $75,000
between 1982 and 1988.
   The Whittaker subsidiary agreed to pay $3.5 million in fines,
civil penalties and reimbursement for the cost of the investigation.
   Scott M. Lamberth, 59, the former head of the subsidiary, and
John F. Van Tassel, ex-director of operations at its Fayetteville,
Ark., facility, also entered guilty pleas before U.S. District
Judge Claude M. Hilton.
   The plea by the Whittaker subsidiary is the third by a
corporation since the investigation began last year. Teledyne
Electronics and Hazeltine Corp. have both entered guilty pleas for
their roles in the procurement scandal.
   According to court papers, officials of Whittaker Corp. of Los
Angeles were unaware of the bribery scheme, which began before the
company acquired the subsidiary in 1986.
   The bribery scheme allegedly began in 1982 when the company was
known as Lee Telecommunications and continued two years after its
acquisition by Whittaker.
   Lamberth was a stockholder of the company and became head of the
subsidiary following its acquisition by Whittaker. Court papers
said Lamberth hid the scheme from Whittaker officials.
   The bribes allegedly were funneled to Sherman through defense
consultants John Marlowe, Thomas Muldoon and Donald Illeman.
   Marlowe is cooperating with the FBI's continuing investigation
of Pentagon procurement fraud dubbed ``Operation Ill Wind.''
Muldoon and Illeman have not been charged.
   Sherman, who pleaded guilty to taking bribes from Marlowe as
part of an FBI undercover sting, signed authorizations that greatly
enhanced the value of two contracts the company obtained to help
the Marines develop a battlefield air traffic control system, court
papers said.
   Sherman signed papers increasing the value of one contract from
$600,000 to $2.5 million, according to the papers, and also
authorized the enhancement of another contract's value from
$540,000 to $3.6 million.
   He also authorized the transfer to Lee Telecommunications of
another contract worth $1.6 million when the company that first
obtained the deal had difficulty developing software, the court
papers said.
   Lamberth faced a possible 20-year sentence and fines up to
$500,000 for his guilty pleas to conspiracy and bribery.
   Van Tassel could be sentenced to up to 15 years and fined
$250,000 for his bribery plea.
   Hilton scheduled a Dec. 15 sentencing proceeding for both
defendants, who have agreed to cooperate with the investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
