<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-ColumbiaPictures 1stLd-Writethru   09-26 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Columbia Pictures, 1st Ld-Writethru,0700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports: Sony Offers $3 Billion for Columbia Pictures</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 new grafs to UPDATE with today's announcement that
board met and recessed until Wednesday. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, Coca-Cola
... DELETES 8th graf pvs, In active ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Columbia Pictures Entertainment Inc. says it is
in buyout talks and published reports indicate Japan's Sony Corp.
has offered about $3 billion for the film and television production
company.
   In a statement today, Columbia said its board met Monday night
to review its discussions about a possible sale of the company and
adjourned the meeting until Wednesday, when it expects ``further
action will be taken.''
   In active trading early today on the New York Stock Exchange,
Columbia was down 25 cents a share at $26.12{. It had risen $5.25 a
share on Monday.
   Columbia Pictures declined comment today on the reports that it
had received a buyout offer from Sony, which previously had
indicated an interest in buying a movie studio. A Sony spokesman
failed to return a telephone call immediately today, but the
company declined coment on Monday.
   Coca-Cola Co., the Atlanta-based soft drink maker that owns 49
percent of Columbia's stock, said Monday it was aware Columbia was
in talks and would consider whatever recommendation may be made,
but declined further comment.
   Columbia triggered a sharp runup in its stock price Monday when
it announced that it was ``in discussions with a third party
involving the acquisition for cash of all of Columbia's outstanding
shares.''
   The Dow Jones News Service, citing unnamed entertainment
industry sources, said Sony had offered to buy Columbia for $26 to
$28 a share. With 112.7 million shares outstanding, that would
value Columbia at $2.93 billion to $3.15 billion. It also has about
$1.3 billion in long-term debt outstanding.
   The New York Times reported in its Tuesday editions that Sony
made an offer of $3.4 billion cash, attributing it to an
unidentified source. The Times said Columbia's board was expected
to accept the bid, possibly as soon as Wednesday.
   Foreign companies have shown a ravenous appetite for U.S.-made
films and TV programming in recent months as cable and satellite
channels have opened up in European and Asian markets.
   Less than two weeks ago, for instance, MGM-UA Communications Co.
accepted a $1.5 billion buyout bid from the Qintex Group of
Australia. Rupert Murdoch's News Corp., also based in Australia,
had offered $1.4 billion for MGM-UA.
   MGM-UA said it had active buyout discussions with Sony in late
1988.
   Analysts say Sony, which bought CBS Records for $2 billion in
January 1988, is eager to own entertainment ``software'' such as
movies and TV shows as a complement to the hardware such as VCRs
and television sets it has been making for years.
   ``There are only a limited supply of companies like this,''
analyst Jeffrey Logsdon said of Columbia. He follows the
entertainment business for the investment firm Crowell Weedon &amp; Co.
in Los Angeles.
   Columbia Pictures operates two movie studios, Columbia Pictures
and Tri-Star Pictures, and has a library of more than 2,700 film
titles and more than 260 TV series.
   Recent movie releases from Columbia have included ``Ghostbusters
II,'' ``The Karate Kid Part III,'' and ``When Harry Met Sally ...
'' while Tri-Star has come out with ``See No Evil, Hear No Evil''
and ``Lock Up.''
   Columbia is one of the leading suppliers of TV programming
through its Columbia Pictures Television and Merv Griffin
Enterprises units.
   Columbia produces or distributes 11 TV series that are being
aired in prime time, including ``Who's The Boss,'' ``Designing
Women'' and ``Married ... with Children.''
   Columbia also owns Merv Griffin Enterprises, whose shows include
``Wheel of Fortune'' and ``Jeopardy,'' the two highest-rated
syndicated shows on U.S. television.
   In addition, the company owns Loews Theatre Management Corp.,
one of the leading motion picture chains with 820 screens in 220
locations as of the close of its fiscal year, which ended Feb. 28.
   Columbia Pictures earned $16 million, or 14 cents a share, on
revenue of $1.62 billion in the fiscal year.
</TEXT>
