<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1254EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Minivans Adv01   09-26 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Minivans, Adv 01,0721</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv01</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday Oct. 1 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nose Jobs: Profile of U.S. Minivans Changing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Minivans-Who's Who</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The face of General Motors Corp.'s minivans has
undergone plastic surgery and Chrysler Corp. may not like GM's nose
job.
   Ever since small passenger vans caught the fancy of American
buyers, Chrysler has commanded a dominant share of the market. GM
is hoping its long-hooded minivans will compel Chrysler owners to
switch makes.
   While the auto market as a whole likely will shrink during the
next year, there are predictions of continued growth in minivans, a
segment which has seen rapid expansion since 1983, when Chrysler
introduced the Dodge Caravan and the Plymouth Voyager.
   The minivan market actually is older than that. Volkswagen
imported a compact van starting in 1950 and Ford Motor Co. in the
early 1960s sold a Falcon Club Wagon, a half-foot shorter than its
current Aerostar minivan.
   Since the minivan's popularity was ignited seven years ago,
Chrysler has commanded more than 50 percent of the segment of the
light-truck market, which includes minivans.
   Chrysler's share is beginning to slip as the Ford Aerostar and
the Mazda MPV grow in popularity. The unknown in the minivan
formula is how much of the market GM will get. Chrysler executives
have conceded they will lose some of their share, perhaps a
percentage point or two.
   ``But we expected that,'' said Robert Lutz, president of
Chrysler Motors Corp., the company's vehicle-making arm. While
Chrysler has slapped big incentives on many of its vehicles, the
Voyager and Caravan have been exempt.
   The patients in GM's plastic surgery are the Chevrolet Lumina
APV, Pontiac Trans Sport and Oldsmobile Silhouette, rakishly styled
minivans made at GM's North Tarrytown, N.Y., assembly plant. Over
the past few months, the company has given plant employees loaner
vans to drive around the New York countryside to let folks get an
eyeful of the futuristic-looking vehicles.
   The GM minivan was originally for the corporation's Pontiac and
Chevrolet divisions, and Oldsmobile was added later, said a source
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Capacity of the North Tarrytown plant is about 200,000 minivans
a year and the mix among the three divisions can be changed
relatively easily. Like other minivan makers, GM officials expect
buyers to come from those looking at sedans and station wagons and,
to a smaller extent, minivan owners ready to trade in their
vehicles.
   GM is banking on some of those current minivan buyers being
intrigued by the shape of the GM versions. The plastic-bodied
vehicles sport a snout that would have made Cyrano de Bergerac
jealous.
   Analyst Charles Brady of Oppenheimer &amp; Co. of New York said he
thinks the new GM minivans are quite attractive.
   The front-wheel-drive vehicles join the conventionally styled
Chevrolet Astro, which is being offered in four-wheel drive for
1990, in the assault on Chrysler's hold on the minivan market. All
Chrysler's minivans are front-wheel drive.
   ``It's the biggest threat that Chrysler minivans have received
to date,'' Brady said. ``There really hasn't been anything that
would serve as a direct substitute; the others have either been
smaller or rear-wheel drive.''
   The minivan battle isn't just between GM and Chrysler.
   Ford continues to offer its Aerostar, and Japanese companies are
hoping to grab larger pieces of the minivan pie.
   Chrysler isn't sitting still, either. It is offering a Town &amp;
Country version of the minivan, more expensive than the Caravan or
Voyager but loaded with extras, including leather seats and a
compass.
   ``We'll sell out two (minivan) plants,'' Lutz said, speaking of
the St. Louis, Mo., and Windsor, Ontario, factories.
   Lutz estimated the introduction of the GM minivans will add
about 200,000 of the vehicles to the road next year, cutting
slightly into Chrysler's share.
   Those new purchasers, he added, will come primarily from
potential station-wagon buyers. Chrysler is offering no station
wagons for 1990.
   Sales of minivans last year amounted to 725,081 units, a 21.1
percent increase over the year before. The vehicle's share of the
light-truck market has climbed to 13.8 percent last year from 7.4
percent in 1985.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 1</NOTE>
