<FIRST>u f PM-Britain-BAT 1stLd-Writethru f0029 09-26 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-BAT, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0029,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>BAT Announces Major Restructuring</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 2nd graf pvs with Goldsmith reaction;
SUBS 7th graf pvs, `The Hoylake... to conform; PICKS UP 8th graf pvs, `Hoylake
has...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BAT Industries PLC, which is fending off a hostile
$22 billion bid from Hoylake Investments Ltd., on Tuesday announced
a major restructuring that includes the sale of its U.S. retail
operations.
   BAT said it would reshape itself to concentrate on tobacco and
fast-growing financial services.
   Sir James Goldsmith, the Anglo-French financier heading
Hoylake's bid, said he welcomed BAT's plan as a ``first step'' to
the ``unbundling'' plan he has proposed.
   He said he would pursue his takeover attempt and said the
bidding group for BAT would vote in favor of the restructuring.
   The British conglomerate said it would sell its retailing
interests in the United States, which include Saks Fifth Avenue and
Marshall Field's stores, as well as other smaller businesses.
   It said it would create two new publicly held companies by
giving its existing shareholders shares in its British retailing
company Argos, as well as shares in a combination of its paper
companies Wiggins Teape, and Appleton.
   BAT also plans to buy back 10 percent of its shares and to
``significantly increase'' its dividend for 1989.
   These measures require shareholder approval, and BAT has called
a special shareholders meeting for Oct. 19.
   The Hoylake bidding group has offered $14.14 worth of securities
for each BAT share. Hoylake has suspended the offer while U.S.
state insurance commissions review its proposed change of ownership
of BAT's Farmers Insurance Group Inc.
   Hoylake has vowed to ``unbundle'' BAT by selling off all its
non-tobacco interests.
   Hoylake and other critics of BAT have complained that BAT's
share price doesn't reflect the true value of its underlying
businesses and is constrained by the relatively slow growth of its
tobacco businesses.
   Now BAT is seeking to fight off the Hoylake bid by addressing
this problem.
   The Hoylake offer, however, has attracted little interest from
BAT's shareholders and analysts have said that the bidders will
have to increase their offer and include some cash in order to
succeed.
   ``We can now accelerate the strategy of concentrating on
financial services and tobacco,'' BAT Chairman Patrick Sheehy said
in a statement.
   ``The board now believes that the five decisive steps will
continue the long-term development of the group and address our
concern about the value of BAT shares on the stock market compared
to the underlying value of the businesses.''
   BAT said it envisions that tobacco will provide steady earnings
growth and strong cash flow which will complement the more rapid
growth expected in financial services during the 1990s. These two
businesses will represent ``an exceptionally powerful combination''
to enhance shareholder value in the years ahead, it said.
   BAT said tobacco and financial services now contribute about
$1.5 billion and $13.36 billion, respectively, to its earnings.
   BAT forecast pre-tax profit of $3.2 billion this year, a 22
percent increase over 1988. Earnings per share also were forecast
to rise by 22 percent to $1.23.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
