<FIRST>r f AM-AnimalTesting     09-26 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Animal Testing,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cosmetics Industry Says Animal Testing Still Necessary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cosmetics industry must have the option of
testing its products on animals while trying to develop alternative
methods to ensure those products are safe for consumers, an
industry spokesman said Tuesday.
   Edward Kavanaugh, president of the Cosmetic, Toiletry and
Fragrance Association, said the industry regards ``the safety of
(its) consumers as their primary responsibility and highest
priority.''
   Responding to efforts to ban the use of animals in such product
testing, Kavanaugh said the industry is trying to develop
alternatives.
   However, ``makers of personal care products must continue to
have the option of using animal research data,'' he said.
   Animal rights activists who gathered outside the industry news
conference argued that alternatives already have been found and are
being used.
   ``Major corporations ... have switched to in vitro or non-animal
methods, including cell-culture techniques, testing on membranes,
computer modeling,'' Susan Rich of People for the Ethical Treatment
of Animals told reporters.
   The nation's largest cosmetics company, Avon, has invested
millions of dollars to develop such non-animal testing
alternatives, company spokesman John Cox said in a telephone
interview.
   However, Cox said Avons backs the industry association position
on testing because ``there is no one test or even a series of tests
that could be developed for everybody's products.''
   ``Until everybody has developed alternatives, we feel they ought
to have the option of testing,'' he said.
   Eight states _ California, Pennsylvania, Illinois, New Jersey,
Maryland, Massachusetts, Connecticut and Hawaii _ are considering
legislation to ban animal testing for cosmetics, household and
pharmaceutical products.
</TEXT>
