<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1424EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Poland-MBAs Bjt   09-26 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-MBAs, Bjt,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lessons In Capitalism for New Breed Of East Bloc Managers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With much of the communist world planning
economic retooling, lessons in capitalism await at the first
business administration schools designed to turn a new breed of
East bloc managers into competitive, market-oriented executives.
   A fundamentally different business environment is developing as
economically weak Poland and increasingly troubled Hungary cut
restraints on domestic entrepreneurs, demand that state-run
enterprises be profitable and open their borders to foreign
investors.
   A handful of executive training programs are being organized to
meld Western management techniques with the realities of Eastern
European business.
   ``Intellectually, these are not new concepts,'' says Andrzej
Kosminski, a Warsaw University professor creating the International
Business School to open Oct. 23 near the capital.
   ``But let's say that in our system of management, there was no
use up to now for that kind of approach ... because of a system
that was obviously in basic contradiction to sound business
practices.''
   Kosminski's school will offer the first East bloc equivalent of
a Master's of Business Administration. In addition, Western
companies are opening business skills schools in Poland and Hungary.
   During more than four decades of centralized planning for
captive consumers in communist-ruled nations, business decisions
were made by remote bureaucratic ministries. There was litle need
to worry about developing hot-selling products, finding market
niches, advertising and packaging.
   Motivating workers, pleasing customers, direct foreign trade and
cost saving largely are new concepts for the would-be East bloc
entrepreneur.
   ``Our business people are used to thinking in socialist
conditions: `I produce because I must cover the social need.' This
is nonsense,'' said Bogda Zukowska, a journalist for Poland's
Economic Life newspaper.
   ``Now they are starting to think, `I must produce because I
would like to sell and earn money, and I must do my best to cope
with the market, what the market needs and the cost of
production,''' she said.
   Hopes for resurrecting Poland's economy hinge largely on foreign
investment and domestic private enterprise. But Poles must learn
how the West does business when there is competition for customers
who have a range of choices, and foreign investors must learn how
business works in what Kosminski calls Poland's ``negotiable''
economy.
   At the International Business School, 48 Polish business people,
some private entrepreneurs and others sent by their state-owned
enterprises, have signed up for the first semester at a cost of
about $250.
   The school also will offer orientation programs for Western
managers interested in doing business in the East bloc and offer
consulting services from students who are doing case studies.
   In Budapest, the Hungarian Management Institute was established
in November 1988 through a joint venture with Italian
organizations. A 10-month ``junior executive'' program is offered
along with lecture series for managers.
   A Canadian-Polish partnership is starting the International
School of Management this fall, offering programs for executives
and courses on ``English for business'' and ``How to start your own
business.''
   Polish regulations on starting private businesses were loosened
this year under a privatization of enterprises considered crucial
for turning the economy toward capitalism, filling empty stores and
reviving commercial links with the West.
   Before these new businesses _ and those being salvaged from the
socialist sector _ can enter the competitive market abroad or
prosper at home, the entrepreneurs will need new techniques,
Kosminski said.
   The classes at his school are ``designed to train the elite of
Polish managers as efficient, market oriented and globally
oriented, socially responsible, competent and reliable business
partners,'' according to a prospectus.
   Polish professors and visiting lecturers will offer courses in
Polish and English _ materials on such subjects as international
marketing and finance are virtually unavailable in Polish _ to be
held one week a month through four semesters over two years so
participants can continue to work.
   Students will learn accounting, business law and quality
control, as well as business protocol, how to organize receptions
and what to say in press releases.
   ``They will combine a knowledge of international business and
international standards of doing business with local specificity,''
Kosminski said.
   Polish managers also will be needed to help Western executives
investing in the country maneuver through logistical and
bureaucratic obstacles.
   ``Our business environment is still exotic,'' Kosminski said,
with multiple currency markets, supplies from typing paper to
office chairs virtually unavailable and an endless string of
``arrangements'' needed to handle the ``negotiable'' bureaucracy.
   ``It is difficult for foreign businesses,'' he said. ``That's
why they need intermediaries, people who know both cultures, and I
think some of our graduates might be able to play that role.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
