<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-26 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Higher, Soybean Tumbles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices moved higher, while soybeans
prices tumbled and corn futures were mostly lower at the close
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   A forecast of ideal harvest weather was depressing corn and
soybeans at the start of the day, analysts said, then professional
fund buying pushed prices higher. But the rally didn't hold and
prices declined toward the end of the session.
   Jon Horton, an analyst for Research Department Inc., said a lack
of any real export demand for soybeans was weighing on futures
prices.
   Wheat prices, however, were supported by Monday's announcement
from the U.S. Agriculture Department of a sale to China of 300,000
metric tons of the commodity and anticipation of more export
business this week, traders said.
   Activity in the corn pit was light as traders await a USDA grain
report later this week, said Susan Leighty of Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   At the close, wheat was 2\ cents to 3} cents higher, with
December at $3.93} a bushel; corn was 1\ cent lower to 1 cent
higher, with December at $2.29} a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 1{
cents higher, with December at $1.43\ a bushel; and soybeans were 1
cent to 5\ cents lower, with November at $56.67\ a bushel.
