<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1520EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-BAT Bjt   09-26 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-BAT, Bjt,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>BAT Reshapes Itself In Attempt to Defeat Hoylake Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BAT Industries PLC on Tuesday proposed the sale of
its U.S. retailing businesses as part of a restructuring the
conglomerate hoped would defeat Hoylake Investments Ltd.'s $22
billion hostile takeover bid.
   The planned restructuring was intended to enhance the value of
BAT's stock, company chairman Patrick Sheehy said in a statement.
   Sir James Goldsmith, the Anglo-French financier who leads
Hoylake, said he welcomed BAT's proposal as a first step toward his
plans for breaking up the conglomerate. Goldsmith said he would not
give up his takeover attempt, which has been suspended while the
group tries to overcome regulatory obstacles.
   Securities analysts said BAT's proposals would enhance the value
of the British conglomerate's stock and was likely to be approved
by its shareholders. But they said Hoylake could still bid for what
is left of BAT.
   Hoylake has offered 13.4 billion pounds, or $22 billion, in
securities for BAT.
   BAT said it would reshape itself to concentrate on its tobacco
business, which is steady and generates cash, and its fast-growing
financial services segment. This would be a significant departure
from its previous strategy of gradually diversifying away from
tobacco.
   The retained businesses are expected to account for 80 percent
of BAT's forecast 1989 pre-tax profit of $3.2 billion, BAT said.
   The British conglomerate said it would sell its U.S. retailing
business, which includes 46 Saks Fifth Avenue stores and 24
Marshall Field's stores. The two retailers have combined annual
sales of $2 billion.
   These and other planned, smaller divestitures could fetch a
total of $2.4 billion, analysts said.
   BAT said it also would create two new publicly held companies by
giving its existing shareholders a stake in its British retailing
company Argos, as well as stock in a combination of its paper
companies, Wiggins Teape and Appleton. Appleton is based in
Wisconsin.
   BAT said it also would buy back 10 percent of its shares _ which
would cost 1.24 billion pounds, or $2 billion, at Tuesday's closing
price on London's Stock Exchange.
   The company also pledged to significantly increase its
dividends. The total dividend for 1989 could go as high as 30
pence, or 48 cents, per share, a 49 percent increase over the
previous year's payment, BAT said.
   BAT called a special shareholders meeting for Oct. 19 to vote on
the proposed restructuring.
   BAT stock rose 2 pence, or 3 cents, a share to close at 818
pence, or $13.17.
   Hoylake has suspended its $14.14 a share offer while state
insurance commissioners in the United States review its proposed
change of ownership of BAT's Farmers Insurance Group Inc.
   Hoylake has vowed to break up BAT by selling off all its
non-tobacco interests. The group and other critics of BAT have
complained the conglomerate's stock price does not reflect the true
value of its underlying businesses because it is constrained by the
relatively slow growth of its tobacco business.
   Sheehy, in an interview on British radio, said the plan would
give existing shareholders the benefit of splitting up BAT, rather
than allowing Hoylake to take a profit from dismantling the
conglomerate.
   Goldsmith said Hoylake would vote in favor of BAT's plan
although the investor group was not abandoning its bid.
   ``The point is that they've made a first step'' in the direction
of realizing a higher share value for BAT shareholders, which is
the basis of the Hoylake argument, Goldsmith said in a telephone
interview.
   The Hoylake offer has attracted little interest from BAT's
shareholders and analysts have said that the bidding group would
have to increase its bid and include some cash to succeed.
   Andrew Mitchell, an analyst with the London investment firm
Smith New Court PLC, said: ``It does seem likely that they
(shareholders) would approve these (BAT) proposals because it gives
them a bird in the hand.''
   It could take Hoylake nine months to get regulatory clearance in
the United States, he said.
   ``It's a useful start,'' said Nigel Utley, an analyst with Laing
and Cruickshank. ``It will enhance shareholder value, but not
necessarily enough to defeat a serious bid.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
