<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     09-26 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude Oil Prices Fluctuate, Close Higher as OPEC Talks Continue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures fluctuated throughout the day
Tuesday before closing slightly higher as traders awaited the
outcome of negotiations on OPEC's production limits.
   ``It opened down on OPEC concerns and then it went up on OPEC
concerns and bounced around during the day on different rumors,''
Jim Fiedler, an analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures
Inc., said of the crude oil market.
   The November contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of crude oil, finally closed 7 cents higher at $19.53 a
42-gallon barrel in New York Mercantile Exchange trading.
   In Geneva, ministers of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries were trying to raise the cartel's production ceiling from
its current 19.5 million barrel limit to a level between 20 million
barrels a day and 21 million barrels for the rest of 1989 without
sending prices skidding.
   The ministers twice postponed what was expected to be a final
round of talks to consider a new Iranian proposal. Negotiations
were to resume Wednesday after private bargaining sessions.
   Iranian Oil Minister Gholamreza Aqazadeh said his country had
offered a plan to raise the production ceiling in the last quarter
of the year. Iran suggested hiking the cap to between 20.5 million
barrels a day and 21 million barrels.
   The cartel has been overproducing, pumping more crude than
allowed under an output agreement signed in June. Analysts'
estimate OPEC production at about 22 million barrels daily.
   Among refined products traded on the mercantile exchange
Tuesday, heating oil for October delivery picked up 0.20 cent to
settle at 57.71 cents a gallon. Unleaded gasoline for October
delivery fell 1.29 cents to 60.38 cents a gallon amid reports of
plentiful supplies.
</TEXT>
