<FIRST>r f BC-ToysRUs-Japan     09-26 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Toys R Us-Japan,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toy Chain To Enter Japan, With Help From McDonald's</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The giant toy store chain Toys R Us Inc. on
Tuesday announced it will open for business in Japan under an
agreement with an arm of fast food powerhouse McDonald's Corp.
   A new company called Toys R Us-Japan is to be 80 percent owned
by the toy company. McDonald's Co. (Japan) Ltd., owned equally by
McDonald's of Oak Brook, Ill., and Japan's Fujita &amp; Co. Ltd., will
control the remaining 20 percent of the new toy company.
   The arrangement will give McDonald's an opportunity to operate
restaurants on toy store sites that will be developed. The first
stores are planned to open in 1991.
   Paramus, N.J.-based Toys R Us embarked on an overseas expansion
in 1984. By the end of this year the company says its international
division will have 74 stores, including 27 in Canada, 23 in the
United Kingdom, 13 in West Germany, five in France, two each in
Singapore and Malaysia and one each in Hong Kong and Taiwan.
   The company, which had sales topping $4 billion last year, bills
itself as the world's biggest specialty toy retailer. At the end of
1989, it will have 404 toy stores in the United States alone and
137 Kids R Us children's clothing stores.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
