<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 1732EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-AutoProductionCuts Bjt   09-26 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Production Cuts, Bjt,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>Production Cuts, Dipping Sales May Mean Rocky Labor Relations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Auto production and sales are dropping, and that
could mean layoffs around the time the United Auto Workers union
begins gearing up for 1990 contract talks with the Big Three
automakers, analysts said Tuesday.
   The 1990 model year technically begins Oct. 1, although some new
models have been on sale for months. Nevertheless, some of General
Motors Corp.'s buyer incentives on its new cars and trucks took
effect before the vehicles officially went on sale.
   That suggests the industry is grappling with a host of potential
problems in moving its product. Much of the recent focus has been
on GM.
   ``Some of us believe that GM will close some plants permanently
in the next few months,'' said analyst John Kirnan of Kidder,
Peabody &amp; Co. in New York. He said the disparity between GM's
production capacity and its market share would indicate four plants
could be closed.
   Last week, GM announced it was idling its Lakewood plant in
Atlanta in March, joining recently closed plants in Framingham,
Mass.; Kansas City, Mo.; and Pontiac, Mich.
   GM has scheduled some temporary production cuts next month at a
half-dozen car and truck plants, lasting a week or two apiece,
because of swollen vehicle inventories.
   Ford Motor Co. has said it temporarily would halt production at
a car and truck plant in early October. Chrysler Corp. hasn't
announced any temporary plant closings for October.
   Analyst Joseph Phillippi of Shearson Lehman Hutton in New York
estimated that fourth quarter production this year would be 10
percent to 15 percent below last year's levels.
   Production cuts may be hastened by auto dealers, who have said
they won't be ordering as many 1990 vehicles as they did during the
1989 model year. There have been estimates that dealer orders may
fall by as much as 30 percent below last year's levels.
   Analysts also said recent sales activity, including a 12.7
percent jump in mid-September car and truck purchases reported
Monday, supports a theory that current sales are being ``borrowed''
from the fourth quarter, as consumers rush to beat 1990 model year
price increases.
   ``I suspect sales are going to be rather soft in the fourth
quarter,'' Phillippi said.
   Softer sales point to lower production, increased layoffs and a
higher potential for labor problems in the last three months of the
year, as the UAW prepares for Big Three contract talks.
   One UAW source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Tuesday
that union officials weren't alarmed but were monitoring production
levels and possible layoffs.
   UAW contracts with each of the Big Three automakers expire Sept.
14, 1990. Preparations for the negotiations, which open next
summer, begin in earnest during the first three months of next year.
   By then, the UAW will be looking back on any temporary layoffs
and ahead to the closing of the Lakewood plant, which will idle
about 2,200 workers.
   ``I think labor relations are going to be very murky in the next
few months,'' Kirnan said.
   In addition to potential layoffs, one question is the kind of
style UAW Vice President Stephen Yokich, the new head of the
union's GM Department, will bring to the bargaining table.
   This June, Yokich succeeded Donald Ephlin, who retired. Under
Ephlin's leadership, GM and the union developed cooperative
programs that injected worker participation in some management
decisions, but also created the UAW's largest internal political
fight in the past 40 years.
   Dissidents under the ``New Directions'' banner have criticized
UAW leadership for eroding workers' rights through joint programs.
   But New Directions leader Jerry Tucker said he liked Yokich's
sharp criticism of GM's planned Lakewood closing. Yokich said the
move undermines efforts to develop a new relationship between the
company and the union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
