<FIRST>u f AM-C&amp;S-Sovran 1stLd-Writethru f0242 09-26 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-C&amp;S-Sovran, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0242,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Citizens &amp; Southern, Sovran Merging To Form 14th-Largest Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT number of states; UPDATES throughout
with quotes, details, minor editing; No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Citizens and Southern Corp. and Sovran
Financial Corp. announced a $4.7 billion merger Tuesday that will
create the nation's 14th-largest bank.
   C&amp;S, based in Atlanta, and Sovran, based in Norfolk, Va., will
have total assets of $47 billion and almost 1,000 offices in seven
states from Maryland to Florida and the District of Columbia.
   Under a newly formed holding company called Avantor Financial
Corp., the two banks will maintain dual headquarters and retain
current management.
   The merger comes five months after C&amp;S fought off a takeover bid
by North Carolina's NCNB Corp. Unlike that proposal, the C&amp;S-Sovran
deal is a friendly merger.
   In a joint statement, Sovran Chairman Albert B. Gornto Jr. and
C&amp;S Chairman Bennett A. Brown said the deal combines the advantages
of size and market strength with success in community-based banking.
   ``We are creating a large, nationally competitive franchise with
a powerful presence in major high-growth markets, and we're
underwriting it with superior credit quality,'' they said in a
statement.
   ``This is a company that will be completely focused on service,
efficiency and profitability,'' the statement said.
   The boards of the two companies have approved the agreement.
Final approval from shareholders and federal and state regulators
is expected in the first quarter of 1990.
   Both companies will remain in existence as subsidiaries of the
new umbrella organization. A new board of directors will be
established with 15 members from Sovran and 14 from C&amp;S.
   ``It's a big deal,'' said Lacy Shockley, a banking industry
analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham Co. in New York. ``It's
going to create the powerhouse in the Southeast.''
   C&amp;S has 489 bank offices in Georgia, Florida and South Carolina.
Sovran has 487 offices in Virginia, Maryland, Washington, D.C.,
Tennessee and Kentucky.
   Scott Scredon, a C&amp;S spokesman in Atlanta, said the merger has
been discussed on and off for about two years.
   ``We feel it's a perfect fit,'' Scredon said. ``We don't overlap
... and we each double our market presence. We both feel it
couldn't be any better.''
   Scredon said customers should not see any immediate changes when
the merger is completed, but once the two institutions pool
resources new services probably will be offered.
   Under the merger agreement, each of Sovran's 59.8 million shares
of outstanding common stock will convert into 1.23 shares of the
new company's common stock. Each of C&amp;S's 62 million shares of
outstanding common stock will convert into 1.0 shares of the new
company's common stock.
   Brown will become chairman and chief executive officer of the
new company while retaining his position at C&amp;S. Gornto will become
chairman of the new company's executive committee and will retain
his position at the Virginia bank.
   Dennis C. Bottorff, Sovran's president and chief operating
officer, will be president and chief operating officer of Avantor
and would become chief executive of the new company upon Brown's
retirement. At that time, Hugh Chapman, now president of C&amp;S, would
become Avantor chairman.
   Last spring, Charlotte, N.C.-based NCNB targeted C&amp;S in a $2.4
billion takeover bid. C&amp;S officials refused to discuss the
proposal, and NCNB eventually withdrew the offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
