<HEAD>Harvest Weather Forecast Depresses Some Grain Futures</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs `Wheat settled ... to CORRECT soybean price;
PICKS UP 8th graf pvs, `At the ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Wriuter</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A forecast of ideal harvest weather sent some grain futures
prices lower Tuesday, but the selloff helped to bolster cattle
prices.
   Wheat futures prices moved higher, while soybeans prices tumbled
and corn futures were mostly lower on the Chicago Board of Trade.
Analysts said the outlook for perfect harvest weather in U.S.
growing areas depressed corn and soybeans.
   On other markets, feeder cattle prices rose, live hogs gained,
precious metals fell and energy prices were mixed.
   Jon Horton, an analyst for Research Department Inc. in Chicago,
said a lack of any real export demand for soybeans was weighing on
futures prices.
   Wheat prices, however, were supported by Monday's announcement
from the U.S. Agriculture Department of a sale to China of 300,000
metric tons and anticipation of more export business this week,
traders said.
   Activity in the corn pit was light as traders awaited a USDA
grain report on Thursday, said analyst Susan Leighty of
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc in New York.
   Wheat settled 2\ cents to 4\ cents higher, with December at
$3.94\ a bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to } cent higher, with
December at $2.29} a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to 2 cents higher,
with December at $1.43{ a bushel; and soybeans were 1 cent to 6\
cents lower, with November at $5.66\ cents a bushel.
   At the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, futures prices for live
cattle soared, while feeder cattle prices were higher and pork
complex futures were mixed.
   Live cattle futures rallied on higher cash prices in Texas and
Kansas, analysts said.
   ``Traders wanted something to be bullish about, and when they
got bullish news, they took prices higher,'' said Dale Benson, a
Chicago analyst for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Feeder cattle prices were supported by live cattle prices and a
selloff in grains. Live hogs also were supported by higher cash
prices.
   Live cattle settled .38 cent to 1 cent higher, with the contract
for October at 72.07 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to
.72 cent higher, with September at 83.25 cents a pound; live hogs
were .28 cent lower to .27 cent higher with October at 43.42 cents
a pound; and pork bellies were .10 cent lower to .30 cent higher
with February at 48.50 cents a pound.
   Futures prices for precious metals fell on the Commodity
Exchange in New York.
   Gold set a new high of $375.30 for the December contract,
recovering $15 since it hit a low on Sept 15 of $360.60. But later
in the session prices slipped when pressure on the U.S. dollar
subsided Tuesday, said Don Tierney, a precious metals analyst in
New York for Stanley Bell &amp; Co.
   Gold settled $1.30 to $1.60 lower, with the contract for
September at $368.50 a troy ounce; and silver was 2 cents lower,
with September at $5.263 a troy ounce.
   Energy prices were mixed on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   Crude oil prices had a choppy session, losing some ground after
OPEC ministers postponed their meeting in Geneza, Switzerland. The
ministers were studying an Iranian proposal to increase the
production ceiling to between 20.5 million barrels a day and 21
million barrels.
   Unleaded gasoline followed crude lower, but heating oil prices
were higher mainly from traders selling the gasoline and using
those profits to buy heating oil, said Ray Mazzeo, an energy
specialist in New York with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Crude oil was .02 cent lower to .10 cent higher, with the
contract for November at $19.53 a barrel; heating oil was .07 cent
to .20 cent higher, with October at 57.71 cents a gallon; and
unleaded gasoline was 1.29 cents lower to .08 cent higher, with
October at 60.38 cents a gallon.
  
</TEXT>
