<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 2012EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TVSports     09-26 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-TV Sports,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Independent Stations Blast Trend to Cable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent television stations Tuesday took a
swing at baseball owners for increasingly limiting television
viewing of the ``American Pastime'' to homes with cable TV.
   Recent agreements giving cable companies rights to New York
Yankees games and a four-year, $400 million contract that gives the
ESPN cable network rights to Wednesday and Sunday night baseball
games typify the flight of sports to cable TV, said Preston Padden,
president of the Assocation of Independent Television Stations.
   Padden, in a letter Tuesday to Francis T. Vincent, the new
commisioner of Major League Baseball, said that given ``the clear
trends in the cable industry ... it seems likely that legislation
will be necessary to preserve sports on free TV.''
   But before that happens, ``we ask you to consider mutually
voluntary changes'' in the ESPN contract, Padden said.
``Specifically, we are concerned about those provisions that
restrict our right to broadcast baseball games on Wednesday and
Sunday evenings.''
   Padden disputed Major League Baseball's assertion that the ESPN
contract would expand TV viewers' choices.
   ``Fans will experience a diminution in the supply of baseball,''
Padden said. ``More to the point, you will be restricting access to
Major League Baseball only to those who have access to cable,
and-or can afford cable rates which average over $25 a month. For
the `American Pastime,' we find this contrary to the public
interest.''
   Calls to the Major League Baseball office in New York for
comment were not immediately returned.
   Padden's letter grew out of a meeting this month in Washington
of TV station executives from 24 of the 26 cities that have Major
League Baseball. The executives agreed to try to get MLB to alter
the ESPN contract.
   The TV executives also were concerned about cable TV contracts
for sports at Big 10, Pacific 10 and Southeastern Conference
schools. They said such contracts point to a day when all sports
will be on pay TV.
   The station executives have enlisted the aid of Sens. Arlen
Specter, R-Pa., and Albert Gore, D-Tenn., to press their case in
Congress.
   The National Cable Television Association has said that local
broadcasters are showing 40 percent more professional baseball
games now when compared with 1975 and that cable is not siphoning
away free TV sports.
</TEXT>
