<FIRST>r f AM-MidwayContract     09-26 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Midway Contract,0155</SECOND>
<HEAD>Midway Flight Attendants Ratify First Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 17 months of negotiations, flight
attendants at Midway Airlines have ratified their first contract,
union officials said Tuesday.
   The 3-year agreement calls for a base salary of $11,700 a year,
said spokeswoman Darlene Brom. In addition, attendants also could
be paid $1,800 to $5,400 a year in expenses, depending on the
amount of time they are away from home, she said.
   The 650 Midway attendants voted to join the Association of
Flight Attendants, AFL-CIO, in November 1987. Talks on the first
contract began in March 1988 and a federal mediator was called in a
year ago.
   Tentative agreement was reached Aug. 25.
   Midway, a mid-sized carrier based in Chicago, is paying $210
million to buy 16 DC-9 aircraft, as well as gates and other airport
facilities in Philadelphia, Washington and New York from
strikebound Eastern Airlines.
