<FIRST>u f AM-ColumbiaPictures 2ndLd-Writethru f0253 09-26 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Columbia Pictures, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0253,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Columbia Board to Reconvene Wednesday on Rumored Sony Buyout Bid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 18th graf pvs, `Its recent ...,' to UPDATE
with report that producer would be named Columbia's president. Picks up
19th graf, `Columbia has ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Columbia Pictures Entertainment Inc. said
Tuesday its board will reconvene Wednesday and may act on a buyout
offer from an unidentified suitor, widely believed to be Japan's
Sony Corp.
   Trading in Columbia stock was active for the second consecutive
session on the reports that Sony had offered about $3 billion for
the film and television producer. The rumored deal also boosted the
prices of stocks of other entertainment companies.
   The deal would be another in a wave of consolidation that has
swept through the entertainment business in recent years as
companies have sought to position themselves to compete in
increasingly accessible global media markets.
   Columbia, Sony and Coca-Cola Co., which owns 49 percent of
Columbia's stock, each declined comment on the published reports
that Sony was offering between $26 and $28 a share for all of
Columbia's common stock. Columbia had about 111 million common
shares outstanding as of May 31.
   Columbia was the most active issue on the New York Stock
Exchange, dropping 12{ cents a share to $26.25 on volume of nearly
4.2 million shares.
   Columbia had jumped $5.25 a share Monday when it disclosed it
was ``in discussions with a third party involving their acquisition
for cash of all of Columbia's outstanding shares.''
   On Tuesday, Columbia said its board had met Monday night to
review those discussions and then adjourned until Wednesday when
``it is anticipated that further action will be taken.''
   Columbia and Sony reportedly have been in talks for months, and
Sony is known to be eager to expand its holdings in the
entertainment field as a complement to its longstanding electronic
hardware business.
   Sony has indicated its interest in buying a movie studio and
Columbia, with a huge library of both films and TV programs could
provide a lucrative new source of revenue for a company that has
specialized in producing the videocassette recorders and other
hardware on which to display those shows.
   Elsewhere in the entertainment group, Paramount Communications
Inc. rose $1.50 a share to $56.25; MCA Inc. climbed $2 a share to
$65.62{ and Orion Pictures Corp. rose 62{ cents a share to $22.75.
   The rumored Sony-Columbia deal ``highlights the scarcity value''
to the remaining independent production companies such as Paramount
and MCA, said Harold Vogel, the entertainment industry analyst for
Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.
   Mara Balsbaugh, an analyst for Smith Barney Harris Upham &amp; Co.,
said upcoming technology developments by companies like Sony are
likely to expand global demand for programming to the benefit of
companies that have large film and TV libraries. Columbia has a
library of more than 2,700 films and 23,000 TV episodes.
   ``Over time, there is a case for continued consolidation in the
industry. The list of buyers is a lot longer than the list of
sellers,'' she said.
   These and other analysts said it was possible but unlikely that
a third party would emerge with a bid that could scuttle a deal
between Sony and Columbia.
   One potential competitor has taken himself out of the running. A
spokesman for Rupert Murdoch, whose News Corp. made an unsuccessful
$1.4 billion bid recently for MGM-UA Entertainment Co., said
Tuesday that Murdoch was not interested in getting into the bidding
for Columbia.
   MGM-UA accepted a $1.5 billion buyout offer from the Qintex
Group of Australia earlier this month. Time Inc. is on the verge of
completing its acquisition of Warner Communications Inc., which
owns the Warner Bros. movie studio and the TV production company
Lorimar. News Corp. bought 20th Century Fox three years ago.
   Columbia's Columbia Pictures and Tri-Star Pictures studios have
captured 14 percent of the domestic box office revenue this year,
trailing Warner, Disney and Paramount. But industry watchers term
its performance disappointing.
   Its recent films have included ``Ghostbusters II,'' ``The Karate
Kid Part III,'' ``Casualties of War'' and ``Lock Up.''
   The New York Times reported in Wednesday editions that movie
producer Peter Guber was expected to replace Victor A. Kaufman as
president and chief executive of Columbia if the Sony buyout is
approved. Guber, who co-produced ``Batman,'' ``Rainman,'' and
``Flashdance,'' is considered one of Hollywood's top producers.
   Columbia has been more successful in TV programming and produces
or distributes 11 series that are being shown in prime time,
including five new series. They include ``Who's the Boss'' and
``Designing Women.''
   It also operates about 820 movie screens in 220 locations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
