<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 2333EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1st-LdWritethru f0283 09-26 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st-Ld Writethru, f0283,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Retreats, Share Prices Firmer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with morning Nikkei, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar retreated further against the
Japanese yen during morning trading Wednesday, pressured by central
bank dollar-selling, dealers said.
   Share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange were firmer as they
reached a new high.
   The dollar was changing hands at 141.35 yen at late morning,
down 1.45 yen from Tuesday's close of 142.80 yen. After opening at
141.60 yen, the currency ranged from 141.00 to 141.62 yen.
   Currency dealers said the coordinated intervention, conducted by
central banks from Japan, the United States and Canada, followed on
the heels of a wave of central bank action in overseas market
Tuesday, meant to check the dollar's upward trend.
   The amount of intervention was not immediately known, but it
followed similar concerted action by the three central banks Monday.
   The Bank of Japan, the nation's central bank, does not comment
on its monetary activities.
   ``The concerted intervention represented a firm commitment by
the monetary authorities to contain the dollar's upward move,''
following the weekend meeting of the Group of Seven nations, said a
dealer with a major commercial bank in Tokyo, who spoke anonymously.
   At the end of the Washington meeting, finance ministers and
central bankers from the United States, Japan, Canada, Britain,
West Germany, France and Italy said in a statement that the
dollar's strength was inconsistent with economic fundamentals.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues gained 93.63 points, or 0.26 percent, closing the morning
session at 35,538.45, a new high. The Nikkei index posted a
484.11-point gain the previous day for a record closing 35,444.82.
   Securities dealers said the market mood remained positive after
Tuesday's advances, but institutional investors were still
cautiously watching the direction of the foreign exchange rates.
   ``The market was further encouraged by the yen's appreciation
against the dollar,'' said a dealer of a major Japanese securities
brokerage who spoke anonymously.
</TEXT>
