<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0148EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryBills     09-26 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interest Rates Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in Monday's auction to the highest level in three
weeks.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.4 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 7.72 percent, up from 7.64 percent
last week. Another $7.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an
average discount rate of 7.79 percent, up from 7.64 percent last
week.
   The rates were the highest since Sept. 5 when three-month bills
sold for 7.88 percent and six-month bills averaged 7.87 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 7.98 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,804.90 and 8.22 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,606.20.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 8.18
percent last week, up from 8.07 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
