<FIRST>r f PM-SeamanRefinancing     09-26 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Seaman Refinancing,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seaman Furniture Announces Tentative Refinancing Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seaman Furniture Co. says it had agreed in
principle with its banks on a partial repayment plan that would
include a fresh $42 million investment by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp;
Co., KKR's investors and members of the Seaman family.
   Seaman went private two years ago in a $360 million buyout
arranged by KKR but ran into trouble making debt payments because
of a downturn in its major market, Long Island.
   The troubles of the 31-store furniture chain came as an
embarrassment to KKR by raising questions about how thoroughly it
had investigated Seaman's prospects before backing the buyout.
   The proposal announced Monday would keep Seaman afloat by
slashing and stretching out its debt to banks and giving paper
instead of cash in payments to junk bond holders until 1996.
Creditors would also get an unspecified amount of Seaman's stock.
   The deal requires approval by the holders of 90 percent of its
junk bonds. The banks have already agreed to it in principle,
Seaman said.
   News of the accord boosted the price of Seaman's junk bonds,
which had lost more than 90 percent of their face value. Its junk
bond issue was trading Monday at $110 bid and $140 asked per $1,000
face value, up from about $70 bid before the announcement,
according to Alan Schlesinger, head of junk bond trading at
Donaldson Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities Corp.
   ``The company's in wonderful shape now, especially with the
insertion of the cash,'' Morton Seaman, the chief executive, said
in an interview.
   Seaman said the company has opened five stores in the last 12
months while closing one. A news release said the refinancing will
let it ``continue to aggressively explore new sites in 1990 and
take advantage of the opportunities we see developing.''
   In exchange for $265 million in existing bank debt, banks would
receive $150 million in senior debt, $25 million in subordinated
pay-in-kind notes and a ``substantial amount of equity,'' Morton
Seaman said.
   The pay-in-kind notes would pay interest in the form of more
notes rather than cash until 1996. They would pay interest in cash
from then until they mature in 1999.
   Banks agreed to receive payments of interest but not principal
on $125 million of their debt from now through Nov. 15, 1992. There
would be no payments even of interest on the remaining $25 million
until that date.
   The investors who put in the extra $42 million would receive
senior subordinated notes. The share that each of the investors
would put in was not specified.
   Owners of Seaman's roughly $83 million in outstanding junk bonds
would get $20.8 million face value of new pay-in-kind notes and 8
percent of the stock in Seaman in exchange for 90 percent of those
junk bonds. The terms of those pay-in-kind notes were not specified.
</TEXT>
