<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0152EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-NewIssues     09-26 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New Issues,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record $187.1 Billion in Bonds Issued in First Three Quarters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A record $187.1 billion in debt securities was
issued to the public in the first three quarters of this year as
interest rates dropped, according to a survey.
   Securities Data Co., in a preliminary survey released Monday for
the first nine months, noted that, on the other hand, the volume of
common stock brought to market fell sharply. The survey covers Jan.
1 through Sept. 20.
   The volume of Treasury bonds and other debt securities issued
jumped to $187.1 billion during the first three quarters, up from
$181.4 billion in the same period last year and surpassing the
previous nine-month record of $184.2 billion in the first three
quarters of 1987.
   The sales were stimulated by falling interest rates, Securities
Data noted. When interest rates decline, bond prices rise.
   The rate on the Treasury's key 30-year bond, for example, has
fallen from 9.08 percent on Jan. 3, the first trading day of the
year, to 8.23 percent in early trading Monday. The yield on the
closely watched bond dropped on Aug. 2 to 7.84 percent, its lowest
level since April 1987.
   While the total volume of bonds issued expanded, ``junk'' bonds
fared poorly during the period, the consulting firm said. It blamed
the recent shakeout in the junk bond market for the smallest number
of the high-risk, high-yield bonds being issued since 1984.
   Ninety-five junk bond offerings were made during the first nine
months, down from 115 in the same period last year. The total
volume of junk bonds offered was nearly stable, at $19.28 billion
compared with $19.36 billion in 1988. But around $4 billion of this
year's volume was accounted for by the $24.53 billion leveraged
buyout of RJR Nabisco Inc., noted Francine Wissak, an assistant
vice president of Securities Data.
   New issues of common stock also turned in a lackluster
performance, according to the survey. Although the Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials soared during the period, surpassing the
2,700 level, common stock issued raised only $13.5 billion, down
from $23.8 billion in the first nine months of 1988.
   Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. Inc. continued to be the leading manager of
new bond and stock issues with 17 percent of the market, according
to the survey.
</TEXT>
