<FILEID>AP-NR-09-26-89 0204EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AirlineBuyouts     09-26 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airline Buyouts,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transportation Department Queries United On Buyout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is asking United Airlines to
disclose how much foreign influence over the airline a planned
employee-management takeover would allow, officials said.
   The inquiry came as The Wall Street Journal reported that
Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner had asked Northwest
Airlines' new principle owner, Alfred Checchi, to cut by $225
million the $400 million investment made in NWA Inc., the airline's
parent corporation, by KLM Royal Dutch Airlines.
   The Transportation Department on Monday gave Steven M. Wolf,
chairman of United parent UAL Corp., until Oct. 10 to furnish
information on investors and financial arrangements in the $6.5
billion stock buyout plan of UAL by the airline's pilots,
management and British Airways PLC. Wolf is to continue as head of
the company under the plan, which would give controlling interest
to United employees.
   Jeffrey N. Shane, assistant transportation secretary for policy
and international affairs, asked Wolf to provide detailed financial
information, including the names of any foreign investors and the
amount of influence they might have over the new company.
   The department is conducting a financial fitness review of the
United deal to determine whether it will extend the airline's
operating certificate under the new ownership. A similar review of
the Northwest takeover was completed last week but the results were
not announced to the public.
   ``We are concerned about any aquisition,'' Shane said in the
letter to United, ``especially a leverage buyout of either the
carrier or its parent that could have a substantial adverse impact
on a carrier's financial structure, might otherwise affect its
ability to operate safely or meet its financial obligations, or
would result in its not being controlled by U.S. citizens.''
   On the Northwest takeover, department spokesman Hal Paris said
he could not confirm the Journal report or give any details of the
department's decision on the buyout.
   KLM made its investment in NWA to help Checchi finance the $3.65
billion purchase. KLM provided 57 percent of the $700 million in
equity Checchi raised to buy Northwest but owns only 5 percent of
the airline.
   Foreign companies cannot own more than 25 percent of a U.S.
airline, but Skinner said last week he was concerned that foreign
investors might have more influence than their ownership reflects
and could compromise U.S. negotiations with other governments over
air routes.
   The Journal also reported that rumors about possible changes in
KLM's Northwest investment sparked a sell-off of stock in United
Airlines' parent corporation.
   British Airways plans to invest $750 million in UAL.
   The department, in its letter to United, asked for a
``citizenship affidavit'' for UAL as it will exist after the
takeover.
   ``Detail any actual or potential ability on the part of these
non-citizen entities to influence or control, directly or
indirectly, the affairs of United,'' Shane instructed in the letter.
   He also asked for any written or oral agreements that might
assure that non-citizen lenders cannot control UAL.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
